WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.920
[Amit Varma]: If you're an Indian of a certain age, you might have heard the question, where were

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:10.440
[Amit Varma]: you when India won the 1983 World Cup?

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:13.600
[Amit Varma]: If you're somewhat younger, the question could be, where were you when Dravid and Lakshman

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:14.600
[Amit Varma]: had that partnership?

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Or when Abhinav Bindra won gold at the Olympics?

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:20.680
[Amit Varma]: Or Vishy Anand became world champion or Dhoni hit that six?

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Someday they will surely ask, where were you when Neeraj Chopra threw that javelin?

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.720
[Amit Varma]: Why is sport such a big deal for so many of us?

00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:31.680
[Amit Varma]: But moments that don't even feature us, that we had nothing to do with personally, become

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:33.680
[Amit Varma]: such a big part of our lives.

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:35.560
[Amit Varma]: Part of the answer isn't pleasant.

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:40.480
[Amit Varma]: Sport can be used to whip up ugly nationalistic sentiment, akin to war minus a shooting, in

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:42.320
[Amit Varma]: George Orwell's famous words.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:43.480
[Amit Varma]: It's a zero-sum game.

00:00:43.480 --> 00:00:45.560
[Amit Varma]: Someone has to lose for someone else to win.

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:50.400
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, some sports like boxing are like ugly artifacts from a more brutal age.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:53.100
[Amit Varma]: But having said this, sport can also elevate us.

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:55.360
[Amit Varma]: It can reveal the best of human character.

00:00:55.360 --> 00:01:00.400
[Amit Varma]: And watching another human being transcend their limitations can inspire us to dream.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, one thing I love about the Olympics is the range of human stories that we are

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:05.600
[Amit Varma]: exposed to.

00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:09.720
[Amit Varma]: So many different people beating the odds and rising above their circumstances.

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes those circumstances can be so harsh that just being there is a crazy achievement.

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:20.080
[Amit Varma]: Even though I'm middle-aged now and should be jaded and cynical, I can't fail to be both

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:23.880
[Amit Varma]: inspired and humbled by what these sports people achieve.

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's especially so if they're from India.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.560
[Amit Varma]: The obstacles for a sportsperson here are insane, almost insurmountable.

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:35.360
[Amit Varma]: Over the decades, Indian sport outside of cricket has been held back by poverty, bad

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:39.320
[Amit Varma]: governance, poor infrastructure, and an inferiority complex.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:42.920
[Amit Varma]: Time and again, we have told ourselves, this is beyond us.

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:44.540
[Amit Varma]: We are not a sporting nation.

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:46.080
[Amit Varma]: We can't dream these dreams.

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:47.080
[Amit Varma]: We can't do this.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Well, the times have changed.

00:01:48.600 --> 00:01:49.740
[Amit Varma]: We can do this.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.320
[Amit Varma]: We are doing this.

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:54.200
[Amit Varma]: Indian sport has turned a corner.

00:01:54.200 --> 00:02:01.840
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:02:01.840 --> 00:02:02.840
[Unknown]: science.

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:08.920
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Badman.

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:15.120
[Amit Varma]: My last episode was about the 1991 reforms and how they changed the way we look at ourselves.

00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:20.880
[Amit Varma]: In the decades since, India opened itself up to the world and gained a new self-confidence.

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:24.000
[Amit Varma]: More and more people became participants in our progress.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.920
[Amit Varma]: And what happened to Indian society and India's economy was mirrored in sport.

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, sadly, in both social and economic terms, we seem to have slipped backwards.

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:34.960
[Amit Varma]: Things don't look good.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:38.080
[Amit Varma]: But as far as sport is concerned, we are marching on.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:42.560
[Amit Varma]: As the euphoria of the Tokyo Olympics settles down, why don't we take stock of Indian sport?

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:45.840
[Amit Varma]: My guests today are Joy Bhattacharya and Nandan Kamath.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:47.320
[Amit Varma]: Joy has been on the show before.

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:52.080
[Amit Varma]: In a fabulous episode, I'll link from the show notes called Building Sports Ecosystems.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:56.400
[Amit Varma]: He spent the first hour of that episode talking about his experience of building the Kolkata

00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Knight Riders.

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:00.960
[Amit Varma]: But it was the second hour that I found both moving and inspiring.

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:05.360
[Amit Varma]: In that, he gave us a close-up look of his journey bringing the Under-17 Football World

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:10.560
[Amit Varma]: Cup to India and trying to build a football ecosystem across the country.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:15.240
[Amit Varma]: He then moved on to volleyball and formed a volleyball league that faced many obstacles

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:17.160
[Amit Varma]: but is due to return soon.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And as you will learn from this episode, he also taught the Indian contingent at Tokyo

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:23.480
[Amit Varma]: to do the Namaste.

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:26.080
[Amit Varma]: My second guest today is also a remarkable figure.

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:30.600
[Amit Varma]: Nandan Kamath loved sports so much as a kid that he would go to bed with a cricket bat

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:31.920
[Amit Varma]: cradled in his arms.

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:36.240
[Amit Varma]: He played cricket for India at the Under-16 level and captained the Karnataka team.

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:41.080
[Amit Varma]: He then chose law as a profession, became a lawyer, went to Oxford as a Rhodes Scholar,

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:45.680
[Amit Varma]: went to Harvard Law School, worked in a top law firm there for three years, and then gave

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:50.080
[Amit Varma]: it up and came back to India because in his heart, he was still that little boy sleeping

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:51.400
[Amit Varma]: with a cricket bat.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:57.120
[Amit Varma]: In 2008, he started the GoSports Foundation, whose aim was to help Indian sportspeople

00:03:57.120 --> 00:03:59.800
[Amit Varma]: who would otherwise fall through the cracks.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:05.600
[Amit Varma]: Over the years, Nandan and his team have helped countless Indian sportspeople in so many unseen

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:06.600
[Amit Varma]: ways.

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:08.880
[Amit Varma]: His insights on Indian sport are second to none.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:13.360
[Amit Varma]: The show notes to this episode contain links to articles by him as well as to a fantastic

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:16.000
[Amit Varma]: book on Indian sport, co-edited by him.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Do check those out.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:21.520
[Amit Varma]: And now, before we get to the conversation with Nandan and Joy, let's take a quick commercial

00:04:21.520 --> 00:04:24.520
[Amit Varma]: break.

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:27.280
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer.

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:32.400
[Amit Varma]: In fact, chances are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut,

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:37.240
[Amit Varma]: which was active between 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:42.280
[Amit Varma]: I love the freedom the form gave me, and I feel I was shaped by it in many ways.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:47.200
[Amit Varma]: I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced to think about many different things

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:49.440
[Amit Varma]: because I wrote about many different things.

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:54.440
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons, and now it is time to revive it.

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:57.240
[Amit Varma]: Only now, I'm doing it through a newsletter.

00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:03.400
[Amit Varma]: I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com, where I will write

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:05.880
[Amit Varma]: regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:10.500
[Amit Varma]: I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else.

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:15.120
[Amit Varma]: So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe.

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:16.120
[Amit Varma]: It is free.

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:20.600
[Amit Varma]: Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox.

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:22.400
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to go anywhere.

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:24.440
[Amit Varma]: So subscribe now for free.

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:28.760
[Amit Varma]: The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:29.760
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:32.960
[Amit Varma]: Joy and Nandan, welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:37.520
[Guest 2]: Hi, terrific to be here, absolutely terrific to be back and to be one of the people who's

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:41.040
[Guest 2]: been called back is a signal honor for me.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:42.040
[Guest 1]: Thank you so much, Amit.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:43.040
[Guest 1]: I'm a debutant here.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:47.200
[Guest 1]: And it's a little bit weird, because I've heard you for maybe two or 300 hours.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.160
[Guest 1]: And now I have a chance to speak.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.000
[Guest 1]: I think I'm, it's the heard and the unheard.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.200
[Guest 1]: So I'm the unheard of the show.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:57.360
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I mean, it's entirely my honor.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:00.840
[Amit Varma]: And I since you've heard so much of the show, I should apologize to you for speaking at

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:04.680
[Amit Varma]: normal speed, because I think most people who listen, listen at higher speeds, and they

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:07.920
[Amit Varma]: find it really weird when they're, you know, they meet me in person, like why are you talking

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:08.920
[Amit Varma]: so slowly?

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:13.400
[Amit Varma]: The reason I say it's an honor for me is because, you know, people like me, we sit around pontificating

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:16.280
[Amit Varma]: about things, having conversations, having discussions.

00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:19.640
[Amit Varma]: And one reason I admire Joy, and one reason I was keen to have you on the show, as soon

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:23.880
[Amit Varma]: as I read up on all the things that you've done, is that you guys are actually out there

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:27.640
[Amit Varma]: making a difference in the real world, not just sitting back and complaining, kya sport

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:31.320
[Amit Varma]: mein yeh haal hai, and look at that federation and this and that, but you're actually out

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:36.000
[Amit Varma]: there kind of making a difference, which is why Joy, before you joined the call, I congratulated

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:37.320
[Amit Varma]: Nandan on the Tokyo result.

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:41.480
[Amit Varma]: And he would, of course, very modestly say that maine kuch nahi kiya, yeh sab athletes

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:42.480
[Amit Varma]: hai.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:46.280
[Amit Varma]: But you know, you guys are also heroes of people who love Indian sport in a way, but

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:47.280
[Amit Varma]: I won't embarrass you further.

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:51.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, before we get down to talking about the state of Indian sport, and so on, I'd

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:54.080
[Amit Varma]: love to know a little bit about your personal journeys.

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:57.440
[Amit Varma]: Joy, of course, in the fantastic episode we did earlier, which I linked from the show

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:01.280
[Amit Varma]: notes to the listeners, you already took us through a bit of it, but I'll ask you more.

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:02.800
[Amit Varma]: So let's start with you, Nandan.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:09.400
[Amit Varma]: It's not that you are a lawyer who's gotten into supporting sports and all of that right

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:10.400
[Amit Varma]: now.

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:11.400
[Amit Varma]: You've been a sports person yourself.

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.000
[Amit Varma]: You've represented India, I believe, right?

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.120
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about your sporting journey and where it begins.

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:21.120
[Amit Varma]: And I read somewhere that you speaking very sort of passionately about how you love sport

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:24.880
[Amit Varma]: so much, that when you were a kid at night, you would sleep with a cricket bat in your

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:28.080
[Amit Varma]: bed, which is, tell me a bit about those years.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:35.800
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so like you put it, Amit, I wasn't a lawyer who went to sport, but a sports person

00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:37.760
[Guest 1]: who ended up in the law.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:40.640
[Guest 1]: And that is the story really sleeping with a cricket bat, right?

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:42.240
[Guest 1]: I think that says it all.

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:45.600
[Guest 1]: In my bedroom, I had this huge poster of Kapil Dev.

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:47.720
[Guest 1]: My sister had a huge poster of Madonna.

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:51.300
[Guest 1]: And that perhaps speaks enough of the both of us.

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:55.040
[Guest 1]: But really, as a kid, just absolutely in love with sport.

00:07:55.040 --> 00:08:01.640
[Guest 1]: I had whole World Cups played by myself against the wall, old Wimbledon's, just so obsessed

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:07.000
[Guest 1]: with the sporting journey and the sporting quest, had lots of heroes, early memories

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:14.640
[Guest 1]: are watching the Olympics, Greg Louganis, Bo Villander, Ben Johnson may not be the greatest

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:20.960
[Guest 1]: ambassador, but all of those are just so imprinted in my mind, but also people like Stefan Edberg.

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:27.280
[Guest 1]: It was really sport was this window out into the world for me, new accents, understanding

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:33.360
[Guest 1]: people seeing, I mean, hearing Australian commentators on the cricket.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:37.720
[Guest 1]: And the earliest memory of all I do have is the 1983 World Cup.

00:08:37.720 --> 00:08:40.520
[Guest 1]: And it's a little bit sort of overdone.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:46.080
[Guest 1]: But I just remember obsessively going through, they had this official guide to the Prudential

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:47.840
[Guest 1]: World Cup 1983.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:53.000
[Guest 1]: I must have read that book, like literally 200 times or 300 times, I knew every scorecard.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:58.320
[Guest 1]: And you Dave Houghton and Tricos, and I mean, literally every player that played for every

00:08:58.320 --> 00:08:59.520
[Guest 1]: one of those teams.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:07.720
[Guest 1]: And it was that obsession, which really never left, in some sense, it translated into playing

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:09.080
[Guest 1]: sport at the school level.

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:13.760
[Guest 1]: So I do share something with Abhinav Bindra and Neeraj Chopra.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:19.400
[Guest 1]: My mom put me into sport because I was a little bit unfit, a little bit pudgy, and wanted

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:20.980
[Guest 1]: me to stay out of trouble.

00:09:20.980 --> 00:09:22.320
[Guest 1]: But that's where the comparison ends.

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:26.800
[Guest 1]: So she put me into school, took me to the PT instructor and said, let him play hockey.

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:30.880
[Guest 1]: So hockey was my first sport, loved it, fantastic team sport.

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:35.000
[Guest 1]: But as I went along, cricket became the one that I was a little bit better at.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:40.920
[Guest 1]: I had good hand-eye coordination, something I played in the streets, but was able to translate

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:42.600
[Guest 1]: into competitive cricket.

00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:47.440
[Guest 1]: I took that pursuit quite seriously, ended up captaining the Karnataka State cricket

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:49.720
[Guest 1]: team at the under-16 level.

00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:52.240
[Guest 1]: When I was 15, I got into the under-21 team.

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest 1]: So I mean, there was that potential, but that potential ended pretty abruptly when I went

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.760
[Guest 1]: to the National Law School entrance exam and I got in.

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:06.560
[Guest 1]: And it became that point of making a decision, are you going to try and pursue this cricket?

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:08.240
[Guest 1]: Or are you going to become a lawyer?

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:13.200
[Guest 1]: And that was something very directly confronted with at my National Law School interview,

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:17.440
[Guest 1]: where Dr. Madhav Menon, the founder of the law school, sits you down for an interview.

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:20.360
[Guest 1]: And he just said, young man, are you going to be a cricketer?

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:22.400
[Guest 1]: Are you going to be a lawyer?

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:24.720
[Guest 1]: And I hadn't really thought of it in that sense.

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:30.400
[Guest 1]: Is it this such a significant binary choice that a 17-year-old person needs to make?

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.360
[Guest 1]: I mean, that's a life choice.

00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:34.160
[Guest 1]: And I was very fortunate.

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:38.720
[Guest 1]: I had very, very open-minded parents, my father was a chartered accountant.

00:10:38.720 --> 00:10:40.680
[Guest 1]: My mother was a political cartoonist.

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:45.840
[Guest 1]: Still, I think India's only political cartoonist, passed away about 20 years ago.

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:47.680
[Guest 1]: But so I had a very open household.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:52.200
[Guest 1]: We had lots of cousins and uncles in the IITs and very academic.

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:53.560
[Guest 1]: But they said, you make the choice.

00:10:53.560 --> 00:10:55.400
[Guest 1]: You want to continue playing cricket?

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:56.400
[Guest 1]: Go for it.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:57.400
[Guest 1]: You want to be a lawyer?

00:10:57.400 --> 00:10:58.400
[Guest 1]: Go for it.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:10:59.840
[Guest 1]: And I chose that latter choice.

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:03.320
[Guest 1]: And at that point, it didn't seem like a very difficult choice to make.

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:07.080
[Guest 1]: There were maybe six, seven people making good careers out of cricket.

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:10.800
[Guest 1]: There were probably thousands of lawyers making reasonable careers.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:14.000
[Guest 1]: So I chose what you would call the conservative choice.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:20.760
[Guest 1]: And looking back, I feel like that defined me, defined not just the pursuit of doing

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:25.080
[Guest 1]: well at the law, I'd given up something I really cared about, and I was possibly good

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:26.080
[Guest 1]: at.

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:28.760
[Guest 1]: And that drove me really hard to do well at my academics.

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:31.520
[Guest 1]: You know, you give up something you loved.

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:33.880
[Guest 1]: Make the other thing count now.

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:38.640
[Guest 1]: But also when I look back on that moment, you know, it may be romanticizing the moment,

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:42.220
[Guest 1]: but it also might be looking back and finding explanations.

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:48.320
[Guest 1]: But that choice for a young person to make, it really stuck with me and still does.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:54.020
[Guest 1]: That someone needs to make that choice between pursuing an education and pursuing sport.

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:58.300
[Guest 1]: And in many ways, that has defined my journey and the things I've chosen to do, the things

00:11:58.300 --> 00:11:59.960
[Guest 1]: I care about.

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:06.840
[Guest 1]: Just really snapshot early years, you I mean, people talk about non vegetarians, I'm willing

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:13.000
[Guest 1]: to to eat anything that moves for me, anything that was sport, I loved and I was willing

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.320
[Guest 1]: to sort of jump in, get involved, participate.

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:18.880
[Guest 1]: It was just just a love affair with sport.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:19.880
[Guest 1]: I can't explain it.

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:20.880
[Guest 1]: It was me.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:22.920
[Guest 1]: And it still is in some sense.

00:12:22.920 --> 00:12:26.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's very resonant.

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:30.600
[Amit Varma]: And of course, it sort of dates you in a certain generation of people 1983 World Cup, the potential

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:31.600
[Amit Varma]: handbook.

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:35.840
[Amit Varma]: I remember, you know, when I was growing up, I had this thick wisdom book of scorecards,

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:40.160
[Amit Varma]: which was published in 1979, and basically had the scorecard of every test match played

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:41.160
[Amit Varma]: until then.

00:12:41.160 --> 00:12:44.360
[Amit Varma]: And I knew all of them by heart pretty much and that there weren't that many test matches

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:46.640
[Amit Varma]: played until then, of course, at that point.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:50.440
[Amit Varma]: So you know, one would go through all those scorecards and make up narratives in your

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:54.520
[Amit Varma]: head about what happened along with all the other supplementary reading you're doing.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And there was such a paucity of that information.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.520
[Amit Varma]: And so on as well, you know, you had one channel, Doordarshan, you didn't really get to see

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:01.800
[Amit Varma]: much sports in it.

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:04.440
[Amit Varma]: You didn't get too much exposure in that sense.

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:06.160
[Amit Varma]: And your choice is particularly heartbreaking.

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:10.280
[Amit Varma]: Because at one level, these are choices that everybody makes that at some point you, you

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:12.960
[Amit Varma]: know, there is the road taken, and there is a road not taken.

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And at that point in time, we might think it's a trivial choice.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:17.080
[Amit Varma]: It's not such a big deal.

00:13:17.080 --> 00:13:21.760
[Amit Varma]: But essentially, you know, one life you could have lived, it's just over at that point,

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:23.160
[Amit Varma]: and another one begins.

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:27.440
[Amit Varma]: But it's especially heartbreaking in the sporting context, because the fact that even if you're

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:32.720
[Amit Varma]: an incredibly talented cricketer, the rational choice would still have been go for law because

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:37.000
[Amit Varma]: like you said, survivor bias, just a handful of people at the top make money, the rest

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
[Amit Varma]: of the people don't really make anything.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.040
[Amit Varma]: Joy, tell me a little bit about your journey, because to the best of my knowledge, you haven't

00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:47.060
[Amit Varma]: really played for India or captain the state team so far.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:51.360
[Amit Varma]: But you've been deeply involved with sports, you know, right from 96, if I remember correctly,

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:52.600
[Amit Varma]: from our last conversation.

00:13:52.600 --> 00:13:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you were a lover of sport before that as well.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.320
[Amit Varma]: So sort of take me through that.

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:01.720
[Amit Varma]: And also, I wonder if you have any insights, like I've been sort of thinking and memory

00:14:01.720 --> 00:14:06.600
[Amit Varma]: is a really strange thing, because you don't always remember what happened, you remember

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:09.500
[Amit Varma]: what you remember, and it changes over time, right?

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:13.920
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes I try and sit back and think about what it was to be an Indian sporting

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:18.800
[Amit Varma]: fan at the time, that is there a sense of inferiority complex, for example, is there

00:14:18.800 --> 00:14:23.320
[Amit Varma]: an assumption that we can never be world class, except perhaps in cricket, which like four

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:25.800
[Amit Varma]: and a half countries play seriously or whatever.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:27.720
[Amit Varma]: So what are those sort of stages like?

00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:28.720
[Amit Varma]: And what is that point?

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:33.800
[Amit Varma]: Like, in a sense, you got into you perhaps love sport all your life, but you get into

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:38.760
[Amit Varma]: active involvement with sport at a time when satellite television comes, India opens up,

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:42.040
[Amit Varma]: you can watch sports channels, you can watch every sport across the world.

00:14:42.040 --> 00:14:45.880
[Amit Varma]: How does that mindset begin to change over a period of time?

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:52.800
[Guest 2]: Well, lots of us, look, to start off, I played sport in college, I played basketball, seriously

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:57.840
[Guest 2]: played for the university, my university was fairly, no, no, it's okay, I was fairly decent

00:14:57.840 --> 00:14:58.840
[Guest 2]: at it.

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:02.900
[Guest 2]: But I mean, fairly decent at a university in Bengal, which is not exactly the hotbed

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:05.840
[Guest 2]: of basketball is, is absolutely fine.

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:11.040
[Guest 2]: But what I did get a great sense of is because I've done inter-university tournaments, what

00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:15.160
[Guest 2]: I did have a great sense of was, especially for sport, which is not cricket.

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:18.240
[Guest 2]: And of course, in those days, at the college level, I don't think it makes that much of

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:19.520
[Guest 2]: a difference.

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:23.440
[Guest 2]: The way sportsmen are treated, I mean, you go for a tournament, you literally sleep on

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:27.120
[Guest 2]: floors, you have, you go to the fields to bathroom, because the bathrooms are so dirty,

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:28.300
[Guest 2]: you can't go anywhere there.

00:15:28.300 --> 00:15:32.440
[Guest 2]: So I've seen all of that, you know, and the two other things that I have seen, perhaps

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:36.360
[Guest 2]: being a bit older than you blokes is, you know, when Sunil Gavaskar was batting and

00:15:36.360 --> 00:15:40.480
[Guest 2]: you're listening to commentary, you know, whether it's 76 or 79.

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:45.480
[Guest 2]: So all Indian fans are, you know, today, they listen for wins.

00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:49.040
[Guest 2]: They listen that, okay, you know, we're going to win this match, we're going to do this.

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:50.480
[Guest 2]: Gavaskar is not batting for wins.

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:51.480
[Guest 2]: He was batting for our self-respect.

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:56.080
[Guest 2]: You know, there's Gavaskar, there's Vishwanath, and there are a couple of players in between,

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:57.280
[Guest 2]: and there's nothing else.

00:15:57.280 --> 00:16:01.880
[Guest 2]: So every time he goes out there and faces these desperately dangerous fast bowlers,

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:06.800
[Guest 2]: whether it's Bob Willis or Dennis Tilly or Jeff Thompson or Michael Holding, he's batting

00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:07.800
[Guest 2]: for our self-respect.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:11.000
[Guest 2]: You can go out and show your face there because, you know, Gavaskar is there.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:16.160
[Guest 2]: So literally, you get onto the bus to go to, you know, school or wherever, and you're waiting

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:19.400
[Guest 2]: because when you're going to get off and go and ask that, you know, is he still around?

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:23.500
[Guest 2]: Or if you're coming back from school, is Gavaskar still batting?

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:30.560
[Guest 2]: So I was part of that one era where literally a self-respecting draw was so important to

00:16:30.560 --> 00:16:31.560
[Guest 2]: us.

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:32.880
[Guest 2]: Victories were very few and far between.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.040
[Guest 2]: You know, everyone talks about 76 board of Spain.

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:37.920
[Guest 2]: But you know, how many times did we do that?

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:38.920
[Guest 2]: Or 81 Melbourne.

00:16:38.920 --> 00:16:41.360
[Guest 2]: They are very few and far between.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:45.960
[Guest 2]: By and large, you're just saying, guys, just allow us to leave this match with our head

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:46.960
[Guest 2]: held high.

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:50.040
[Guest 2]: Or even if it's a defeat, let it not be a crushing defeat.

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:54.200
[Guest 2]: So I've seen a lot of that phase of Indian cricket, which perhaps you guys have seen.

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:56.600
[Guest 2]: Post-83, you've seen far more success.

00:16:56.600 --> 00:17:01.800
[Guest 2]: And really, our test sides were also better coupled there, you know, 86-87 England, 91-92,

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:03.840
[Guest 2]: we are actually competing in Australia as well.

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:10.280
[Guest 2]: So those are very different sides from the sides that I saw between the mid-70s and mid-80s.

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:15.640
[Guest 2]: And the other thing that I did see is the actual, you know, one sport rising and the

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:18.720
[Guest 2]: other in decline, which is cricket and hockey.

00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:24.200
[Guest 2]: So in every middle-class household in the big 60s, I don't know about the rest, everyone

00:17:24.200 --> 00:17:25.880
[Guest 2]: had a hockey stick as well.

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:27.680
[Guest 2]: You would have a hockey stick at home.

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:28.880
[Guest 2]: You'd go down and play hockey.

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:33.360
[Guest 2]: And in fact, most of the balls with which we played cricket most of the time were cocket

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:34.920
[Guest 2]: balls where a lot of hockey was played.

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:38.440
[Guest 2]: If you didn't play serious cricket, if you played at home, you played a lot with the

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:39.840
[Guest 2]: cocket ball.

00:17:39.840 --> 00:17:44.520
[Guest 2]: And those are the kind of things that are actually, I remember actually, if you see

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:49.280
[Guest 2]: a Hrishikesh Mukherjee film like Golmal, he's crazy about cricket, he's crazy about hockey.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:53.280
[Guest 2]: And then this slowly starts diverging at some point in time.

00:17:53.280 --> 00:17:55.240
[Guest 2]: And I think that's the two journeys I saw.

00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:59.240
[Guest 2]: I've seen Indian cricket's journey to self-respect and winning.

00:17:59.240 --> 00:18:04.080
[Guest 2]: And I've seen Indian cricket rise and Indian hockey fall.

00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:07.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, like you brought up the interesting point of self-respect, which is, again, resonant,

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:08.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, Gavaskar's playing.

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And today we look back and we say that, oh, you know, personal records mattered and Gavaskar

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.840
[Amit Varma]: would play for himself and all of that.

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:18.400
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, most of the time the team would lose, especially when they went abroad.

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:21.180
[Amit Varma]: So he's just putting up the front that he can.

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:23.400
[Amit Varma]: But my question about self-respect is this.

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:28.160
[Amit Varma]: This ties into a larger question that if we kind of look at how the world has progressed

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:32.720
[Amit Varma]: in the last 20, 30 years, not just India, but the world is that there is a fragmentation

00:18:32.720 --> 00:18:33.720
[Amit Varma]: of everything.

00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:38.200
[Amit Varma]: For example, you look at the media in the 80s and 90s, you have these trusted mainstream

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:39.200
[Amit Varma]: sources.

00:18:39.200 --> 00:18:42.800
[Amit Varma]: There is a consensus on truth and then it gets democratized and everything gets completely

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:44.520
[Amit Varma]: fragmented and it's both good and bad.

00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:47.920
[Amit Varma]: It's good because now everyone has a means of production.

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And some of the negative knock-on effects are that it becomes a war of narratives.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:53.760
[Amit Varma]: There's no consensus on truth anymore.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:59.080
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, what I see happening in entertainment and perhaps sport, which I would kind of say

00:18:59.080 --> 00:19:04.440
[Amit Varma]: is a twin of entertainment in a certain sense, is that, you know, there are more options.

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:07.900
[Amit Varma]: Like if you were in the 70s, you would be watching hockey and cricket and maybe the

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:11.400
[Amit Varma]: balance shifted at some point, but essentially that was it.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:15.400
[Amit Varma]: Today, there's a lot else, you know, even something like chess is very popular on YouTube

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:19.320
[Amit Varma]: and there are all these other kinds of sports which people follow, you know, in the last

00:19:19.320 --> 00:19:24.040
[Amit Varma]: 20 years, there's been this burgeoning of Indian fans suddenly finding English football

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:27.240
[Amit Varma]: clubs to be loyal to, even though they've never been there.

00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:31.600
[Amit Varma]: Is that something that in a sense has changed the stakes?

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:38.040
[Amit Varma]: Is that a reason why a modern Indian sporting fan may not understand, say, the visceral

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:40.920
[Amit Varma]: impact that sport could have had on people like us?

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:47.200
[Amit Varma]: And of course, at this moment, speaking purely from a sort of a fanhood perspective.

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:52.040
[Guest 2]: So look, the two things, one is that one of the things that the international sport did

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:57.200
[Guest 2]: do when it started coming in, especially Star Sports and all these channels coming in, it

00:19:57.200 --> 00:20:01.200
[Guest 2]: showed us something that we were not aware of and it was a rude awakening.

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:05.440
[Guest 2]: And I remember specifically in football, the rude awakening, like we've had Premier League

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:08.360
[Guest 2]: football and all going on since 93, 94.

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:14.000
[Guest 2]: But in 1996, ESPN Star Sports, in those days, there was a separate ESPN channel and a separate

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:15.000
[Guest 2]: Star Sports channel.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.240
[Guest 2]: They got together around 97.

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:22.760
[Guest 2]: So ESPN, in their great wisdom, was showing Euro 96, which was fantastic.

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:26.880
[Guest 2]: And in the breaks between Euro 96, they have bought 10 years of rights to Calcutta League

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:27.880
[Guest 2]: football.

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:33.040
[Guest 2]: OK, and it's a defining moment, because what happened was there was a half an hour gap

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:34.040
[Guest 2]: between matches.

00:20:34.040 --> 00:20:35.760
[Guest 2]: They didn't have a studio show.

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:38.840
[Guest 2]: So what they'd do is they'd show a Euro match.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:42.240
[Guest 2]: And then in the half an hour before the next Euro match, they'd show Calcutta Football

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:43.240
[Guest 2]: League highlights.

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:45.800
[Guest 2]: Esbinghol, Mohun Bagan, Mahmood and Sporting.

00:20:45.800 --> 00:20:49.000
[Guest 2]: And I remember my father was there with me because he was on his way.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:54.160
[Guest 2]: And in those days, I was working for IMGT, and he was on his way to visit my sister in

00:20:54.160 --> 00:20:55.160
[Guest 2]: the US.

00:20:55.160 --> 00:20:56.160
[Guest 2]: So he was with me.

00:20:56.160 --> 00:20:59.240
[Guest 2]: So he used to watch these Euro matches, and then he's suddenly seeing Esbinghol, Mohun

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:00.240
[Guest 2]: Bagan.

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:03.880
[Guest 2]: And you know, suddenly that football is in such sharp contrast, because you're seeing

00:21:03.880 --> 00:21:05.720
[Guest 2]: one against the other.

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:10.280
[Guest 2]: And my father actually once really bewildered and looked at me and said, are these guys

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:11.840
[Guest 2]: playing in slow motion?

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:15.240
[Guest 2]: Because suddenly he's seeing what international football looks like.

00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:20.160
[Guest 2]: So yes, 30% of it is better cameras, better vision, all that.

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:25.840
[Guest 2]: But 70% of it was that suddenly the game that he thought was perfectly normal to play, an

00:21:25.840 --> 00:21:30.160
[Guest 2]: Esbinghol, Mohun Bagan match, was shown in contrast to what international football really

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:31.800
[Guest 2]: looked like.

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:35.120
[Guest 2]: And that's a realization that has happened in Indian sport.

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:39.600
[Guest 2]: And it's a very powerful realization, because suddenly every football team in India today,

00:21:39.600 --> 00:21:43.120
[Guest 2]: we are struggling again to get back, because we are saying, OK, you know, our football

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:46.880
[Guest 2]: was 30% world standard, now we are at 55%, 54%, 55%.

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:48.880
[Guest 2]: We are moving there.

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:53.840
[Guest 2]: But clearly, you have a choice of watching an ISL team, or you have a choice of watching

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:55.920
[Guest 2]: Messi or Ronaldo play.

00:21:55.920 --> 00:22:00.600
[Guest 2]: And that choice has made things much more difficult for Indian fans, and much more difficult

00:22:00.600 --> 00:22:02.400
[Guest 2]: for Indian sport to grow.

00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:07.040
[Guest 2]: Because you're suddenly up against, you know, channels don't know loyalty.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:08.880
[Guest 2]: You know, your remote button knows no loyalty.

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:13.520
[Guest 2]: So that is now a challenge that's facing every part of Indian sport.

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:16.920
[Guest 2]: And perhaps cricket is the best off in that nature, because whatever it is, you know,

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:20.760
[Guest 2]: the IPL, the best cricket players in the world come and play in the IPL.

00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:25.760
[Guest 2]: Every other product we have is an inferior product to something you'll see abroad.

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:27.200
[Amit Varma]: So OK, here's my next question.

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:33.360
[Amit Varma]: I just did an episode on the importance of liberalization, the 91 reforms.

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:36.080
[Amit Varma]: And my guest was Shruti Rajgopalan and Ajay Shah.

00:22:36.080 --> 00:22:40.200
[Amit Varma]: And right at the end, I asked him that, you know, on what gave them hope and what gave

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:41.320
[Amit Varma]: them despair.

00:22:41.320 --> 00:22:42.920
[Amit Varma]: And Ajay gave me an interesting answer.

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:46.600
[Amit Varma]: He said that what gives me hope is that the 91 reforms, even if you've gone backwards

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:51.440
[Amit Varma]: and terrible things are happening now, even if all that has happened, the 91 reforms,

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:56.120
[Amit Varma]: and what happened in the subsequent 20 years till about 2011, showed us that Indians can

00:22:56.120 --> 00:22:57.120
[Amit Varma]: achieve anything.

00:22:57.120 --> 00:23:00.920
[Amit Varma]: We can compete with the best in the world, we can do anything we want, there are no barriers.

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:05.040
[Amit Varma]: And that knowledge is important, that we don't have to make excuses, we don't have to talk

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:10.480
[Amit Varma]: about our great past or our great civilization or whatever, we can be the best in the present.

00:23:10.480 --> 00:23:14.840
[Amit Varma]: And that knowledge is important, at least now, you know, now I have a similar question

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:18.400
[Amit Varma]: about Indian sport, that there was always this assumption.

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:22.240
[Amit Varma]: And I have to say that for a large period of time, even I shared it, that India will

00:23:22.240 --> 00:23:27.280
[Amit Varma]: never be a great sporting nation, because of a variety of reasons, like one, of course,

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:31.720
[Amit Varma]: we don't really have a sporting culture, the way kids say in Australia will in their free

00:23:31.720 --> 00:23:33.560
[Amit Varma]: time, they'll just go out and play sports.

00:23:33.560 --> 00:23:36.640
[Amit Varma]: And over here, they won't do that they may watch some sports, but that sporting culture

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:37.640
[Amit Varma]: isn't there.

00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:42.560
[Amit Varma]: And one ascribed various reasons to it, people would say that, you know, it's the genes and,

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:48.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's the climate and it's a nutrition, or maybe it's just a vicious cycle of a cultural

00:23:48.040 --> 00:23:49.760
[Amit Varma]: practice is not there in the culture.

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:52.600
[Amit Varma]: So it never comes into the culture, and so on and so forth.

00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:56.880
[Amit Varma]: But it seems to me that just as perhaps what Ajay was talking about the, you know, the

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:01.160
[Amit Varma]: post 91 reforms, whatever happened, showing that India can be the best can do anything,

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:04.440
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me that in sport, a similar thing has now happened.

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:08.720
[Amit Varma]: Like when you see Neeraj Chopra win the javelin gold medal, you cannot anymore say that there

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:11.840
[Amit Varma]: is something inherent that is keeping us back.

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:14.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Nandan, in your excellent book, Go, you know, you wrote the last chapter of the

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:15.840
[Amit Varma]: book.

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:19.880
[Amit Varma]: And there you spoke about the importance of the Abhinav Bindra moment, that that made

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:24.640
[Amit Varma]: such a difference that, you know, he wins the gold, and suddenly you have this self

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:29.040
[Amit Varma]: confidence that we can do it, which wasn't there earlier.

00:24:29.040 --> 00:24:34.080
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about the impact that it had, because at one level, it's just a matter

00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:35.620
[Amit Varma]: of millimeters, right?

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:38.640
[Amit Varma]: If somebody else had just done a little bit better, he wouldn't have got the gold, he

00:24:38.640 --> 00:24:42.400
[Amit Varma]: would have gotten the silver, and we've gotten silver before, would it have made such an

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:43.400
[Amit Varma]: impact?

00:24:43.400 --> 00:24:44.900
[Amit Varma]: Did getting that gold?

00:24:44.900 --> 00:24:46.080
[Amit Varma]: Was it a seminal moment?

00:24:46.080 --> 00:24:49.040
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about kind of what you what you feel about that?

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:50.400
[Guest 1]: Absolutely, Amit.

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:56.220
[Guest 1]: So it was also the time when we had just begun our journey as a foundation, Go Sports Foundation.

00:24:56.220 --> 00:25:01.560
[Guest 1]: And our dream was really this is to change the mindset and the belief system of what

00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:06.640
[Guest 1]: is possible not just for the athletes, but also for the surrounding ecosystem and people

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:13.280
[Guest 1]: who participate in those journeys and including stakeholders like parents, coaches, school

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:15.800
[Guest 1]: principals, college principals.

00:25:15.800 --> 00:25:20.800
[Guest 1]: So the point is that, like you mentioned, there were many, many, many stereotypes in

00:25:20.800 --> 00:25:25.040
[Guest 1]: Indian sport, which had actually seeped into the management of sport.

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:30.360
[Guest 1]: So we had these concepts of priority disciplines and non-priority disciplines.

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:33.440
[Guest 1]: Based on that, the government would fund different federations.

00:25:33.440 --> 00:25:38.600
[Guest 1]: So if you were a talented athlete in a non-priority sport, you probably had zero chance of making

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:39.680
[Guest 1]: it to the Olympics.

00:25:39.680 --> 00:25:45.060
[Guest 1]: So it wasn't talent based, lots of perceptions, I mean, we had limited sports budget.

00:25:45.060 --> 00:25:48.820
[Guest 1]: So let's be clear, this was not a priority for many, many, many years, right?

00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:56.400
[Guest 1]: So we move towards funding some athletes, we go to the Olympics, most of them are just

00:25:56.400 --> 00:26:01.800
[Guest 1]: so happy to get there because of the number of obstacles overcome to get to the Olympics.

00:26:01.800 --> 00:26:05.960
[Guest 1]: And I'll just back up before the Abhinav Bindra story to around the same time.

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:11.240
[Guest 1]: At that point, I've gone to the UK, studied in the UK and the US and now come back to

00:26:11.240 --> 00:26:16.080
[Guest 1]: India very, very passionate about doing something meaningful in sport, I haven't found what

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:17.080
[Guest 1]: that is yet.

00:26:17.080 --> 00:26:22.160
[Guest 1]: But one day, I just get a call from one of my law school colleagues, and he says, Hey,

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:27.320
[Guest 1]: I'm at the Bangalore airport, this is the HAL old airport, and I've just come upon one

00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:30.120
[Guest 1]: of the stars of the Indian hockey team.

00:26:30.120 --> 00:26:33.680
[Guest 1]: So this guy is trying to get to the Sai Centre, Bangalore, which is pretty far away, it's

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:36.600
[Guest 1]: close to the National Law School, Kingiri.

00:26:36.600 --> 00:26:41.080
[Guest 1]: And he's standing at the auto stand, and no auto is willing to take him.

00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:43.980
[Guest 1]: So this is an Indian national hockey player.

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:45.680
[Guest 1]: And he said, we got to do something.

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:50.600
[Guest 1]: So like, he literally picks him up, goes and drops him at Sai, comes back and we begin

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:55.440
[Guest 1]: the relationship, like I do things like including filling up his Arjuna Award application, which

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:57.160
[Guest 1]: he eventually gets.

00:26:57.160 --> 00:27:01.880
[Guest 1]: But on the day of his Arjuna Award, you know, they do these lots of interviews at the Ashok

00:27:01.880 --> 00:27:02.880
[Guest 1]: Hotel.

00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:06.880
[Guest 1]: So I'm there, he's talking, and the journalist asks him, so what has the journey been like?

00:27:06.880 --> 00:27:13.760
[Guest 1]: And he says, I can't even tell you because we are literally sent out to represent India,

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:18.640
[Guest 1]: telling us, you're going to lose anyway, so just have a good time and come back.

00:27:18.640 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest 1]: And this is our national, I mean, quasi de facto national sport, which we won so much

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:25.000
[Guest 1]: at.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:28.280
[Guest 1]: So to me, that was such a telling moment and a heartbreaking moment.

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:33.800
[Guest 1]: But what Abhinav's moment was, a lot of people, I think, don't cut him the slack saying he

00:27:33.800 --> 00:27:40.200
[Guest 1]: got all the facilities, I think, despite having all the facilities, he still went through

00:27:40.200 --> 00:27:42.360
[Guest 1]: the motions of doing whatever it took.

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:46.240
[Guest 1]: And if you read his book, and I really recommend it, A Shorthead History is one of the great

00:27:46.240 --> 00:27:50.920
[Guest 1]: sports books worldwide, not even talking Indian book, Rohit Brijnath and him have written

00:27:50.920 --> 00:27:55.520
[Guest 1]: fantastically on it, the number of journeys he went through to get there.

00:27:55.520 --> 00:28:02.560
[Guest 1]: And to me, that is the moment for Indian sport, which also came around the IPL as well.

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:10.320
[Guest 1]: So 2008 is our 1983 moment or the 1991 moment.

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:14.120
[Guest 1]: Lots changed and lots changed in the mind.

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:18.820
[Guest 1]: And I still talk to Abhinav a lot, and we talk about what it takes to win that medal.

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:21.360
[Guest 1]: And so much of it is in the mind.

00:28:21.360 --> 00:28:26.700
[Guest 1]: So you can go to the Olympics, world champion, you can go to the Olympics, world number one,

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:28.180
[Guest 1]: but it's being there.

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:31.440
[Guest 1]: And you can convince yourself all you want, it's just another day.

00:28:31.440 --> 00:28:36.160
[Guest 1]: The more and more you try and do that, the tougher and tougher it gets because it's sort

00:28:36.160 --> 00:28:38.940
[Guest 1]: of the Olympic moment is between your ears, right?

00:28:38.940 --> 00:28:42.040
[Guest 1]: So it's the stadium, but also between your ears.

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:48.120
[Guest 1]: And but what he did is change the self-talk of the Indian athlete.

00:28:48.120 --> 00:28:53.060
[Guest 1]: Because it became from if he can do it, I can do it, and then we can do it.

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:59.400
[Guest 1]: So just beginning to connect the dots on what is possible as an Indian.

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:06.680
[Guest 1]: And to me that it needed a single breakthrough as a gold medal, like it needed breakthroughs

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:12.360
[Guest 1]: of different sorts, even Olympic qualification in a sport we thought we were never good at,

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:13.920
[Guest 1]: or did not have a chance in.

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:19.880
[Guest 1]: So each athlete is building on the other and by Abhinav's moment, there had been enough

00:29:19.880 --> 00:29:23.960
[Guest 1]: to make that an incremental, but very, very significant moment.

00:29:23.960 --> 00:29:28.680
[Guest 1]: And in our book, Rohit Brijnath talks about it, the we can moment of the belief that we

00:29:28.680 --> 00:29:29.760
[Guest 1]: can.

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:34.600
[Guest 1]: And a lot of people ask, so we've been through not 12 years of working in Indian sport with

00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:39.160
[Guest 1]: our foundation and a lot of people say, okay, what, how do you measure this and tell me

00:29:39.160 --> 00:29:40.160
[Guest 1]: what's happened?

00:29:40.160 --> 00:29:41.520
[Guest 1]: Is all the money worth it?

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:44.860
[Guest 1]: We put in so much CSR fund, the government fund so much.

00:29:44.860 --> 00:29:46.280
[Guest 1]: So what has really changed?

00:29:46.280 --> 00:29:51.200
[Guest 1]: And I mean, it certainly helps to have an Olympic medal tally, which is our best ever.

00:29:51.200 --> 00:29:56.280
[Guest 1]: But my answer is always, I may not be able to measure it, but qualitatively, I can feel

00:29:56.280 --> 00:29:57.280
[Guest 1]: it.

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:01.840
[Guest 1]: I've met athletes over the years, the way they stand, the way they hold them themselves,

00:30:01.840 --> 00:30:07.760
[Guest 1]: the way they look you in the eye, what they say, the language of expression, not just

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:12.120
[Guest 1]: how they say things, but what they say has completely changed.

00:30:12.120 --> 00:30:18.560
[Guest 1]: And to me, that is indicative of a confident, self-aware, but also well-resourced athlete.

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:23.080
[Guest 1]: And I think we'll get to that of how they've become well-resourced and absolutely critical

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:28.960
[Guest 1]: is knowing that nothing has not been done when you're standing on that, at that shooting

00:30:28.960 --> 00:30:36.200
[Guest 1]: range or in the sort of boxing ring, whatever else, the confidence, what is confidence?

00:30:36.200 --> 00:30:40.720
[Guest 1]: Confidence is knowing that there was nothing else you could have done to get to where you

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:46.960
[Guest 1]: are and prepared everything that you could have possibly done to deal with uncertainty

00:30:46.960 --> 00:30:51.240
[Guest 1]: of competitor, location, various different things.

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:56.000
[Guest 1]: And I think that that transformation was Abhinav's, but it was the transformation of everyone

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:57.940
[Guest 1]: who came before him as well.

00:30:57.940 --> 00:31:01.200
[Guest 1]: So bronze turned to silver, silver turned to gold.

00:31:01.200 --> 00:31:06.640
[Guest 1]: And I think we've taken a couple of Olympics to get the legacy effect of that.

00:31:06.640 --> 00:31:11.520
[Guest 1]: And I'm so glad it happened in this Olympics, it's a huge, huge moment that and a huge load

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:15.640
[Guest 1]: of I think Abhinav's back because I think one of the quotes we have in our book there

00:31:15.640 --> 00:31:19.120
[Guest 1]: is that it's great being the first one, but I don't want to be the only one.

00:31:19.120 --> 00:31:21.600
[Guest 1]: And I think he's finally got his wish.

00:31:21.600 --> 00:31:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, and in a sense, you could argue that subsequent gold medals also, you know,

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:31.840
[Amit Varma]: have something to do with his gold medal, as you pointed out, I loved your definition

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:35.120
[Amit Varma]: of confidence, because it focuses on process.

00:31:35.120 --> 00:31:38.680
[Amit Varma]: I've done everything I can to get here and, you know, and that's your confident and you

00:31:38.680 --> 00:31:43.080
[Amit Varma]: just do what you have to do, which is such a wonderful and inspiring definition.

00:31:43.080 --> 00:31:47.040
[Amit Varma]: But one of the things that struck me and it struck me also when I read this recent piece

00:31:47.040 --> 00:31:52.660
[Amit Varma]: that you wrote in Deccan Herald, is that Indian sports, not just authorities and federations,

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:56.160
[Amit Varma]: but also fans tend to be two results oriented.

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:59.640
[Amit Varma]: In your piece, you were speaking about, you know, the support that athletes need, and

00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:04.160
[Amit Varma]: you wrote, quote, career pathways require incremental reward towards the athlete's journey.

00:32:04.160 --> 00:32:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Instead, central and state governments reserve huge monetary rewards for medal winners.

00:32:08.520 --> 00:32:13.340
[Amit Varma]: While exceptional athletes deserve every accolade, such a system can skew the balance between

00:32:13.340 --> 00:32:15.180
[Amit Varma]: process and outcome, stop quote.

00:32:15.180 --> 00:32:19.640
[Amit Varma]: And even when I think about this Olympics, right, Neeraj threw 87 points something, right?

00:32:19.640 --> 00:32:22.680
[Amit Varma]: We are all celebrating that because hey, he won the gold.

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:23.680
[Amit Varma]: But what if he hadn't?

00:32:23.680 --> 00:32:27.220
[Amit Varma]: You know, Johannes Wetter, for example, I think threw more than 90 meters seven times

00:32:27.220 --> 00:32:28.220
[Amit Varma]: this year already.

00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:29.860
[Amit Varma]: And it's almost routine for him.

00:32:29.860 --> 00:32:32.520
[Amit Varma]: So let's say he hadn't won the gold, but he had thrown 87.

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, my argument would be that it is deserving of equal celebration.

00:32:37.440 --> 00:32:42.440
[Amit Varma]: Equally, you know, somebody was cribbing on Twitter about how our boxing guys and wrestling

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:46.320
[Amit Varma]: guys are placed so high in the world, but they didn't really, you know, win any goals.

00:32:46.320 --> 00:32:48.380
[Amit Varma]: And my argument there is it doesn't matter.

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:52.800
[Amit Varma]: This is one event, there's a lot of luck, you can't be two results oriented, the fact

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:56.600
[Amit Varma]: that they're rated so high in the world, they won world championships and all that shows

00:32:56.600 --> 00:32:58.720
[Amit Varma]: you that the process is working.

00:32:58.720 --> 00:33:02.920
[Amit Varma]: Fans don't often get this, you know, I'm sure sports people obviously do, because that's

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:04.160
[Amit Varma]: the secret of success, right?

00:33:04.160 --> 00:33:06.100
[Amit Varma]: You focus on process and not outcome.

00:33:06.100 --> 00:33:09.040
[Amit Varma]: But fans don't get this and sporting bodies don't often get this.

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:15.640
[Amit Varma]: Do you see this as a mindset issue that still has to change, that you look at the performance

00:33:15.640 --> 00:33:21.520
[Amit Varma]: and not necessarily the result that if Neeraj throws 87.5, that's a great throw regardless

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:24.600
[Amit Varma]: of whether it gets a gold or whether it's outside the top four, which it might well

00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:26.720
[Amit Varma]: have been on a different day.

00:33:26.720 --> 00:33:30.040
[Amit Varma]: What are your respective thoughts on this?

00:33:30.040 --> 00:33:35.160
[Guest 2]: So look, my point about this is that Neeraj winning is a great thing.

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:36.960
[Guest 2]: But I am completely with Nandan.

00:33:36.960 --> 00:33:39.120
[Guest 2]: The point is, everyone is not going to understand.

00:33:39.120 --> 00:33:43.040
[Guest 2]: Therefore, you'll need a few results, you need an Abhinav, you need a Neeraj.

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:46.120
[Guest 2]: But the point of it is that Nandan is absolutely right.

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:49.920
[Guest 2]: It's process and it's process that gets you to a particular position.

00:33:49.920 --> 00:33:54.000
[Guest 2]: The sad bad fact of it is that if you're a cricketer, you're going to get 50 chances

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.520
[Guest 2]: through the year to prove whether you're right or wrong.

00:33:56.520 --> 00:34:00.240
[Guest 2]: If you're an Olympic athlete, you're basically going to get the Olympics, possibly the Asian

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:02.320
[Guest 2]: Games, possibly the Commonwealth Games.

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:07.080
[Guest 2]: And remember, rarely do you are at least good at both the Asian Games and the Commonwealth

00:34:07.080 --> 00:34:12.520
[Guest 2]: Games because the way it's skewed, you know, if you're going safe towards a sprinting event,

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:14.680
[Guest 2]: the Commonwealth Games are a terrible place to be.

00:34:14.680 --> 00:34:17.720
[Guest 2]: On the other hand, if you're playing badminton, the Asian Games is probably a more dangerous

00:34:17.720 --> 00:34:18.720
[Guest 2]: event.

00:34:18.720 --> 00:34:23.760
[Guest 2]: So in any case, you basically have a one in two year chance of actually having a share

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:25.040
[Guest 2]: of mind.

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:27.120
[Guest 2]: That's the pressure that's on the athlete.

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:33.240
[Guest 2]: And that is the fundamental issue that what also happens a lot is and see federations

00:34:33.240 --> 00:34:38.400
[Guest 2]: and even the government, everyone is not trusting because we've not had great results before.

00:34:38.400 --> 00:34:43.360
[Guest 2]: So very often what happens is we actually keep sending athletes to ranking tournaments

00:34:43.360 --> 00:34:46.720
[Guest 2]: to show the government, look, this guy's doing this, this guy's doing that.

00:34:46.720 --> 00:34:50.840
[Guest 2]: And a lot of the times, the Chinese and South Koreans, perhaps, you know, they've done more

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:53.820
[Guest 2]: in the sport, they're more adept to the system.

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:56.480
[Guest 2]: So they'll say, look, we're not going to send our athletes here.

00:34:56.480 --> 00:35:00.120
[Guest 2]: So a lot of the archery events you'll see, you know, crucial archery events, we remember

00:35:00.120 --> 00:35:02.240
[Guest 2]: Deepika Kumari winning a lot.

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:05.000
[Guest 2]: But the South Koreans were not there, the Chinese were not there, they wouldn't come

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:06.680
[Guest 2]: for an event like that.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:11.280
[Guest 2]: But we needed to because if we didn't go there and Deepika didn't win something, they could

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:14.000
[Guest 2]: turn around and say, you know, Deepika's not really in form.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:21.400
[Guest 2]: So still as sporting people, even as a federation or a government body, we don't have the confidence.

00:35:21.400 --> 00:35:26.560
[Guest 2]: We are not in a position to be able to say, you know, this athlete's good enough, we'll

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:31.720
[Guest 2]: let go of this event, we'll focus on a peak during the Olympics.

00:35:31.720 --> 00:35:32.960
[Guest 2]: These are very important things.

00:35:32.960 --> 00:35:35.240
[Guest 2]: And I think this is the next stage in maturity.

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:40.120
[Guest 2]: Look, I am already I'm quite happy the fact that we are sending athletes to exposure tours

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:44.440
[Guest 2]: because you know, exposure tours and other tours are much better than not going anywhere

00:35:44.440 --> 00:35:48.000
[Guest 2]: and not knowing exactly, you know, you're not sure what food to eat.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:51.920
[Guest 2]: I remember the horror story that my brother-in-law told me, I think it was Shivnath Singh.

00:35:51.920 --> 00:35:56.120
[Guest 2]: And Shivnath Singh was before going to Montreal, he was in Oxford where my brother-in-law was

00:35:56.120 --> 00:35:58.360
[Guest 2]: also a Rhodes Scholar, he was there.

00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:02.200
[Guest 2]: And he said, the guy just survived, he didn't know what to eat, so he had to survive on

00:36:02.200 --> 00:36:05.800
[Guest 2]: bread and milk, because those are the only two things he would understand.

00:36:05.800 --> 00:36:08.320
[Guest 2]: And there's nobody to cook for him, there's no diet.

00:36:08.320 --> 00:36:11.960
[Guest 2]: And he's saying that this is what's happening to him in the UK where there is a little bit

00:36:11.960 --> 00:36:14.120
[Guest 2]: of a support system of us around him.

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:16.280
[Guest 2]: What's going to happen to him in Montreal?

00:36:16.280 --> 00:36:21.020
[Guest 2]: And those are the kind of things that, you know, athletes today at least have so much

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:25.520
[Guest 2]: more support, so much more understanding, people around them who are there to take care

00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:26.520
[Guest 2]: of this.

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:30.520
[Guest 2]: So yes, we have matured, we've come a long way, I think we need to take the next step

00:36:30.520 --> 00:36:36.780
[Guest 2]: and say that if this person is a premier athlete, perhaps not participating in this and peaking

00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:41.960
[Guest 2]: in the Olympics is more important than winning this just to prove that he or she is a good

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:42.960
[Guest 2]: athlete.

00:36:42.960 --> 00:36:43.960
[Guest 2]: And that's one of the things I'd look at.

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:48.240
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I think that's brilliantly put, like I said, my mother was a cartoonist and I sometimes

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:49.240
[Guest 1]: think of cartoons.

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:53.080
[Guest 1]: I've actually been very upset with Neeraj Chopra because he's destroyed my favorite

00:36:53.080 --> 00:36:54.120
[Guest 1]: cartoon.

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:58.200
[Guest 1]: And that had essentially a cave mother talking to her two sons.

00:36:58.200 --> 00:37:00.620
[Guest 1]: One of them is kicking around the round thing.

00:37:00.620 --> 00:37:03.320
[Guest 1]: And the other is sort of going hunting with a spear.

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:06.880
[Guest 1]: And the mother is telling the young fellow, what do you think you're going to make money

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:08.500
[Guest 1]: kicking this round thing around?

00:37:08.500 --> 00:37:11.200
[Guest 1]: Look at your brother, he's throwing a spear, right?

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:14.200
[Guest 1]: And no way you're going to be making money throwing a spear.

00:37:14.200 --> 00:37:19.160
[Guest 1]: But I think here's Neeraj Chopra with, I think, tens of crores of reward, destroyed my cartoon

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:23.360
[Guest 1]: along the way, but also has got some very random prizes as well.

00:37:23.360 --> 00:37:29.000
[Guest 1]: But I think as Joy puts it, there's things that happen in the system as a result of this

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:35.960
[Guest 1]: type of what I call a bounty system, is that you have, you're going to be rewarded hugely

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:40.640
[Guest 1]: if you're successful, and everyone else is in some sense left behind.

00:37:40.640 --> 00:37:47.960
[Guest 1]: It breaks other parts of the system with this hypercompetitivism and also people using shortcuts.

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:53.080
[Guest 1]: There's a strong linkage of even doping because there's no consequence to getting caught.

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:58.000
[Guest 1]: The only consequence is if you don't get caught and you succeed, you might get some large

00:37:58.000 --> 00:37:59.400
[Guest 1]: reward.

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:04.600
[Guest 1]: But Joy hit a very important point as well on how funding used to work.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:09.160
[Guest 1]: And there's been a transformation in the last five, six, seven years with a pretty significant

00:38:09.160 --> 00:38:14.240
[Guest 1]: government scheme called the Target Olympic Podium Scheme and how it worked with federations,

00:38:14.240 --> 00:38:16.040
[Guest 1]: with other bodies as well.

00:38:16.040 --> 00:38:21.600
[Guest 1]: But earlier, what you had was this push to show that you were world class by maintaining

00:38:21.600 --> 00:38:22.600
[Guest 1]: rankings.

00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:26.200
[Guest 1]: And in many sports, you had to maintain ranking just by playing a lot.

00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:30.520
[Guest 1]: So you figured out how to play a lot, and how to game the systems.

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:34.520
[Guest 1]: And I think you've seen lots of examples even in chess of how to become a grandmaster, by

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:37.920
[Guest 1]: even sort of paying off people to lose against you and stuff.

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:43.480
[Guest 1]: So huge amounts of effort, parental effort, athlete effort would be on getting to rankings

00:38:43.480 --> 00:38:46.120
[Guest 1]: because funding depended on it.

00:38:46.120 --> 00:38:51.360
[Guest 1]: There was a very ad hoc system of how athletes and particularly elite athletes would get

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:52.400
[Guest 1]: funded.

00:38:52.400 --> 00:38:57.560
[Guest 1]: It would be given in smaller tranches based on rankings, performance, and it was a limited

00:38:57.560 --> 00:39:02.800
[Guest 1]: pool, which lots of people were fighting for, which also led to other stuff like we'd have

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:06.200
[Guest 1]: Wimbledon junior champions, but none of them would progress.

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:08.240
[Guest 1]: You had the Leander who broke through that.

00:39:08.240 --> 00:39:13.440
[Guest 1]: But what you had was, while European kids were already playing seniors losing first

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:17.480
[Guest 1]: round, first round, first round, first round for for half a year, before they made it to

00:39:17.480 --> 00:39:22.400
[Guest 1]: second round quarterfinals, and then I mean, look at a Roger Federer story, our kids were

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:25.960
[Guest 1]: still playing junior events, because that was the only way to get funded.

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:31.320
[Guest 1]: And those breakages actually make a system because you aren't seeing people progress

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:32.320
[Guest 1]: through the pathways.

00:39:32.320 --> 00:39:37.800
[Guest 1]: You have to learn how to lose and get exposed to loss to begin winning.

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:40.680
[Guest 1]: And we didn't have that give in the system.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:45.520
[Guest 1]: We were willing to fund people who had already proved themselves and how they had got there

00:39:45.520 --> 00:39:51.160
[Guest 1]: was I mean, none of our business in some sense, and willing to reward the people who had won.

00:39:51.160 --> 00:39:55.720
[Guest 1]: But we had not necessarily seen the journey and the pathway there.

00:39:55.720 --> 00:39:59.720
[Guest 1]: And like I said, there were other sort of things like we have priority sports, we have

00:39:59.720 --> 00:40:04.480
[Guest 1]: shooting, boxing, wrestling, we are going to say that these are the things worth focusing

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:09.840
[Guest 1]: on, because someone in the past has broken through of their own accord, got some support

00:40:09.840 --> 00:40:16.040
[Guest 1]: and proved that Indians are capable of winning a shooting medal, maybe a tennis medal, boxing,

00:40:16.040 --> 00:40:20.400
[Guest 1]: wrestling, weightlifting, now everything else, we are not competent.

00:40:20.400 --> 00:40:25.240
[Guest 1]: And we convince ourselves, we convince our donors, we convince our government, everyone

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:28.680
[Guest 1]: is convinced that we can't be anything else.

00:40:28.680 --> 00:40:33.240
[Guest 1]: We are good at the sports which require dexterity and speed and other things.

00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:37.200
[Guest 1]: But don't talk about strength or stamina, running, all of that.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:41.840
[Guest 1]: We just don't have the genes, like you said, we don't have aptitude, there's no point even

00:40:41.840 --> 00:40:43.560
[Guest 1]: trying.

00:40:43.560 --> 00:40:48.960
[Guest 1]: And that is a system that has gone through, I would say reformation in the last eight

00:40:48.960 --> 00:40:49.960
[Guest 1]: or 10 years.

00:40:49.960 --> 00:40:53.360
[Guest 1]: And there are various reasons for that, which we could to chat about too.

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:58.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, a lot of fascinating stands and big questions to pick up on and I'll come back

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:01.100
[Amit Varma]: to your personal journey at a later point in time.

00:41:01.100 --> 00:41:04.440
[Amit Varma]: But first, a few questions, but you know, as far as the cartoon is concerned, it's still

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:09.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of valid because I can guarantee you that the 100 best footballer in the world

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:12.360
[Amit Varma]: makes way more money than the 100 best javelin thrower.

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:15.600
[Amit Varma]: So I don't think you know, that kind of balance sort of remains.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:19.240
[Amit Varma]: As far as chess, grandmasters, gaming norms, and all that is concerned, that's extreme

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:20.240
[Amit Varma]: outlier.

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:21.240
[Amit Varma]: Those guys don't really get anywhere.

00:41:21.240 --> 00:41:25.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, in some obscure corner of the Soviet Union, they'll have these fictitious tournaments

00:41:25.280 --> 00:41:29.040
[Amit Varma]: which never even happen and rating is kind of given but that is such an outlier.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:30.040
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't matter.

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:33.840
[Amit Varma]: One of the strands I want to pick up on is also then these trade offs that you mentioned,

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:38.840
[Amit Varma]: like on the one hand, you know, Joy was talking about the trade off that one when you're supporting

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:41.900
[Amit Varma]: athletes, you want to take them towards sporting excellence.

00:41:41.900 --> 00:41:45.640
[Amit Varma]: So you want to space out their training, you want them to peak at the right time.

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:50.440
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you also have to satisfy another constituency and build those narratives

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:56.640
[Amit Varma]: So you send him to random tournaments, which may not otherwise be good for him.

00:41:56.640 --> 00:42:01.600
[Amit Varma]: And the necessity of that trade off is worrisome and similar trade off and you mentioned about

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:06.440
[Amit Varma]: Indian kids winning Wimbledon juniors, when people their age are already sort of playing

00:42:06.440 --> 00:42:07.440
[Amit Varma]: the senior level.

00:42:07.440 --> 00:42:10.360
[Amit Varma]: And this happens in chess also, by the way, that you know, for the last few years, the

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:14.040
[Amit Varma]: best players don't take part in the World Junior Championships because they're already

00:42:14.040 --> 00:42:16.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of fighting to get into the actual top 10.

00:42:16.960 --> 00:42:20.920
[Amit Varma]: This also sort of reminds me of what happens in women's chess, like people have this misconception

00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:22.960
[Amit Varma]: that there is men's chess and women's chess.

00:42:22.960 --> 00:42:26.760
[Amit Varma]: But actually, there's no such thing as men's chess, there's an open category where everyone

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:27.760
[Amit Varma]: plays.

00:42:27.760 --> 00:42:29.460
[Amit Varma]: And then there's a women's category.

00:42:29.460 --> 00:42:33.200
[Amit Varma]: Because for all kinds of reasons, you know, women haven't been able to get results at

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:37.720
[Amit Varma]: the open category, historical reasons, social reasons, whatever, bunch of stuff.

00:42:37.720 --> 00:42:41.760
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, there have been women who have said that I will not play the women's category,

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:45.920
[Amit Varma]: I will play the open category, I will play with the boys, I don't want a separate category.

00:42:45.920 --> 00:42:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And very notably, Judith Polger reached the world top 10 in the open.

00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:54.080
[Amit Varma]: And Yifan who dropped out, she was women's world champion, she dropped out of the cycle

00:42:54.080 --> 00:42:58.240
[Amit Varma]: and is no longer women's world champion, because she said, I will only play open events.

00:42:58.240 --> 00:43:02.240
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, a few years ago, there was this player called Alexandra Goryachkina.

00:43:02.240 --> 00:43:06.640
[Amit Varma]: So I think when she was 15 and 16, she won the girls junior world championship when she

00:43:06.640 --> 00:43:07.640
[Amit Varma]: was 15 and 16.

00:43:07.640 --> 00:43:09.400
[Amit Varma]: And juniors was under 20.

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:11.720
[Amit Varma]: And then she said that no, I want to play the open.

00:43:11.720 --> 00:43:15.120
[Amit Varma]: And the next few years, she played the open junior championship and finished middle of

00:43:15.120 --> 00:43:17.440
[Amit Varma]: the field like 30th, 40th, whatever.

00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:18.880
[Amit Varma]: But she continued doing that.

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:20.120
[Amit Varma]: And she's a very strong player today.

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:22.080
[Amit Varma]: But now she's back to playing women's events.

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:26.280
[Amit Varma]: The juniors who would finish around her the male juniors, 30th or 40th are probably earning

00:43:26.280 --> 00:43:27.360
[Amit Varma]: nothing.

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:32.080
[Amit Varma]: But you know, she could take part in the women's event and earn much better because that was

00:43:32.080 --> 00:43:33.080
[Amit Varma]: sort of spun out.

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:35.560
[Amit Varma]: So similar kind of trade offs in play.

00:43:35.560 --> 00:43:40.560
[Amit Varma]: Is it getting better in terms of these trade offs and this perception management, I understand

00:43:40.560 --> 00:43:44.280
[Amit Varma]: that private involvement is much more you guys are funding all this, we'll talk in detail

00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:45.760
[Amit Varma]: about tops as well.

00:43:45.760 --> 00:43:51.160
[Amit Varma]: But is there on the one hand, not just a case for building a great product, but also marketing

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:57.280
[Amit Varma]: that great product to the state, to the government, ki nahi isko bhejna hai, isko kyu bheje?

00:43:57.280 --> 00:44:00.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, iska yeh ranking hai, how do you get that ranking?

00:44:00.440 --> 00:44:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Is that game still a problem?

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Or is there a period in time where that game is becoming less and less of a problem?

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.960
[Amit Varma]: Because these results are gradually starting to come through.

00:44:09.960 --> 00:44:15.280
[Guest 2]: So I'll pick up on that first, because I think, as I said, Nandan is in that thing of, you

00:44:15.280 --> 00:44:17.800
[Guest 2]: know, some of what he's doing is involved with it.

00:44:17.800 --> 00:44:22.200
[Guest 2]: Actually, I was, well, I spent six months doing some work with the Ghost Sports Foundation

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:24.800
[Guest 2]: is one of the best things I ever did.

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:26.760
[Guest 2]: But I think it's getting better.

00:44:26.760 --> 00:44:32.600
[Guest 2]: I think what had happened right to the start is when tops came, everyone thought, you know,

00:44:32.600 --> 00:44:36.200
[Guest 2]: is tops an all or nothing, you know, this is what it is, they're going to fund it, they're

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:37.200
[Guest 2]: going to do it.

00:44:37.200 --> 00:44:40.240
[Guest 2]: There are some things that a government cannot do.

00:44:40.240 --> 00:44:41.240
[Guest 2]: There are reasons for that.

00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:43.680
[Guest 2]: There are government policies, there are government decisions.

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:47.200
[Guest 2]: A simple thing, you know, do you want to fly an athlete business class?

00:44:47.200 --> 00:44:48.680
[Guest 2]: Okay, it's a simple thing.

00:44:48.680 --> 00:44:52.040
[Guest 2]: Now, it may be necessary for some events, it may not be necessary.

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:56.480
[Guest 2]: But for some events, it may actually be necessary, that kind of extra sleep, that kind of extra

00:44:56.480 --> 00:44:57.960
[Guest 2]: rest may be useful.

00:44:57.960 --> 00:44:58.960
[Guest 2]: Okay.

00:44:58.960 --> 00:45:00.920
[Guest 2]: Now, tops could not do that.

00:45:00.920 --> 00:45:05.400
[Guest 2]: It's difficult for tops to do that, given the system that we follow, okay.

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:09.560
[Guest 2]: Or you need a separate physio, and some people are just comfortable with a particular physio,

00:45:09.560 --> 00:45:12.160
[Guest 2]: or some people are comfortable that their mother travels with them.

00:45:12.160 --> 00:45:17.160
[Guest 2]: Now, that may drop off in time, that person, that athlete may mature in time.

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:21.160
[Guest 2]: But right at the start in their first few tournaments, they may need that family support.

00:45:21.160 --> 00:45:25.040
[Guest 2]: Now, those are things that the government cannot do.

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:28.520
[Guest 2]: So what has happened is right in the beginning, there was, you know, everyone thought it's

00:45:28.520 --> 00:45:31.320
[Guest 2]: either tops or these private schemes.

00:45:31.320 --> 00:45:34.960
[Guest 2]: And I think what's happened over the last three, four years, and especially the last

00:45:34.960 --> 00:45:39.480
[Guest 2]: couple of years, very successfully is, both of them have realized that for Indian athletes

00:45:39.480 --> 00:45:42.040
[Guest 2]: to succeed, they need to go hand in hand.

00:45:42.040 --> 00:45:47.280
[Guest 2]: And in fact, I remember being part of a series of seminars with Olympic athletes, which was

00:45:47.280 --> 00:45:51.040
[Guest 2]: all about giving them an understanding of what the idea of India as it were, in a very

00:45:51.040 --> 00:45:55.980
[Guest 2]: simple potted, if I would put it, and what Tokyo is all about, and what they could expect

00:45:55.980 --> 00:46:00.520
[Guest 2]: to find out there in very practical terms, not just in terms of the sea, but what are

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:03.320
[Guest 2]: Japanese like, what the city is going to be.

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:07.880
[Guest 2]: And it was researched and put together by Ghost Sports Foundation.

00:46:07.880 --> 00:46:10.120
[Guest 2]: But the athletes were bought in by tops.

00:46:10.120 --> 00:46:14.760
[Guest 2]: And that gives you a little bit of an idea about the fact that these guys are now, they're

00:46:14.760 --> 00:46:17.880
[Guest 2]: saying, it's not my product, it's not your product.

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:20.340
[Guest 2]: These athletes win, it's going to be good for all of us.

00:46:20.340 --> 00:46:25.200
[Guest 2]: And I think that is the one huge thing in Indian sport that we're seeing.

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:32.820
[Guest 2]: And right into 2015, 16, when tops started, it was all about, it's my way or the highway.

00:46:32.820 --> 00:46:36.800
[Guest 2]: And I think everyone now realizes that the only way to make a highway is if everyone

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:39.640
[Guest 2]: gets together to try and build it.

00:46:39.640 --> 00:46:41.040
[Guest 1]: I would totally agree.

00:46:41.040 --> 00:46:46.040
[Guest 1]: And seeing that experience from the other end as well, I mean, there's no I in team,

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:48.160
[Guest 1]: but there's more than one in Team India, right?

00:46:48.160 --> 00:46:54.320
[Guest 1]: So the recognition that there are many, many participants, and every athlete is India's

00:46:54.320 --> 00:46:59.720
[Guest 1]: athlete, it's not a government athlete or private athlete or some other scheme.

00:46:59.720 --> 00:47:05.600
[Guest 1]: And that really came through in the last five, six years, a recognition that it's a common

00:47:05.600 --> 00:47:06.720
[Guest 1]: journey.

00:47:06.720 --> 00:47:10.280
[Guest 1]: And everyone has different roles to play.

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:15.160
[Guest 1]: The end of the day, the government is the biggest funder of an activity like sport,

00:47:15.160 --> 00:47:23.360
[Guest 1]: huge amounts go into the other programs of athletes, high performance, tournament experts.

00:47:23.360 --> 00:47:30.480
[Guest 1]: But at the same time, like Joy mentions, the government is inherently obliged to be transactional.

00:47:30.480 --> 00:47:35.320
[Guest 1]: There are protocols it has to follow, there are ways of doing public money.

00:47:35.320 --> 00:47:41.640
[Guest 1]: So there's this room to build other things to focus and support the government, complement

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:46.640
[Guest 1]: the government doing things that the government cannot do, or is not yet ready to do.

00:47:46.640 --> 00:47:53.560
[Guest 1]: And in many ways, the private involvement is not by any means and a sort of a capture

00:47:53.560 --> 00:47:57.720
[Guest 1]: or should not be seen as something which you're doing, which the government should have been

00:47:57.720 --> 00:48:01.180
[Guest 1]: doing and you're trying to show the government office not doing it.

00:48:01.180 --> 00:48:07.920
[Guest 1]: And that's been the moment that has now come where it feels like everyone is participating

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:13.120
[Guest 1]: knows their role, and is actively pushing a common agenda.

00:48:13.120 --> 00:48:18.680
[Guest 1]: And a lot of that credit goes to the people running the top scheme and the sports ministry.

00:48:18.680 --> 00:48:25.560
[Guest 1]: That seven medals is actually an under reward for the amount of managerial work, the amount

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:29.160
[Guest 1]: of funding and the amount of support that our contingent got.

00:48:29.160 --> 00:48:36.240
[Guest 1]: I'm so glad that we got to seven, but not just the athletes, but everyone who put the

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:39.720
[Guest 1]: work in there, to me deserve more.

00:48:39.720 --> 00:48:45.840
[Guest 1]: And the fact that we expected more and feel like we deserve more tells the story that

00:48:45.840 --> 00:48:50.600
[Guest 1]: we had our best Olympics, but it could have been and should have been better.

00:48:50.600 --> 00:48:51.600
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous.

00:48:51.600 --> 00:48:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And I'll get to the details of that in a short while.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:57.040
[Amit Varma]: But there's a meta question I want to ask first, which is slightly long winded, if you

00:48:57.040 --> 00:49:01.880
[Amit Varma]: forgive me, but it's something that I haven't quite been able to reconcile for myself, which

00:49:01.880 --> 00:49:05.240
[Amit Varma]: is of state involvement in sport, right?

00:49:05.240 --> 00:49:09.280
[Amit Varma]: Which is that for all of these sports, we depend on the state and its federations and

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:10.280
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

00:49:10.280 --> 00:49:15.880
[Amit Varma]: And the point is, one has to wonder how that is sort of palatable or justifiable in a country

00:49:15.880 --> 00:49:21.080
[Amit Varma]: like India, like in India, 3000 children die in India every day from starvation, one in

00:49:21.080 --> 00:49:23.080
[Amit Varma]: four Indian children are malnourished.

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:27.360
[Amit Varma]: This is modern data, we are a desperately poor country, there's an opportunity cost

00:49:27.360 --> 00:49:28.360
[Amit Varma]: for money.

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And the question is that, is it okay to spend it on a space program or on sports?

00:49:33.600 --> 00:49:37.400
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, in my opinion, every reasonable person can argue that we should not be building

00:49:37.400 --> 00:49:38.800
[Amit Varma]: giant statues.

00:49:38.800 --> 00:49:42.520
[Amit Varma]: But it becomes more thorny when you talk about sports and space programs, because national

00:49:42.520 --> 00:49:44.200
[Amit Varma]: pride is tied in with them.

00:49:44.200 --> 00:49:48.280
[Amit Varma]: And this reminds me of a story that I sometimes tell about Tolstoy and his chicken.

00:49:48.280 --> 00:49:53.600
[Amit Varma]: So essentially, Tolstoy, of course, was vegetarian, and he wrote books about ethical treatment

00:49:53.600 --> 00:49:55.140
[Amit Varma]: of animals and all of that.

00:49:55.140 --> 00:49:58.480
[Amit Varma]: So at one point in time, an aunt of his was coming to dinner.

00:49:58.480 --> 00:50:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And she said, I will only eat chicken.

00:50:00.960 --> 00:50:02.560
[Amit Varma]: So he said, Okay, fine, come.

00:50:02.560 --> 00:50:06.400
[Amit Varma]: So when the aunt gets to the dining table, she finds that there is a live chicken flapping

00:50:06.400 --> 00:50:08.360
[Amit Varma]: about on her chair.

00:50:08.360 --> 00:50:11.800
[Amit Varma]: And Tolstoy tells her that you wanted chicken, here's your chicken, we're not going to kill

00:50:11.800 --> 00:50:14.000
[Amit Varma]: it for you, you do it yourself.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:17.800
[Amit Varma]: And that seems to me to be a very almost Gandhian demonstration.

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:22.280
[Amit Varma]: And Gandhi was, of course, influenced by Tolstoy, a Gandhian demonstration of the difference

00:50:22.280 --> 00:50:25.920
[Amit Varma]: between the chicken on the chair and the chicken on the plate, that they are actually one and

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:26.920
[Amit Varma]: the same.

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:29.520
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, we have this mental barrier between it.

00:50:29.520 --> 00:50:33.400
[Amit Varma]: And I think we do a similar thing in sport, where we think that government spending on

00:50:33.400 --> 00:50:38.280
[Amit Varma]: sport, you know, state funds going into, you know, athletics, and this and that is such

00:50:38.280 --> 00:50:40.600
[Amit Varma]: a beautiful, noble thing, and all of that.

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:42.000
[Amit Varma]: But there is a cost to it.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:46.760
[Amit Varma]: And the cost to it at some level, includes the 3000 children dying every day of starvation.

00:50:46.760 --> 00:50:50.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, obviously, it is not the case that if the government stopped funding, say, fencing,

00:50:50.720 --> 00:50:51.720
[Amit Varma]: children would stop dying.

00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:55.320
[Amit Varma]: That's obviously not the case, it would go into somebody's pocket for you know, but that's

00:50:55.320 --> 00:50:57.160
[Amit Varma]: a dilemma that we face.

00:50:57.160 --> 00:51:02.960
[Amit Varma]: And my sense is that this connection between the state and sport is really because of reasons

00:51:02.960 --> 00:51:07.120
[Amit Varma]: that can shade over that essentially has both sides to it.

00:51:07.120 --> 00:51:12.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, you could say that it is self respect and esteem of the kind that you know, we might

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:16.100
[Amit Varma]: have felt when we watch Gavaskar play all the defiant innings that he played.

00:51:16.100 --> 00:51:20.960
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, it's it's this kind of toxic nationalism, you know, Orwell famously

00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:23.760
[Amit Varma]: said, sport is war minus the shooting.

00:51:23.760 --> 00:51:29.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, so that's, you know, one counter view to the state in sport, that's kind of

00:51:29.080 --> 00:51:32.940
[Amit Varma]: the side that we don't see, I mean, this is a scene in the unseen, so to say, and a follow

00:51:32.940 --> 00:51:37.600
[Amit Varma]: up minor question that arises from that is you were drawing the comparison in that cartoon

00:51:37.600 --> 00:51:39.340
[Amit Varma]: between football and javelin.

00:51:39.340 --> 00:51:43.080
[Amit Varma]: And the point is, why will the kid kicking the ball makes him so much more money, it's

00:51:43.080 --> 00:51:47.120
[Amit Varma]: because so many more people watch the sport, they care about football, they deeply care

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:48.120
[Amit Varma]: about it.

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:49.520
[Amit Varma]: And there's a lot of money going into it.

00:51:49.520 --> 00:51:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's our eyeballs that are directly funding all the sports that we watch, which I'm perfectly

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.080
[Amit Varma]: fine with, as it should be.

00:51:56.080 --> 00:52:02.640
[Amit Varma]: But you could also argue that a lot of sports, these Olympic sports are perhaps archaic artifacts

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:07.360
[Amit Varma]: that you know, no one would watch if it wasn't for this whole thing of national pride through

00:52:07.360 --> 00:52:09.120
[Amit Varma]: sporting expression.

00:52:09.120 --> 00:52:11.160
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not taking a stand one way or the other.

00:52:11.160 --> 00:52:14.200
[Amit Varma]: I'm raising this because I'm conflicted about it.

00:52:14.200 --> 00:52:18.120
[Amit Varma]: Because to me, one of my best moments this year was, you know, when Neeraj won the gold

00:52:18.120 --> 00:52:22.360
[Amit Varma]: or other things that I've seen in sport that I otherwise wouldn't, you know, if not for

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:25.960
[Amit Varma]: this, but at the same time, there is this other aspect of it, how does one reconcile

00:52:25.960 --> 00:52:26.960
[Amit Varma]: these two?

00:52:26.960 --> 00:52:28.920
[Amit Varma]: Is this something that you've thought about?

00:52:28.920 --> 00:52:35.320
[Amit Varma]: And also, Nandan, specifically in your case, where you've done so much work, sort of mobilizing

00:52:35.320 --> 00:52:40.160
[Amit Varma]: the voluntary action of private individuals towards promoting sport, which is kind of

00:52:40.160 --> 00:52:45.400
[Amit Varma]: the way I would really love to see all of it happen, that is there a way of seeing sport

00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:51.160
[Amit Varma]: go forward without the necessary involvement of the state, as it is in some sports in other

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:54.880
[Amit Varma]: countries, you know, like the British government doesn't have to promote football, you know,

00:52:54.880 --> 00:52:59.280
[Amit Varma]: the Premier League is all there, you know, even the BCCI is kind of independent, and

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:01.400
[Amit Varma]: the IPL is its own ecosystem.

00:53:01.400 --> 00:53:05.940
[Amit Varma]: But with other sports, we have to always think of the state getting involved.

00:53:05.940 --> 00:53:08.240
[Amit Varma]: So what are your respective thoughts on this?

00:53:08.240 --> 00:53:12.640
[Guest 1]: It's a great question, Amit, because it's at the center of I think, the future of Indian

00:53:12.640 --> 00:53:13.640
[Guest 1]: sport as well.

00:53:13.640 --> 00:53:20.480
[Guest 1]: We do have this notion that if anything goes wrong in sport, it's the government's fault.

00:53:20.480 --> 00:53:24.840
[Guest 1]: So I mean, someone like runs with a bull and supposedly runs faster than Usain Bolt, the

00:53:24.840 --> 00:53:29.800
[Guest 1]: sports minister is supposed to call him for a trial, someone, I mean, it's literally everything

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:33.480
[Guest 1]: that happens is the government's responsibility with sport.

00:53:33.480 --> 00:53:37.480
[Guest 1]: And that's how also a lot of these schemes have been built, there's the government is

00:53:37.480 --> 00:53:42.440
[Guest 1]: building the Kilo India youth games, university games, there's a talent scouting, there's

00:53:42.440 --> 00:53:48.320
[Guest 1]: sports hostels, infrastructure, name it, and the government is the biggest sports management

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:50.400
[Guest 1]: company in the country.

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:55.720
[Guest 1]: The reality is that a lot of this in the sports governance structure, international sports

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:59.520
[Guest 1]: governance structure is to be done by federations.

00:53:59.520 --> 00:54:06.800
[Guest 1]: And we haven't got there yet in transferring in some sense responsibility, but also operational

00:54:06.800 --> 00:54:11.540
[Guest 1]: integrity to our federations in a cogent, clear way.

00:54:11.540 --> 00:54:14.320
[Guest 1]: Because we've been so government centric, when you ask the government, government will

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:18.120
[Guest 1]: deliver because that's what the population is asking for.

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:23.640
[Guest 1]: What we haven't moved towards is the US model, the US Olympic and Paralympic Committee gets

00:54:23.640 --> 00:54:26.560
[Guest 1]: probably zero funding from the government.

00:54:26.560 --> 00:54:32.840
[Guest 1]: It is also all sponsor driven, all driven by private enterprise, pushed up by university

00:54:32.840 --> 00:54:35.040
[Guest 1]: sport, Europe has club sport.

00:54:35.040 --> 00:54:41.240
[Guest 1]: So we found micro enterprises, we found sponsors, we found boosters in different places.

00:54:41.240 --> 00:54:47.720
[Guest 1]: For us, other than the BCCI, the government, some state governments are the funder of first

00:54:47.720 --> 00:54:50.640
[Guest 1]: resort and the funder of last resort.

00:54:50.640 --> 00:54:57.320
[Guest 1]: What it does in some sense is it absolves also a lot of the federations of responsibility,

00:54:57.320 --> 00:55:01.520
[Guest 1]: because of the way that the sports governance framework has been built, not to say that

00:55:01.520 --> 00:55:03.080
[Guest 1]: all federations are run badly.

00:55:03.080 --> 00:55:08.560
[Guest 1]: And I think you saw the results of some well run federations, transformative results in

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:12.800
[Guest 1]: the Olympics as well, including hockey, which I'm sure we'll talk about a little bit more.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:16.120
[Guest 1]: But the reality is there are dozens and dozens of federations.

00:55:16.120 --> 00:55:20.040
[Guest 1]: And I mean, we've had many conferences on this and one of our speakers talked about

00:55:20.040 --> 00:55:25.280
[Guest 1]: a bunch of these federations called kitchen table governance, where literally the president

00:55:25.280 --> 00:55:29.160
[Guest 1]: and secretary sit in someone's kitchen and run the federation.

00:55:29.160 --> 00:55:34.160
[Guest 1]: And there are really no implications for that worldwide federations are supposed to be private

00:55:34.160 --> 00:55:38.240
[Guest 1]: autonomous bodies, which may get some funding from the government.

00:55:38.240 --> 00:55:43.640
[Guest 1]: But that autonomy is to be enjoyed with certain responsibilities to run tournaments to run

00:55:43.640 --> 00:55:45.880
[Guest 1]: events to do talent scouting.

00:55:45.880 --> 00:55:51.960
[Guest 1]: So essentially, to deliver talent opportunities, and to convert talent into opportunities and

00:55:51.960 --> 00:55:54.740
[Guest 1]: opportunities into competitiveness.

00:55:54.740 --> 00:55:59.800
[Guest 1]: And that is where we in some sense have failed when the government doesn't enforce a governance

00:55:59.800 --> 00:56:03.120
[Guest 1]: framework where that autonomy is earned.

00:56:03.120 --> 00:56:07.960
[Guest 1]: What you end up doing is the government doing all of it in itself, because one constant

00:56:07.960 --> 00:56:12.760
[Guest 1]: there, whether the federations do it or the government does it, it's government's money.

00:56:12.760 --> 00:56:17.080
[Guest 1]: So either the government's fund the federations, or they do the schemes themselves.

00:56:17.080 --> 00:56:22.080
[Guest 1]: Now what what happens is, if you're given that binary choice, saying it's your money,

00:56:22.080 --> 00:56:29.680
[Guest 1]: you can either go and execute Halo India games, talent scouting, sports hostels, big infrastructure,

00:56:29.680 --> 00:56:34.580
[Guest 1]: yourself and have accountability, or you can pass it on to others, and you may get a report

00:56:34.580 --> 00:56:38.520
[Guest 1]: once a year, if you're lucky, which is the one you're going to choose, right.

00:56:38.520 --> 00:56:44.240
[Guest 1]: And to me, there is a gap and perhaps Joy can talk a little bit more about it in our

00:56:44.240 --> 00:56:49.760
[Guest 1]: willingness to sort of call out federations who aren't doing their job, because at the

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:54.140
[Guest 1]: end of the day, these federations are monopolies by law.

00:56:54.140 --> 00:56:58.480
[Guest 1]: And these are not monopolies created by Indian law or any national law.

00:56:58.480 --> 00:57:01.720
[Guest 1]: These are self professed monopolies worldwide.

00:57:01.720 --> 00:57:06.860
[Guest 1]: So they get their recognition from international bodies, which are also not tied to any country.

00:57:06.860 --> 00:57:12.300
[Guest 1]: So they are recognized by the International Federation and claim some like serious dominion

00:57:12.300 --> 00:57:17.200
[Guest 1]: over the sport, where you can't move, you can't enter this what is called the sports

00:57:17.200 --> 00:57:19.600
[Guest 1]: pyramid without their permission.

00:57:19.600 --> 00:57:24.880
[Guest 1]: Now when you're running a monopoly, that monopoly with an autonomy is a pretty sort of challenging

00:57:24.880 --> 00:57:29.380
[Guest 1]: dish to serve if you don't have responsibility tied to that.

00:57:29.380 --> 00:57:34.800
[Guest 1]: So are you handing over the keys to an entire gamut of activities, from doing events to

00:57:34.800 --> 00:57:40.000
[Guest 1]: selecting determining who represents India using the national flag, and in some sense,

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:44.180
[Guest 1]: curating identity of what we are capable of and what we are not.

00:57:44.180 --> 00:57:47.160
[Guest 1]: And some of it could just be simply from inaction.

00:57:47.160 --> 00:57:50.360
[Guest 1]: So are you saying that you're going to hand over the keys and you're not you don't care

00:57:50.360 --> 00:57:52.800
[Guest 1]: if the person starts the engine, right?

00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:54.640
[Guest 1]: And that is where there are gaps.

00:57:54.640 --> 00:57:58.880
[Guest 1]: And if we want to move from this government funded, we will do everything because people

00:57:58.880 --> 00:58:05.120
[Guest 1]: expect us to do we will enable build the legal frameworks and I'm a lawyer and I'll always

00:58:05.120 --> 00:58:10.800
[Guest 1]: come from that, build the infrastructure that needs to be built that I mean, land and power

00:58:10.800 --> 00:58:15.720
[Guest 1]: of the state are the only things that the state really has monopoly over, get experts

00:58:15.720 --> 00:58:18.600
[Guest 1]: to do the work of each sport.

00:58:18.600 --> 00:58:22.120
[Guest 1]: But that is going to come you're going to get private participation, you're going to

00:58:22.120 --> 00:58:28.780
[Guest 1]: get private enterprise, when there is accountability and responsibility, and a fair chance to participate

00:58:28.780 --> 00:58:34.720
[Guest 1]: on decent terms for private enterprise to come in and not get kicked out in two or three

00:58:34.720 --> 00:58:39.640
[Guest 1]: years because something else has grown better or that investment is not protected.

00:58:39.640 --> 00:58:44.920
[Guest 1]: And we've seen so many examples of this in Indian sport, multiple leagues, multiple different

00:58:44.920 --> 00:58:50.440
[Guest 1]: examples where private enterprise, you come and take the risk, if it turns out well, we

00:58:50.440 --> 00:58:52.920
[Guest 1]: will co-opt and we don't need you anymore.

00:58:52.920 --> 00:58:57.280
[Guest 1]: If you're losing money, keep continuing to lose money and we're thankful to you.

00:58:57.280 --> 00:59:00.480
[Guest 1]: And I'm sure Joy has a lot to say on this topic.

00:59:00.480 --> 00:59:02.120
[Guest 2]: No, absolutely.

00:59:02.120 --> 00:59:07.920
[Guest 2]: And I think where I'm going to start off, first and foremost, you know, every year,

00:59:07.920 --> 00:59:08.920
[Guest 2]: there's a dance.

00:59:08.920 --> 00:59:09.920
[Guest 2]: Okay.

00:59:09.920 --> 00:59:15.760
[Guest 2]: It's a dance between what they call SAI and the Ministry of Sports and the federations.

00:59:15.760 --> 00:59:16.760
[Guest 2]: Okay.

00:59:16.760 --> 00:59:23.000
[Guest 2]: So SAI and the Ministry of Sport have a particular budget to dole out to federations.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:26.880
[Amit Varma]: For my listeners, we should elaborate SAI is a sports authority of India.

00:59:26.880 --> 00:59:28.400
[Guest 2]: Sports authority of India.

00:59:28.400 --> 00:59:33.080
[Guest 2]: So every year, all these federations go out there and they have their plans and they say,

00:59:33.080 --> 00:59:35.600
[Guest 2]: this is what we're going to do, give us some money.

00:59:35.600 --> 00:59:36.600
[Guest 2]: Okay.

00:59:36.600 --> 00:59:41.560
[Guest 2]: And 90% of the federations will get money from no other source other than this.

00:59:41.560 --> 00:59:44.880
[Guest 2]: You know, they'll put out an auction to say, where will we hold the nationals?

00:59:44.880 --> 00:59:48.080
[Guest 2]: And somebody who will do the nationals because, you know, they want to do it this year and

00:59:48.080 --> 00:59:50.520
[Guest 2]: they want to be probably president next year.

00:59:50.520 --> 00:59:53.420
[Guest 2]: And they'll do it in a particular city and they'll do it in a particular way.

00:59:53.420 --> 00:59:55.400
[Guest 2]: This is the cycle followed.

00:59:55.400 --> 00:59:59.160
[Guest 2]: So I just want to tell you about something about the federation, which is actually fairly

00:59:59.160 --> 01:00:02.800
[Guest 2]: well done because I've worked with it, which is the football federation.

01:00:02.800 --> 01:00:07.120
[Guest 2]: And I remember in 2015, we were working on the under 17 football world cup.

01:00:07.120 --> 01:00:11.680
[Guest 2]: And so we were required to present to the All India Football Federation general body

01:00:11.680 --> 01:00:14.000
[Guest 2]: meeting that, you know, how is the world cup progressing?

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:16.000
[Guest 2]: So we are there for the meeting.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.760
[Guest 2]: And just before us, there's a few points of order.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:23.320
[Guest 2]: So the general secretary of the football federation turns around and says, and Baitung Bhutia

01:00:23.320 --> 01:00:24.320
[Guest 2]: is there at the meeting.

01:00:24.320 --> 01:00:29.160
[Guest 2]: And I think he's also there for some other reason to talk about some of the projects.

01:00:29.160 --> 01:00:33.600
[Guest 2]: And mind you, so all these guys who have come to this meeting are guys who have been flown

01:00:33.600 --> 01:00:36.240
[Guest 2]: in by the All India Football Federation.

01:00:36.240 --> 01:00:39.400
[Guest 2]: They'll stay for two days at a hotel, they'll attend these meetings and they'll go back.

01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:43.840
[Guest 2]: Maybe each of them, you know, each state, probably a lakh of rupees is being spent just

01:00:43.840 --> 01:00:45.120
[Guest 2]: to bring them here.

01:00:45.120 --> 01:00:49.400
[Guest 2]: So one of the points of order was that they said that, you know, the registration fees

01:00:49.400 --> 01:00:57.400
[Guest 2]: for each local federation is 500 rupees, 500 rupees a year for a local state federation.

01:00:57.400 --> 01:01:00.200
[Guest 2]: And they said that, you know, that has to be increased because, you know, there's a

01:01:00.200 --> 01:01:03.920
[Guest 2]: lot of paperwork, you're increasing it to 10,000 rupees a year because, you know, that's

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:05.600
[Guest 2]: about how much.

01:01:05.600 --> 01:01:10.960
[Guest 2]: And four federations, including India's most popular state, caught up and said, how can

01:01:10.960 --> 01:01:11.960
[Guest 2]: you do that?

01:01:11.960 --> 01:01:12.960
[Guest 2]: 10,000 rupees?

01:01:12.960 --> 01:01:13.960
[Guest 2]: How can we afford it?

01:01:13.960 --> 01:01:18.920
[Guest 2]: And at that point, Baitung Bhutia, who was there, he just could not believe it.

01:01:18.920 --> 01:01:25.680
[Guest 2]: And he says that, you know, if in India's most popular state, the world's most popular

01:01:25.680 --> 01:01:31.600
[Guest 2]: game cannot raise 10,000 rupees, then probably the wrong people are running it.

01:01:31.600 --> 01:01:33.720
[Guest 2]: And there was chaos in that meeting and everything.

01:01:33.720 --> 01:01:36.160
[Guest 2]: But that was so absolutely true.

01:01:36.160 --> 01:01:38.160
[Guest 2]: I'll tell you something, Amit.

01:01:38.160 --> 01:01:42.260
[Guest 2]: A lot of the people who are running these federations and a lot of, they are good federations

01:01:42.260 --> 01:01:46.520
[Guest 2]: as Nandan will, you know, hasten to tell you and as I will, okay.

01:01:46.520 --> 01:01:50.880
[Guest 2]: But in 90 percent of cases, it's not just the fact that the federations are corrupt

01:01:50.880 --> 01:01:51.880
[Guest 2]: because they are.

01:01:51.880 --> 01:01:52.880
[Guest 2]: Many of them are corrupt.

01:01:52.880 --> 01:01:57.240
[Guest 2]: But in a lot of cases, they are just unable.

01:01:57.240 --> 01:02:01.880
[Guest 2]: So if you turn on and give a federation two crores and say, okay, do a national game which

01:02:01.880 --> 01:02:05.880
[Guest 2]: is proper, they wouldn't know how to do it because they don't know how to deal with those

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:07.160
[Guest 2]: kinds of sums of money.

01:02:07.160 --> 01:02:08.920
[Guest 2]: They don't know how to scale up.

01:02:08.920 --> 01:02:11.360
[Guest 2]: A lot of them don't know how to use a computer properly.

01:02:11.360 --> 01:02:14.120
[Guest 2]: A lot of them wouldn't be able to use an Excel sheet.

01:02:14.120 --> 01:02:18.920
[Guest 2]: So the problem is that Indian sport is hugely undermined by the federations.

01:02:18.920 --> 01:02:21.160
[Guest 2]: And I'll tell you why this has happened.

01:02:21.160 --> 01:02:26.400
[Guest 2]: In early days, you know, suppose your table tennis, okay, now table tennis was played

01:02:26.400 --> 01:02:28.600
[Guest 2]: and there were certain places, you know.

01:02:28.600 --> 01:02:31.880
[Guest 2]: So Maharashtra had some table tennis, Kerala had some table tennis, Bengal had some table

01:02:31.880 --> 01:02:34.680
[Guest 2]: tennis, railways had some table tennis.

01:02:34.680 --> 01:02:38.360
[Guest 2]: The other states, they were not that strong in table tennis, Assam had some table tennis.

01:02:38.360 --> 01:02:42.100
[Guest 2]: What would happen is suppose your Uttarakhand table tennis.

01:02:42.100 --> 01:02:47.600
[Guest 2]: So somebody who wants to win the next elections inside the Table Tennis Federation would ask

01:02:47.600 --> 01:02:51.880
[Guest 2]: a cousin or relative, somebody in Uttarakhand and say, hey, do you want to be the head of

01:02:51.880 --> 01:02:55.000
[Guest 2]: the Uttarakhand Table Tennis Federation?

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:56.000
[Guest 2]: And they'll think, hey, why not?

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:59.160
[Guest 2]: They said, look, you're going to come down for the national games, you'll get a couple

01:02:59.160 --> 01:03:02.520
[Guest 2]: of free trips a year, all you need to do is vote for me.

01:03:02.520 --> 01:03:05.980
[Guest 2]: And you don't really need to know anything about table tennis.

01:03:05.980 --> 01:03:12.800
[Guest 2]: So that's how a lot of these state federations sort of started putting their own people in,

01:03:12.800 --> 01:03:16.800
[Guest 2]: voters in, often who had nothing to do with the game.

01:03:16.800 --> 01:03:19.400
[Guest 2]: And what we are dealing with is still that system.

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:25.040
[Guest 2]: We are dealing with that system, those people, and therefore also one incompetent people,

01:03:25.040 --> 01:03:30.120
[Guest 2]: be people who don't know the game, see people who have no idea what to do if money actually

01:03:30.120 --> 01:03:33.360
[Guest 2]: comes into the sport because they're not capable of running.

01:03:33.360 --> 01:03:36.480
[Guest 2]: And those are the essential problems that we are dealing with.

01:03:36.480 --> 01:03:40.560
[Guest 2]: As I said, you know, Nandan will tell you, at this point in time, I don't think the lack

01:03:40.560 --> 01:03:44.200
[Guest 2]: of money is India's problem at all in sport.

01:03:44.200 --> 01:03:45.200
[Guest 2]: There is enough money.

01:03:45.200 --> 01:03:48.680
[Guest 2]: And if you go to the private sector, and you tell them that, okay, this is a project we

01:03:48.680 --> 01:03:52.720
[Guest 2]: can do, and this is a project, these are the deliverables, and this is how we can do it,

01:03:52.720 --> 01:03:54.400
[Guest 2]: you can raise the money.

01:03:54.400 --> 01:03:59.560
[Guest 2]: It's lack of competency, it's the federations who are the roadblocks.

01:03:59.560 --> 01:04:04.200
[Amit Varma]: So you know, extremely insightful points, and speaking of lack of competency, speaking

01:04:04.200 --> 01:04:07.520
[Amit Varma]: about people who might not know what to do if the money comes to them.

01:04:07.520 --> 01:04:11.840
[Amit Varma]: And also the very valid point that you made that these are not necessarily bad people.

01:04:11.840 --> 01:04:14.800
[Amit Varma]: All of this gets me to thinking about structure and incentives.

01:04:14.800 --> 01:04:18.160
[Amit Varma]: And this is something I think we might have discussed in the last episode we did together

01:04:18.160 --> 01:04:19.640
[Amit Varma]: and Nandan just alluded to it.

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:24.560
[Amit Varma]: So as you know, Nandan mentioned, all our federations through accidents of circumstances

01:04:24.560 --> 01:04:28.200
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, the way sporting federations throughout the world have evolved is that

01:04:28.200 --> 01:04:31.400
[Amit Varma]: one they are monopolies, two they are also monopsonies.

01:04:31.400 --> 01:04:36.520
[Amit Varma]: So not only will say the Federation of archery have a monopoly on archery, anyone who wants

01:04:36.520 --> 01:04:40.920
[Amit Varma]: to do archery has to, you know, register with the Federation and play under their auspices

01:04:40.920 --> 01:04:42.120
[Amit Varma]: or whatever.

01:04:42.120 --> 01:04:48.340
[Amit Varma]: But they also have no one else to sell their services to, which makes them incredibly powerful.

01:04:48.340 --> 01:04:51.640
[Amit Varma]: And without any accountability, where does accountability come from, it typically comes

01:04:51.640 --> 01:04:52.640
[Amit Varma]: from competition.

01:04:52.640 --> 01:04:56.800
[Amit Varma]: Now, in this case, within their sport, their monopolies and monopsonies, you could argue

01:04:56.800 --> 01:04:59.760
[Amit Varma]: that each sport is competing with every other sport.

01:04:59.760 --> 01:05:02.040
[Amit Varma]: So that might be a kind of accountability.

01:05:02.040 --> 01:05:07.440
[Amit Varma]: But that plays out only over the long run, and is no relief to say a current archer who

01:05:07.440 --> 01:05:11.680
[Amit Varma]: finds that you know, there is deep nepotism within his federation or whatever.

01:05:11.680 --> 01:05:17.120
[Amit Varma]: Also, as far as the question of autonomy and accountability come, this becomes a very difficult

01:05:17.120 --> 01:05:21.840
[Amit Varma]: balance, I would imagine, because, you know, a government can say that, okay, ex federation,

01:05:21.840 --> 01:05:23.460
[Amit Varma]: you are now autonomous.

01:05:23.460 --> 01:05:27.120
[Amit Varma]: But to keep you accountable, these are the following reporting procedures you will have

01:05:27.120 --> 01:05:31.160
[Amit Varma]: to follow or benchmarks you will have to meet, because that still gives the state a certain

01:05:31.160 --> 01:05:34.000
[Amit Varma]: amount of power over them and power always corrupts.

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And these inevitably become sort of rent seeking operations.

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:42.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, what we saw on cricket and where the IPL was so good, is that the IPL proved a

01:05:42.680 --> 01:05:47.200
[Amit Varma]: jugaadu way out of the monopsony problem, that if you were a cricketer, you weren't

01:05:47.200 --> 01:05:51.800
[Amit Varma]: only selling your talent to the BCCI, you could sell your talent separately to, you

01:05:51.800 --> 01:05:57.360
[Amit Varma]: know, Mumbai Indians or Royal Challengers or whatever, you had these people competing

01:05:57.360 --> 01:05:59.240
[Amit Varma]: for your services.

01:05:59.240 --> 01:06:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And you also had these people competing to discover new talent, because that's how the

01:06:04.320 --> 01:06:06.800
[Amit Varma]: incentives suddenly worked in that new structure.

01:06:06.800 --> 01:06:11.880
[Amit Varma]: So you still had BCCI, which is a monopoly and a monopsony and which used that monopsonistic

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:16.640
[Amit Varma]: power to shut down the ICL, for example, and to make sure no one would compete with it.

01:06:16.640 --> 01:06:21.160
[Amit Varma]: But you know, that jugaadu set up within it of the IPL, where there is competition on

01:06:21.160 --> 01:06:26.240
[Amit Varma]: all fronts, made the lives of so many Indian cricketers much better off to the extent that

01:06:26.240 --> 01:06:30.440
[Amit Varma]: I imagine if the IPL had been around when you had to make a difficult choice, then you

01:06:30.440 --> 01:06:34.720
[Amit Varma]: might well have thought, okay, no, there are so many options, I'll just continue with cricket.

01:06:34.720 --> 01:06:35.720
[Amit Varma]: One doesn't know.

01:06:35.720 --> 01:06:38.920
[Amit Varma]: But on the margins, I think that would be the kind of difference that they could be

01:06:38.920 --> 01:06:39.920
[Amit Varma]: there.

01:06:39.920 --> 01:06:43.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, how do we get past this is what I kind of don't understand.

01:06:43.920 --> 01:06:47.840
[Amit Varma]: Because it seems to me that these structures are things that we are stuck with.

01:06:47.840 --> 01:06:50.040
[Amit Varma]: And this is not a uniquely Indian problem.

01:06:50.040 --> 01:06:55.700
[Amit Varma]: Of course, because rent seeking is so natural and inherent to our entire systems of governance.

01:06:55.700 --> 01:06:56.960
[Amit Varma]: This just fits into that.

01:06:56.960 --> 01:07:01.960
[Amit Varma]: But this problem of federations, which are monopoly and monopsony are true, all across

01:07:01.960 --> 01:07:04.760
[Amit Varma]: the world, it just permeates through.

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:07.020
[Amit Varma]: So what are the ways through that?

01:07:07.020 --> 01:07:12.840
[Amit Varma]: Is there a point at which this just becomes something that we have to excel in spite of?

01:07:12.840 --> 01:07:18.480
[Amit Varma]: Or is it possible to reform the system in structural ways that I possibly, you know,

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:21.800
[Amit Varma]: can't imagine, but you're a lawyer, and then you've thought about the structural aspects

01:07:21.800 --> 01:07:26.680
[Amit Varma]: of this, obviously, and how rules of the game can reform a system like this.

01:07:26.680 --> 01:07:30.880
[Amit Varma]: So I'd love insights from both of you, because both of you have, you know, while I am really

01:07:30.880 --> 01:07:35.040
[Amit Varma]: spouting theory right now, both of you have been on the ground, no doubt, you know, running

01:07:35.040 --> 01:07:39.360
[Amit Varma]: into countless frustrations dealing with these federations and, you know, coming from people

01:07:39.360 --> 01:07:43.720
[Amit Varma]: who are otherwise perfectly good human beings and good individuals and well meaning people,

01:07:43.720 --> 01:07:46.240
[Amit Varma]: but they're responding to the incentives of the system.

01:07:46.240 --> 01:07:49.440
[Guest 1]: Yeah, Amit, great question.

01:07:49.440 --> 01:07:50.760
[Guest 1]: It's not an easy answer.

01:07:50.760 --> 01:07:57.360
[Guest 1]: I will have to preface by saying governance is an incredibly difficult job in sport.

01:07:57.360 --> 01:08:00.720
[Guest 1]: Sport in general has so many different stakeholders.

01:08:00.720 --> 01:08:05.320
[Guest 1]: And everyone is coming with different interests, very, very different interests.

01:08:05.320 --> 01:08:08.880
[Guest 1]: So an athlete may have an interest, the parent may have a completely different interest from

01:08:08.880 --> 01:08:10.040
[Guest 1]: the athlete.

01:08:10.040 --> 01:08:14.200
[Guest 1]: So might the coach, you'll have teams, you have federations, you have the government,

01:08:14.200 --> 01:08:18.680
[Guest 1]: you have private enterprise, you have sponsors trying to come in, you have broadcasters.

01:08:18.680 --> 01:08:25.360
[Guest 1]: So there's a whole bunch of people consider it people trying to take from some sort of

01:08:25.360 --> 01:08:27.000
[Guest 1]: a pot.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:31.280
[Guest 1]: And there's a there's a great story that Rahul Dravid tells about what a team environment

01:08:31.280 --> 01:08:32.280
[Guest 1]: is about.

01:08:32.280 --> 01:08:38.480
[Guest 1]: He talks about it being a pot of energy, which every individual has to give to so that they

01:08:38.480 --> 01:08:43.200
[Guest 1]: can take from right and particularly relevant, I think in a sport like cricket, which is

01:08:43.200 --> 01:08:46.400
[Guest 1]: an individual sport in a team environment.

01:08:46.400 --> 01:08:51.080
[Guest 1]: And that is really what sport is, is that there are multiple people trying to give a

01:08:51.080 --> 01:08:53.800
[Guest 1]: little and take a lot from sport.

01:08:53.800 --> 01:08:55.160
[Guest 1]: And what is governance?

01:08:55.160 --> 01:09:01.200
[Guest 1]: Governance is balancing these various interests in the sort of keeping the interests of sport,

01:09:01.200 --> 01:09:06.500
[Guest 1]: this sort of mythical beast, the interest of sport as the priority.

01:09:06.500 --> 01:09:10.180
[Guest 1]: So you will take the money from the broadcaster, but what sort of rights will you give the

01:09:10.180 --> 01:09:11.920
[Guest 1]: broadcaster in return?

01:09:11.920 --> 01:09:17.360
[Guest 1]: You will allow the athlete an opportunity to train, but what if the athlete is not doing

01:09:17.360 --> 01:09:18.680
[Guest 1]: things sincerely?

01:09:18.680 --> 01:09:24.960
[Guest 1]: So there's constantly people trying to give less and take more from sport.

01:09:24.960 --> 01:09:29.120
[Guest 1]: And in general, really sport determines when you get something back, you really can't be

01:09:29.120 --> 01:09:30.760
[Guest 1]: extractive.

01:09:30.760 --> 01:09:37.680
[Guest 1]: And the issue is when you have governance in a way that is not structured with accountability,

01:09:37.680 --> 01:09:43.360
[Guest 1]: the ability to be extractive with participation of people who are in the federations goes

01:09:43.360 --> 01:09:44.360
[Guest 1]: up.

01:09:44.360 --> 01:09:50.900
[Guest 1]: So already a difficult task with some misaligned incentives.

01:09:50.900 --> 01:09:57.540
[Guest 1]: What has changed in more recent years is the emergence of the sort of excellent athlete

01:09:57.540 --> 01:10:02.080
[Guest 1]: from federations who have really not maybe done that much in time as well.

01:10:02.080 --> 01:10:06.960
[Guest 1]: And to me, a little bit of this competition issue was solved by this target Olympic podium

01:10:06.960 --> 01:10:10.700
[Guest 1]: scheme, which was really agnostic to which sport you came from.

01:10:10.700 --> 01:10:17.300
[Guest 1]: If you showed Olympic qualification or podium potential, they would pick you and then also

01:10:17.300 --> 01:10:20.600
[Guest 1]: work with the federation to make sure everything was okay.

01:10:20.600 --> 01:10:26.440
[Guest 1]: So it became almost an Indian Olympic program, which didn't go into priority sport, which

01:10:26.440 --> 01:10:30.620
[Guest 1]: federation, it looked at each athlete as an individual.

01:10:30.620 --> 01:10:34.200
[Guest 1]: What it did is it brought people together and said, come and help us.

01:10:34.200 --> 01:10:37.080
[Guest 1]: Do you have an athlete in some sense that deserves this?

01:10:37.080 --> 01:10:38.280
[Guest 1]: Come and present.

01:10:38.280 --> 01:10:41.880
[Guest 1]: We've had wonderful cases of people who have never qualified for the Olympics before from

01:10:41.880 --> 01:10:46.120
[Guest 1]: their sport now progressively come from a foundation like ours.

01:10:46.120 --> 01:10:49.320
[Guest 1]: So we had the first fencer make it to the Olympics.

01:10:49.320 --> 01:10:54.800
[Guest 1]: That person got a chance because, this is we're talking about Bhavani Devi, because

01:10:54.800 --> 01:10:56.920
[Guest 1]: the Tamil Nadu state government supported her.

01:10:56.920 --> 01:11:01.960
[Guest 1]: We as a foundation supported her at a point when she was considering quitting sport.

01:11:01.960 --> 01:11:05.640
[Guest 1]: And I think she's gone on record to say we had the selection interview.

01:11:05.640 --> 01:11:09.880
[Guest 1]: If we had not selected her and she didn't expect to be selected because fencing and

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:13.320
[Guest 1]: why fencing, she was going to quit the sport.

01:11:13.320 --> 01:11:17.640
[Guest 1]: And the reality is for five or six years, we worked with her, the government, and eventually

01:11:17.640 --> 01:11:23.320
[Guest 1]: the top scheme took over, which is a fantastic public private collaboration, because it was

01:11:23.320 --> 01:11:29.200
[Guest 1]: something that the government could not have really funded when you have 150 other athletes

01:11:29.200 --> 01:11:31.380
[Guest 1]: in line above her.

01:11:31.380 --> 01:11:35.040
[Guest 1]: Why would you pick a fencer when India's never qualified at fencing?

01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:41.520
[Guest 1]: So what you got was in some sense, this Jugaadu, like the equivalent of an IPL, multiple different

01:11:41.520 --> 01:11:44.920
[Guest 1]: people trying to solve problems together.

01:11:44.920 --> 01:11:50.000
[Guest 1]: In some sense, problems that could not be solved by the other was solved and handed

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:55.120
[Guest 1]: over in a way that when the person was ready for that support.

01:11:55.120 --> 01:12:00.040
[Guest 1]: So in some sense, the success of these last six or seven years has been that collaboration

01:12:00.040 --> 01:12:05.760
[Guest 1]: between the private and the public, the Federation's recognizing a little bit more that having

01:12:05.760 --> 01:12:09.960
[Guest 1]: an excellent high performance athlete is not always a threat.

01:12:09.960 --> 01:12:12.960
[Guest 1]: And I think it's an opportunity as well to grow your sport.

01:12:12.960 --> 01:12:17.360
[Guest 1]: I know it sounds absurd when I say that, I mean, you would expect you want top class

01:12:17.360 --> 01:12:21.400
[Guest 1]: athletes, but many of them are just happy to not be in the limelight to just do their

01:12:21.400 --> 01:12:26.640
[Guest 1]: own thing along the side, travel to the Olympics, even if you don't have a athlete at the Olympics,

01:12:26.640 --> 01:12:30.160
[Guest 1]: you might be handball Federation or something that you're going to the Olympics without

01:12:30.160 --> 01:12:31.440
[Guest 1]: a team there.

01:12:31.440 --> 01:12:37.920
[Guest 1]: But suddenly you have an athlete, there's a gradual recognition of the opportunity a

01:12:37.920 --> 01:12:42.160
[Guest 1]: prime athlete in a sport sort of can deliver.

01:12:42.160 --> 01:12:46.880
[Guest 1]: And we've seen that in many ways, you look at it as the athlete as sort of top of the

01:12:46.880 --> 01:12:52.320
[Guest 1]: pyramid in an ecosystem in the way that you have sort of a predator, the health of the

01:12:52.320 --> 01:12:54.360
[Guest 1]: predators, the health of the system.

01:12:54.360 --> 01:13:00.120
[Guest 1]: And we've seen like you take a fencer, you suddenly expose the system to a fencer.

01:13:00.120 --> 01:13:01.480
[Guest 1]: What happens?

01:13:01.480 --> 01:13:07.480
[Guest 1]: People learn about fencing, physiotherapists learn how to deal with a fencer, coaches sort

01:13:07.480 --> 01:13:09.400
[Guest 1]: of have to upgrade their skills.

01:13:09.400 --> 01:13:12.000
[Guest 1]: So suddenly a system starts working.

01:13:12.000 --> 01:13:14.640
[Guest 1]: And sometimes all it takes is one athlete.

01:13:14.640 --> 01:13:20.080
[Guest 1]: And this is not even one athlete winning a gold medal or any medal, making that leap

01:13:20.080 --> 01:13:22.840
[Guest 1]: to be good enough to get prominence.

01:13:22.840 --> 01:13:28.840
[Guest 1]: What is the Olympics greatest stage on earth, attention is directed towards the Olympics.

01:13:28.840 --> 01:13:35.280
[Guest 1]: And we have to figure out how to capture the value of not just the medals, but all of these

01:13:35.280 --> 01:13:38.120
[Guest 1]: breakthrough achievements.

01:13:38.120 --> 01:13:39.520
[Guest 1]: And we failed in many instances.

01:13:39.520 --> 01:13:43.560
[Guest 1]: So the previous Olympics, the thing we as Go Sports Foundation are proudest of was Deepak

01:13:43.560 --> 01:13:46.600
[Guest 1]: Karmakar, a gymnast.

01:13:46.600 --> 01:13:50.940
[Guest 1]: What have we done five years later, I mean, we had a gymnast qualified through the sort

01:13:50.940 --> 01:13:56.480
[Guest 1]: of solidarity quota, but we have not developed a pathway, we have not developed a legacy,

01:13:56.480 --> 01:14:01.840
[Guest 1]: this brilliant, brilliant achievement by this girl coming forth at the Olympics.

01:14:01.840 --> 01:14:05.240
[Guest 1]: Have we captured the value in the performance system?

01:14:05.240 --> 01:14:06.240
[Guest 1]: No.

01:14:06.240 --> 01:14:10.920
[Guest 1]: Have we captured the value of that performance more broadly in society?

01:14:10.920 --> 01:14:12.880
[Guest 1]: My guess is perhaps not.

01:14:12.880 --> 01:14:18.120
[Guest 1]: And while things are improving, we really have to be clear on why we're going after

01:14:18.120 --> 01:14:24.080
[Guest 1]: the medals, and to build a legacy plan for every single medal, but also every single

01:14:24.080 --> 01:14:26.000
[Guest 1]: breakthrough sort of achievement.

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:30.880
[Guest 1]: You have your first equestrian for Mirza, you have your first female sailor, you have

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:33.840
[Guest 1]: your first fencer, what does that mean?

01:14:33.840 --> 01:14:38.880
[Guest 1]: Are you out there building the next generation in 10 years, in 15 years?

01:14:38.880 --> 01:14:44.800
[Guest 1]: Are you going to have your Abhinav Bindra moment, where a 10 or 12 year old who's watched

01:14:44.800 --> 01:14:49.460
[Guest 1]: that achievement, goes through the cycle and is ready to emulate?

01:14:49.460 --> 01:14:54.160
[Guest 1]: And those are the questions to ask in the setup of competition, but also the building

01:14:54.160 --> 01:14:56.240
[Guest 1]: of pathways, they're connected.

01:14:56.240 --> 01:15:00.920
[Guest 1]: To answer very briefly your question in a sort of a legal technical manner, the issue

01:15:00.920 --> 01:15:05.480
[Guest 1]: of autonomy, accountability and interference is a very live one.

01:15:05.480 --> 01:15:08.760
[Guest 1]: It's in fact in the courts in the Delhi High Court, one of my friends Rahul Mehra has been

01:15:08.760 --> 01:15:13.080
[Guest 1]: fighting this battle for, for years and years, I think he's not very well liked for obvious

01:15:13.080 --> 01:15:18.520
[Guest 1]: reasons by the federations, but looking back 20 years from now, I think we will thank him

01:15:18.520 --> 01:15:24.680
[Guest 1]: for what he has done in terms of building wonderful legal precedent on recognizing the

01:15:24.680 --> 01:15:27.440
[Guest 1]: public function that these bodies play.

01:15:27.440 --> 01:15:32.360
[Guest 1]: So what is now the public function test for private organizations that the sports bodies

01:15:32.360 --> 01:15:33.400
[Guest 1]: might be.

01:15:33.400 --> 01:15:38.760
[Guest 1]: What we do have is a sports code, which is essentially an accountability framework, saying

01:15:38.760 --> 01:15:44.520
[Guest 1]: we'll recognize your autonomy, but it is conditional autonomy, I mean, you're an autonomous vehicle,

01:15:44.520 --> 01:15:46.800
[Guest 1]: you still have to follow the rules of the road.

01:15:46.800 --> 01:15:51.940
[Guest 1]: You can't be an autonomous, random vehicle, you'll be crashing into people and other vehicles.

01:15:51.940 --> 01:15:56.600
[Guest 1]: So there's standards, it's financial integrity, operational integrity, are you holding enough

01:15:56.600 --> 01:15:57.600
[Guest 1]: tournaments?

01:15:57.600 --> 01:16:02.320
[Guest 1]: But the sad part is, and I've been on a committee to try and reform that we have a 2011 version

01:16:02.320 --> 01:16:03.320
[Guest 1]: of the court.

01:16:03.320 --> 01:16:04.320
[Guest 1]: That's not passed.

01:16:04.320 --> 01:16:09.160
[Guest 1]: I mean, there's an element of people in the power with the power to change things, being

01:16:09.160 --> 01:16:11.760
[Guest 1]: stakeholders and not being changed.

01:16:11.760 --> 01:16:17.600
[Guest 1]: Even the existing one is not being implemented to the fullest extent possible, because there

01:16:17.600 --> 01:16:21.800
[Guest 1]: are just too many lapses to justify inaction.

01:16:21.800 --> 01:16:25.760
[Guest 1]: And if you're going to give people the keys, like I said, you have to make sure that they're

01:16:25.760 --> 01:16:27.560
[Guest 1]: driving the engine.

01:16:27.560 --> 01:16:33.520
[Guest 1]: And while we can take the government to task if we perform badly, the likely outcome is

01:16:33.520 --> 01:16:37.840
[Guest 1]: that you're going to have more and more and more centralization and government doing and

01:16:37.840 --> 01:16:38.920
[Guest 1]: solving.

01:16:38.920 --> 01:16:44.960
[Guest 1]: If you do not fix the ability and the accountability on federations, or otherwise going to continue

01:16:44.960 --> 01:16:49.840
[Guest 1]: to enjoy the sort of the benefits of power without the responsibility, because in some

01:16:49.840 --> 01:16:52.800
[Guest 1]: sense, the job has been outsourced to the government.

01:16:52.800 --> 01:16:54.880
[Guest 1]: And you're seeing results, you're seeing things happen.

01:16:54.880 --> 01:16:58.440
[Guest 1]: And those collaborations will be very limited collaborations.

01:16:58.440 --> 01:17:00.200
[Guest 1]: So do you want to get there?

01:17:00.200 --> 01:17:05.160
[Guest 1]: Yes, number one, fix the sports code, fix accountability framework.

01:17:05.160 --> 01:17:11.040
[Guest 1]: Number two, and sort of an underdone aspect of sport law in India, and again, committed

01:17:11.040 --> 01:17:16.960
[Guest 1]: from regulatory perspective, is the role of competition law, antitrust law, and how it

01:17:16.960 --> 01:17:19.280
[Guest 1]: applies to sport situations.

01:17:19.280 --> 01:17:21.040
[Guest 1]: It's evolved quite a bit in Europe.

01:17:21.040 --> 01:17:23.640
[Guest 1]: So EU law on competition is significant.

01:17:23.640 --> 01:17:28.600
[Guest 1]: You're seeing much more private participation, like there's a very famous case of the skating

01:17:28.600 --> 01:17:29.600
[Guest 1]: union.

01:17:29.600 --> 01:17:33.640
[Guest 1]: There's a swimming, swimming league case, you're seeing more and more the separation

01:17:33.640 --> 01:17:39.120
[Guest 1]: of the regulatory function and the commercial function of sports federations, with the right

01:17:39.120 --> 01:17:46.000
[Guest 1]: of private enterprise to not step on the toes of federations in their regulatory function,

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:51.920
[Guest 1]: but have a neutral entry point to use stadia to use players.

01:17:51.920 --> 01:17:55.640
[Guest 1]: I mean, there's a lot of different things going on, making sure that players don't get

01:17:55.640 --> 01:17:59.280
[Guest 1]: banned for playing in what are called private leagues.

01:17:59.280 --> 01:18:02.360
[Guest 1]: But I mean, the US is full of private leagues, right?

01:18:02.360 --> 01:18:06.840
[Guest 1]: Sort of 360 days of the year, you're playing private leagues, five days a year, you're

01:18:06.840 --> 01:18:09.160
[Guest 1]: sort of going in representing your country.

01:18:09.160 --> 01:18:13.720
[Guest 1]: So there's a lot of legal structural frameworks that need work.

01:18:13.720 --> 01:18:17.480
[Guest 1]: I don't think we got there yet, we're still sort of not even enforcing the frameworks

01:18:17.480 --> 01:18:18.480
[Guest 1]: we do have yet.

01:18:18.480 --> 01:18:23.880
[Guest 2]: I'm not even going to, Nandan has taught me a lot over the last couple of years I've been

01:18:23.880 --> 01:18:28.520
[Guest 2]: dealing with him, especially, you know, with regard to the Volleyball Federation of India

01:18:28.520 --> 01:18:30.480
[Guest 2]: and whatever else that's happening.

01:18:30.480 --> 01:18:34.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, I think the base of it is the truth is that, you know, first take a name like

01:18:34.920 --> 01:18:42.720
[Guest 2]: BCCI, Board of Control, understand the words, control for cricket in India.

01:18:42.720 --> 01:18:44.400
[Guest 2]: It's about controlling things.

01:18:44.400 --> 01:18:50.680
[Guest 2]: And mind you, let's be honest, the BCCI has done the best job in the country of having

01:18:50.680 --> 01:18:56.440
[Guest 2]: age level competitions, of making sure money comes into the system of empowering the system,

01:18:56.440 --> 01:19:00.160
[Guest 2]: and with all their internal politics, and there's been a lot of it, and you know, nobody

01:19:00.160 --> 01:19:05.400
[Guest 2]: needs to talk about it, they've actually been not allowed most of that to get on to the

01:19:05.400 --> 01:19:06.400
[Guest 2]: field.

01:19:06.400 --> 01:19:12.320
[Guest 2]: In fact, I feel 80s and 90s, BCCI was far more, you know, far more on the field was

01:19:12.320 --> 01:19:17.280
[Guest 2]: being impacted by what was happening inside boardrooms, I think much less is now.

01:19:17.280 --> 01:19:20.040
[Guest 2]: And I think those separations have happened.

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:23.640
[Guest 2]: So two things I want to talk about, and I think, you know, a couple of years back, Nandan

01:19:23.640 --> 01:19:27.600
[Guest 2]: spoke about a very important point, which is that, what happens is that suppose you

01:19:27.600 --> 01:19:31.320
[Guest 2]: have something like a sports court saying, you know, this is what happens.

01:19:31.320 --> 01:19:38.440
[Guest 2]: Now, where do satraps in the federation, where do satraps in the ministry get power?

01:19:38.440 --> 01:19:43.600
[Guest 2]: They get power in the cracks, they get power in the places which are ambiguous.

01:19:43.600 --> 01:19:47.320
[Guest 2]: Whenever there's something ambiguous, then I sort of as a federation official have a

01:19:47.320 --> 01:19:51.760
[Guest 2]: right to decide, I'll go this way or that way.

01:19:51.760 --> 01:19:56.360
[Guest 2]: What we are trying to do or what people like Nandan are trying to do is making it as unambiguous

01:19:56.360 --> 01:19:58.120
[Guest 2]: as possible.

01:19:58.120 --> 01:20:01.440
[Guest 2]: This is the rule, this is how it works.

01:20:01.440 --> 01:20:06.160
[Guest 2]: But when you make things unambiguous, the people in power don't have power, they have

01:20:06.160 --> 01:20:08.560
[Guest 2]: to follow rules.

01:20:08.560 --> 01:20:13.880
[Guest 2]: So there's a constant battle in every organization between people who are saying, can I make

01:20:13.880 --> 01:20:16.520
[Guest 2]: as fair and transparent rule as possible?

01:20:16.520 --> 01:20:20.920
[Guest 2]: And people saying that, if it is completely fair and completely transparent, I don't have

01:20:20.920 --> 01:20:22.600
[Guest 2]: any power.

01:20:22.600 --> 01:20:25.320
[Guest 2]: So that's the battle that's going on now.

01:20:25.320 --> 01:20:30.840
[Guest 2]: And mind you, that's at a level which is always going to happen, okay?

01:20:30.840 --> 01:20:34.320
[Guest 2]: At the lower level than that, it's a simple thing.

01:20:34.320 --> 01:20:36.920
[Guest 2]: If you're a federation, how does a sport develop?

01:20:36.920 --> 01:20:40.960
[Guest 2]: A sport develops when you actually build a sport, when more games are held.

01:20:40.960 --> 01:20:45.080
[Guest 2]: Now, if the only thing a federation is doing is pitching to the government saying, okay,

01:20:45.080 --> 01:20:49.080
[Guest 2]: national games will be held and that's all I have, then you're not really building the

01:20:49.080 --> 01:20:50.080
[Guest 2]: sport.

01:20:50.080 --> 01:20:54.240
[Guest 2]: So a lot of these federations don't really want to go out and get too many sponsors because

01:20:54.240 --> 01:20:55.920
[Guest 2]: it's difficult.

01:20:55.920 --> 01:20:59.880
[Guest 2]: And if I get a sponsor, it means I have to deliver them a product, I have to show them,

01:20:59.880 --> 01:21:02.880
[Guest 2]: I have to put up their banners, I have to put it on TV because they're going to ask

01:21:02.880 --> 01:21:03.880
[Guest 2]: these questions.

01:21:03.880 --> 01:21:09.720
[Guest 2]: And look, I either am not efficient enough to do it, or I don't want to be called into

01:21:09.720 --> 01:21:13.040
[Guest 2]: question because somebody will ask me, yeah, I've given you 30 lakhs, what have you done

01:21:13.040 --> 01:21:14.040
[Guest 2]: with it?

01:21:14.040 --> 01:21:17.420
[Guest 2]: They don't want to be accountable.

01:21:17.420 --> 01:21:22.520
[Guest 2]: So those are basic, basic issues and we dealt with the Volleyball Federation, this is one

01:21:22.520 --> 01:21:27.320
[Guest 2]: of the things that we realized that A, that once you deal with these people or once you

01:21:27.320 --> 01:21:33.440
[Guest 2]: deal with them, firstly, the laws of the land and what Nandan was alluding to, say that

01:21:33.440 --> 01:21:38.120
[Guest 2]: they have absolutely no power, there's something called restraint of trade.

01:21:38.120 --> 01:21:41.060
[Guest 2]: You cannot stop me from making a living.

01:21:41.060 --> 01:21:45.480
[Guest 2]: So for example, if there is a Volleyball League and I start another Volleyball League, there

01:21:45.480 --> 01:21:52.520
[Guest 2]: is no way anyone can stop me from allowing players in my league to make a living.

01:21:52.520 --> 01:21:57.600
[Guest 2]: So legally, and there's a huge amount of precedent in this, restraint of trade is something that

01:21:57.600 --> 01:22:01.220
[Guest 2]: has never been used efficiently in India, but it's there.

01:22:01.220 --> 01:22:03.720
[Guest 2]: And if tomorrow you want to pull it out, you will.

01:22:03.720 --> 01:22:08.120
[Guest 2]: And I think the first changes have already happened.

01:22:08.120 --> 01:22:11.680
[Guest 2]: And I'll give you a very good example, Kabaddi.

01:22:11.680 --> 01:22:15.640
[Guest 2]: So Kabaddi, we all know, Mashal sport came and before that, the Kabaddi Federation, nobody's

01:22:15.640 --> 01:22:17.960
[Guest 2]: ever heard of, Kabaddi nobody's heard of.

01:22:17.960 --> 01:22:22.880
[Guest 2]: Charu Sharma comes in, he speaks to Anand Mahindra, who introduces him to a lot of friends.

01:22:22.880 --> 01:22:27.640
[Guest 2]: They get together, they start the Kabaddi League and to their eternal credit, Starr

01:22:27.640 --> 01:22:30.240
[Guest 2]: says, let's throw our weight behind it.

01:22:30.240 --> 01:22:34.560
[Guest 2]: And they do, they really do in terms of the amount of publicity they give it, the amount

01:22:34.560 --> 01:22:37.960
[Guest 2]: of space they give it, how well they put it together.

01:22:37.960 --> 01:22:42.280
[Guest 2]: It's a lesson, it's an object lesson because it's not an easy sport to make that popular,

01:22:42.280 --> 01:22:43.640
[Guest 2]: but they did it.

01:22:43.640 --> 01:22:45.280
[Guest 2]: Now here's what happens.

01:22:45.280 --> 01:22:50.520
[Guest 2]: What we don't know, don't talk about is, in these four, five years that the Kabaddi League

01:22:50.520 --> 01:22:56.080
[Guest 2]: has been operating, the Federation has changed three times over again, because once money

01:22:56.080 --> 01:22:59.660
[Guest 2]: has come into the Federation, all these guys are saying, look, all these guys are making

01:22:59.660 --> 01:23:00.660
[Guest 2]: so much money.

01:23:00.660 --> 01:23:01.940
[Guest 2]: Why are we not making money?

01:23:01.940 --> 01:23:03.500
[Guest 2]: So you need to pay me.

01:23:03.500 --> 01:23:06.960
[Guest 2]: And Mashal sports must have told them or Starr sports must have told them where to exactly

01:23:06.960 --> 01:23:10.000
[Guest 2]: to go and put what their demands are.

01:23:10.000 --> 01:23:12.440
[Guest 2]: And they would have said, OK, we've changed it.

01:23:12.440 --> 01:23:19.240
[Guest 2]: So if you really follow the small print, you'll realize that in 2019 or 20, the Kabaddi Federation

01:23:19.240 --> 01:23:25.320
[Guest 2]: changed and they awarded the rights of the next Kabaddi League to Sony.

01:23:25.320 --> 01:23:29.560
[Guest 2]: Nobody even knows about it because by that time, every player knew that there's no point

01:23:29.560 --> 01:23:30.560
[Guest 2]: following this.

01:23:30.560 --> 01:23:35.720
[Guest 2]: They just went to Mashal, they joined the Kabaddi League, and it went on as it did.

01:23:35.720 --> 01:23:40.400
[Guest 2]: So the most interesting thing I want to tell you is this year, there was a tender which

01:23:40.400 --> 01:23:46.840
[Guest 2]: had actually been taken out by Mashal sports saying, OK, these are for the media rights,

01:23:46.840 --> 01:23:49.900
[Guest 2]: which were finally again acquired by Starr.

01:23:49.900 --> 01:23:53.720
[Guest 2]: But the interesting thing was not that the media rights were spelled out or the PQL was

01:23:53.720 --> 01:23:54.720
[Guest 2]: spelled out.

01:23:54.720 --> 01:24:01.800
[Guest 2]: What is interesting is that in that one notice, there was not one mention about the Kabaddi

01:24:01.800 --> 01:24:02.800
[Guest 2]: Federation.

01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:07.440
[Guest 2]: Clearly, they were charting their own path.

01:24:07.440 --> 01:24:09.680
[Guest 2]: And I think that's what's going to happen.

01:24:09.680 --> 01:24:11.920
[Guest 2]: Nandan knows a little bit about our journey.

01:24:11.920 --> 01:24:13.600
[Guest 2]: In volleyball, we had the same thing.

01:24:13.600 --> 01:24:17.480
[Guest 2]: The International Volleyball Federation came down for our finals because they thought here

01:24:17.480 --> 01:24:22.680
[Guest 2]: in India, which is probably the largest democracy in the world, 1.3 billion people, there's

01:24:22.680 --> 01:24:25.720
[Guest 2]: a sport and you actually got a good product.

01:24:25.720 --> 01:24:29.060
[Guest 2]: And then all sorts of things happened because people got greedy.

01:24:29.060 --> 01:24:34.200
[Guest 2]: But what's happened as a result is we are launching a volleyball league once again.

01:24:34.200 --> 01:24:36.600
[Guest 2]: And this time it's without the Federation.

01:24:36.600 --> 01:24:39.080
[Guest 2]: And can I tell you, Amit, why it's without the Federation?

01:24:39.080 --> 01:24:41.320
[Guest 2]: Because people think very practically.

01:24:41.320 --> 01:24:47.520
[Guest 2]: So every time you go to a team and say, invest money, they say, OK, fine, we'll invest money.

01:24:47.520 --> 01:24:49.480
[Guest 2]: So when will I make money?

01:24:49.480 --> 01:24:52.880
[Guest 2]: You say, OK, sport is a long gestation period.

01:24:52.880 --> 01:24:56.440
[Guest 2]: So you say four years, five years, you're going to make money.

01:24:56.440 --> 01:25:00.280
[Guest 2]: They said, boss, if this league is successful for the first three years, the Federation

01:25:00.280 --> 01:25:04.160
[Guest 2]: tomorrow will get greedy and will throw you guys out and find somebody else, which has

01:25:04.160 --> 01:25:07.720
[Guest 2]: happened in badminton, which has happened in wrestling, which has happened in five other

01:25:07.720 --> 01:25:09.100
[Guest 2]: sports.

01:25:09.100 --> 01:25:10.600
[Guest 2]: So why should I invest money?

01:25:10.600 --> 01:25:14.440
[Guest 2]: Because the moment it gets good, the Federation will throw us out because they'll then get

01:25:14.440 --> 01:25:16.480
[Guest 2]: greedy and want money.

01:25:16.480 --> 01:25:23.560
[Guest 2]: So then we discovered that the only way to actually assure people that your investment

01:25:23.560 --> 01:25:27.600
[Guest 2]: is protected is to say, this has nothing to do with the Federation.

01:25:27.600 --> 01:25:32.640
[Guest 2]: Because the moment the Federation comes into effect, if people are greedy enough, they'll

01:25:32.640 --> 01:25:35.760
[Guest 2]: just turn around and say that, hey, boss, this is making money.

01:25:35.760 --> 01:25:36.760
[Guest 2]: Why am I?

01:25:36.760 --> 01:25:39.120
[Guest 2]: I'm sitting out here, and I'm not making any money.

01:25:39.120 --> 01:25:40.400
[Guest 2]: And here are these teams.

01:25:40.400 --> 01:25:41.400
[Guest 2]: And they're very simple things.

01:25:41.400 --> 01:25:45.280
[Guest 2]: They look at athletes staying in five-star hotels or four-star hotels with gyms, and

01:25:45.280 --> 01:25:49.800
[Guest 2]: they wonder, these are the athletes that we used to give rice and dal to and sambar to

01:25:49.800 --> 01:25:51.640
[Guest 2]: for breakfast in the nationals.

01:25:51.640 --> 01:25:52.960
[Guest 2]: Why are they staying in five-star hotels?

01:25:52.960 --> 01:25:56.720
[Guest 2]: Obviously, there's a lot of money, which means I need that money.

01:25:56.720 --> 01:25:59.120
[Guest 2]: So these are the problems that affect Indian sport.

01:25:59.120 --> 01:26:04.320
[Guest 2]: And if you don't break free of that, if you don't create a system, and it's not as if

01:26:04.320 --> 01:26:05.880
[Guest 2]: it's in the president over the world.

01:26:05.880 --> 01:26:08.720
[Guest 2]: I mean, USA basketball has nothing to do with the NBA.

01:26:08.720 --> 01:26:11.360
[Guest 2]: The NBA is a group of owners who get together, and they play the sport.

01:26:11.360 --> 01:26:17.000
[Guest 2]: And in fact, in 92, when the Dream Team happened, it was a huge negotiation between the NBA

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:19.120
[Guest 2]: and USA basketball.

01:26:19.120 --> 01:26:24.680
[Guest 2]: And that's exactly how it is in whether it's American football, a host of other places.

01:26:24.680 --> 01:26:30.000
[Guest 2]: The fact of the matter is that if you're not competent to run the federation, at least

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:33.080
[Guest 2]: let private enterprise get a chance.

01:26:33.080 --> 01:26:37.080
[Guest 2]: And that doesn't mean that tomorrow, if, for example, the federation starts a league of

01:26:37.080 --> 01:26:39.960
[Guest 2]: their own, which is successful, bully for them.

01:26:39.960 --> 01:26:40.960
[Guest 2]: Fantastic.

01:26:40.960 --> 01:26:44.240
[Guest 2]: Then guys will get two leagues to play with, or three leagues to play with, and there's

01:26:44.240 --> 01:26:46.880
[Guest 2]: nothing better than that competition.

01:26:46.880 --> 01:26:51.840
[Guest 2]: As Matt Ridley said, all of us sort of, Matt Ridley's are both our gurus, and we all talk

01:26:51.840 --> 01:26:55.120
[Guest 2]: about competition and how it develops, and it's fantastic.

01:26:55.120 --> 01:26:58.200
[Guest 2]: But you need to do that for sport.

01:26:58.200 --> 01:27:02.440
[Guest 2]: And that's where I think, over the next few years, Indian sport will take the next few

01:27:02.440 --> 01:27:03.960
[Amit Varma]: steps.

01:27:03.960 --> 01:27:05.320
[Amit Varma]: So this is eye opening for me.

01:27:05.320 --> 01:27:08.640
[Amit Varma]: And before I go on to the next question, I want to make a brief point because I thought

01:27:08.640 --> 01:27:13.200
[Amit Varma]: what you said about power often coming from ambiguity in rules is very wise and applies

01:27:13.200 --> 01:27:14.360
[Amit Varma]: to a lot more than sport.

01:27:14.360 --> 01:27:19.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if you just look at the Indian Constitution, you look at the caveats to free speech, which

01:27:19.080 --> 01:27:20.920
[Amit Varma]: are there in Article 19.

01:27:20.920 --> 01:27:25.360
[Amit Varma]: And there are vague things like public order, morality, decency, whatever, which can be

01:27:25.360 --> 01:27:29.640
[Amit Varma]: interpreted by a bureaucrat or a police constable any way he wants.

01:27:29.640 --> 01:27:31.840
[Amit Varma]: And that ambiguity is a problem.

01:27:31.840 --> 01:27:37.040
[Amit Varma]: And of course, what lawyers like Nandan perhaps spend their lifetimes doing is just, you know,

01:27:37.040 --> 01:27:41.600
[Amit Varma]: sub clause or sub clause, make it as specific as possible, don't let people mess around.

01:27:41.600 --> 01:27:45.520
[Amit Varma]: So my next question is kind of a follow up to this, like Nandan, you spoke about how

01:27:45.520 --> 01:27:47.960
[Amit Varma]: in Europe, and I wasn't aware of this.

01:27:47.960 --> 01:27:53.440
[Amit Varma]: So please enlighten me, that you spoke about how in Europe, there is now this distinction

01:27:53.440 --> 01:27:58.240
[Amit Varma]: being drawn between regulatory and commercial, that it's okay for a federation that governs

01:27:58.240 --> 01:28:03.800
[Amit Varma]: a sport, which has through circumstance achieved at monopoly and monopsony, it's okay for them

01:28:03.800 --> 01:28:06.120
[Amit Varma]: to continue regulating the sport.

01:28:06.120 --> 01:28:10.160
[Amit Varma]: But as far as a commercial is concerned, that that has to be open to competition.

01:28:10.160 --> 01:28:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And competition, of course, is oxygen.

01:28:12.000 --> 01:28:15.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's where excellence inevitably comes from.

01:28:15.880 --> 01:28:19.760
[Amit Varma]: And Joy just gave an example of that in the volleyball league, which he's doing and in

01:28:19.760 --> 01:28:20.880
[Amit Varma]: the Kabaddi league.

01:28:20.880 --> 01:28:27.760
[Amit Varma]: So is that the future vision of Indian sport in the sense that you have these federations,

01:28:27.760 --> 01:28:30.880
[Amit Varma]: but they are autonomous, but they are bound by rules.

01:28:30.880 --> 01:28:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And anybody, any entrepreneur can then go in and compete within that space.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:39.280
[Amit Varma]: So tomorrow, someone like me can go and say, okay, I'm going to start a handball league

01:28:39.280 --> 01:28:41.040
[Amit Varma]: or this league or that league.

01:28:41.040 --> 01:28:45.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I function within the rules of the game, but I can do whatever.

01:28:45.240 --> 01:28:49.400
[Amit Varma]: So number one, is that your vision of Indian sport, say 20 years down the line, are we

01:28:49.400 --> 01:28:52.400
[Amit Varma]: going to evolve in that direction?

01:28:52.400 --> 01:28:56.360
[Amit Varma]: And the other sort of orthogonal question, which Joy might have a really good sense of

01:28:56.360 --> 01:29:03.400
[Amit Varma]: having built the volleyball league, is that does it then become a question of building

01:29:03.400 --> 01:29:08.200
[Amit Varma]: the popularity of a sport before it's necessarily commercially viable?

01:29:08.200 --> 01:29:14.720
[Amit Varma]: Like if someone was to tell you 10 years ago, the natural assumption of someone like me

01:29:14.720 --> 01:29:17.400
[Amit Varma]: would have been that there aren't viewers for the game.

01:29:17.400 --> 01:29:19.600
[Amit Varma]: And then it becomes a chicken and egg problem.

01:29:19.600 --> 01:29:25.520
[Amit Varma]: So our entrepreneurs then going in and saying that, you know, we'll just go first.

01:29:25.520 --> 01:29:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And we'll put a good product out there and the viewership will come.

01:29:29.120 --> 01:29:31.580
[Amit Varma]: Is that a model that you see working?

01:29:31.580 --> 01:29:35.040
[Amit Varma]: And then therefore, would you say that many of these so called Olympic sports, which,

01:29:35.040 --> 01:29:37.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, aren't necessarily super popular today?

01:29:37.200 --> 01:29:39.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we watch Javelin once in four years.

01:29:39.080 --> 01:29:43.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is the first time in my life, I saw a Javelin event, in fact, life.

01:29:43.240 --> 01:29:47.480
[Amit Varma]: Can that change because of the efforts of entrepreneurs who go out there and build that

01:29:47.480 --> 01:29:48.480
[Amit Varma]: market?

01:29:48.480 --> 01:29:50.620
[Guest 1]: Excellent point, Amit.

01:29:50.620 --> 01:29:54.800
[Guest 1]: And I think Joy's volleyball league is really going to be a precursor.

01:29:54.800 --> 01:29:58.500
[Guest 1]: It's going to be interesting to see how the legal system responds to this.

01:29:58.500 --> 01:30:03.660
[Guest 1]: So historically, most of these leagues have now gone out with private enterprise.

01:30:03.660 --> 01:30:07.920
[Guest 1]: But they also always have had to take sanction from the federation.

01:30:07.920 --> 01:30:09.580
[Guest 1]: And very often, that's just a payment.

01:30:09.580 --> 01:30:17.200
[Guest 1]: It is supposed to be payment in lieu of regulatory services, which is essentially integrity services,

01:30:17.200 --> 01:30:22.080
[Guest 1]: making sure that the rules are structured properly, sort of having some dispute resolution

01:30:22.080 --> 01:30:23.080
[Guest 1]: structures.

01:30:23.080 --> 01:30:27.400
[Guest 1]: But very often, it's just a check that is given in exchange for being allowed to do

01:30:27.400 --> 01:30:28.880
[Guest 1]: the league.

01:30:28.880 --> 01:30:32.080
[Guest 1]: What is going to happen with volleyball is it's a test case.

01:30:32.080 --> 01:30:37.720
[Guest 1]: How is the sort of official pyramid of sport and if I may just take a moment to talk about

01:30:37.720 --> 01:30:44.440
[Guest 1]: how the pyramid is structured, is every sort of federation has an international linkage.

01:30:44.440 --> 01:30:47.760
[Guest 1]: So let's say it's the Volleyball Federation as an International Volleyball Federation

01:30:47.760 --> 01:30:50.720
[Guest 1]: which recognizes the Indian one.

01:30:50.720 --> 01:30:54.440
[Guest 1]: The Ministry of Sport also recognizes the Volleyball Federation and there have been

01:30:54.440 --> 01:30:58.440
[Guest 1]: changes and the recognition recognition over time.

01:30:58.440 --> 01:31:04.560
[Guest 1]: But then that recognition is dependent on that Volleyball Federation having state federations

01:31:04.560 --> 01:31:06.040
[Guest 1]: as their members.

01:31:06.040 --> 01:31:09.960
[Guest 1]: The state federations are expected to have district federations and you're supposed to

01:31:09.960 --> 01:31:15.280
[Guest 1]: have literally national coverage to be this National Sports Federation and to comply with

01:31:15.280 --> 01:31:17.160
[Guest 1]: certain norms.

01:31:17.160 --> 01:31:22.880
[Guest 1]: Now the question is, is everything that you do, theoretically say within this pyramid,

01:31:22.880 --> 01:31:29.800
[Guest 1]: is it truly a monopoly or monopsony or is the power that has been endowed simply a regulatory

01:31:29.800 --> 01:31:35.600
[Guest 1]: power to essentially keep trusteeship of the rules of the game?

01:31:35.600 --> 01:31:40.800
[Guest 1]: Because the essential function of this pyramid is that this pyramid is connected to the international

01:31:40.800 --> 01:31:42.160
[Guest 1]: sports pyramid.

01:31:42.160 --> 01:31:46.760
[Guest 1]: So that there has to be a coherence and universality to sport, right?

01:31:46.760 --> 01:31:51.120
[Guest 1]: If volleyball in India was played differently from volleyball in Argentina versus Spain

01:31:51.120 --> 01:31:57.200
[Guest 1]: versus Brazil, you couldn't have an international tournament because it's sort of disaggregated

01:31:57.200 --> 01:32:00.140
[Guest 1]: pieces trying to feed to a common goal, right?

01:32:00.140 --> 01:32:06.000
[Guest 1]: So there is a principle value and there is a natural monopoly element to this, which

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:12.700
[Guest 1]: is universality of rules and coherence in a sort of a trajectory moving upwards.

01:32:12.700 --> 01:32:18.080
[Guest 1]: But that really comes up largely for the Olympic Games or multi-sport games.

01:32:18.080 --> 01:32:20.040
[Guest 1]: What happens in between?

01:32:20.040 --> 01:32:25.360
[Guest 1]: And is everything theoretically from a legal perspective under the pyramid?

01:32:25.360 --> 01:32:29.560
[Guest 1]: The answer coming from the law is the answer is no.

01:32:29.560 --> 01:32:31.840
[Guest 1]: There is a monopoly and it is not a monopsony.

01:32:31.840 --> 01:32:38.840
[Guest 1]: There's a monopoly in creating the rules of the game, enforcing the rules of the game,

01:32:38.840 --> 01:32:41.940
[Guest 1]: making sure there's no breach of like integrity, let me put it.

01:32:41.940 --> 01:32:47.420
[Guest 1]: So someone's not destroying and diluting what the game looks like or the way it's played.

01:32:47.420 --> 01:32:51.040
[Guest 1]: But beyond that, does it give you the right to run business?

01:32:51.040 --> 01:32:55.880
[Guest 1]: That is a right that has been claimed, but it is not a right that theoretically could

01:32:55.880 --> 01:32:58.120
[Guest 1]: be asserted under competition law.

01:32:58.120 --> 01:33:01.040
[Guest 1]: And I mean, Indian competition law is new.

01:33:01.040 --> 01:33:02.960
[Guest 1]: It's in a decade or two old.

01:33:02.960 --> 01:33:06.160
[Guest 1]: We have a competition commission of India that has done some very interesting cases

01:33:06.160 --> 01:33:11.560
[Guest 1]: on BCCM media rights, on Hockey India, there have been multiple federation type cases.

01:33:11.560 --> 01:33:16.040
[Guest 1]: Very interesting one is on how it dealt with the Athletics Federation of India, which had

01:33:16.040 --> 01:33:20.800
[Guest 1]: taken the view that every marathon in India had to be authorized by the Athletics Federation

01:33:20.800 --> 01:33:21.800
[Unknown]: of India.

01:33:21.800 --> 01:33:26.440
[Guest 1]: And the CCA actually held no, you do not have the right to prevent someone from holding

01:33:26.440 --> 01:33:27.440
[Guest 1]: a marathon.

01:33:27.440 --> 01:33:32.520
[Guest 1]: You can go and send athletes to international events, but your regulatory function and your

01:33:32.520 --> 01:33:34.520
[Guest 1]: commercial function are separate.

01:33:34.520 --> 01:33:37.120
[Guest 1]: You can charge a fee, anyone can pay that fee.

01:33:37.120 --> 01:33:40.980
[Guest 1]: If it's a five lakhs, you'll measure the course, you'll make sure that health and safety is

01:33:40.980 --> 01:33:45.800
[Guest 1]: taken care of and no sort of match fixing happening, etc.

01:33:45.800 --> 01:33:49.500
[Guest 1]: But anyone should be able to go and charge, you can charge for it.

01:33:49.500 --> 01:33:51.320
[Guest 1]: It's governance as a service.

01:33:51.320 --> 01:33:54.880
[Guest 1]: But anyone can hold a marathon, just look at the way the running movement has evolved

01:33:54.880 --> 01:33:55.880
[Guest 1]: as a result.

01:33:55.880 --> 01:33:56.880
[Guest 1]: Right?

01:33:56.880 --> 01:34:01.160
[Guest 1]: Imagine if you had to have Athletics Federation approved events all over the country, significant

01:34:01.160 --> 01:34:03.280
[Guest 1]: intervention by competition commission.

01:34:03.280 --> 01:34:09.880
[Guest 1]: And this is going to be a sort of a process of building businesses, building business

01:34:09.880 --> 01:34:10.880
[Guest 1]: models.

01:34:10.880 --> 01:34:15.160
[Guest 1]: But there before I hand over to Joy, I'd just like to say, we've been damaged a little bit

01:34:15.160 --> 01:34:21.640
[Guest 1]: by the sort of the me too culture of sports leagues, where everyone is, we talked about

01:34:21.640 --> 01:34:26.880
[Guest 1]: the 2008 movement moment of the IPL as much as Abhinav Bindra's.

01:34:26.880 --> 01:34:31.280
[Guest 1]: That was adopted as a business model that could work everywhere.

01:34:31.280 --> 01:34:36.700
[Guest 1]: And I have a problem with that because cricket and franchising made sense.

01:34:36.700 --> 01:34:41.800
[Guest 1]: Because the prototype had already been developed, there was an audience, what you did is franchise

01:34:41.800 --> 01:34:44.080
[Guest 1]: for growth.

01:34:44.080 --> 01:34:47.840
[Guest 1]: But what every other league has tried to do, and I think you alluded to that a little bit

01:34:47.840 --> 01:34:53.440
[Guest 1]: earlier is if that sport doesn't exist, can you build a solid franchise system, franchise

01:34:53.440 --> 01:34:59.000
[Guest 1]: system is being used as startup capital, rather than expansion capital.

01:34:59.000 --> 01:35:05.360
[Guest 1]: And I think they have to be new and innovative models, where you are not necessarily just

01:35:05.360 --> 01:35:11.720
[Guest 1]: sort of outsourcing risk, and building unsustainable models, which break elsewhere as well.

01:35:11.720 --> 01:35:17.120
[Guest 1]: And lots of our leagues have been very destructive to the sport, they're seen as very, very sort

01:35:17.120 --> 01:35:22.200
[Guest 1]: of visionary and helpful, but very few have made it to their third year.

01:35:22.200 --> 01:35:28.000
[Guest 1]: And once something does badly, it builds a mentality that this is not sustainable.

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:32.400
[Guest 1]: But it could simply be the business model that you've chosen the wrong way to go about

01:35:32.400 --> 01:35:33.400
[Guest 1]: doing things.

01:35:33.400 --> 01:35:35.200
[Guest 1]: And you've chosen the wrong people to do it with.

01:35:35.200 --> 01:35:39.620
[Guest 1]: And I'll just give you an example, I think the IPL was fantastic, because of the ability

01:35:39.620 --> 01:35:45.360
[Guest 1]: to reach new people democratize the tools of production, new selectors, you can market

01:35:45.360 --> 01:35:49.200
[Guest 1]: in Kolkata differently from the way you market in Bangalore or Bombay.

01:35:49.200 --> 01:35:54.120
[Guest 1]: But many of the other sports were not that they were saying, come and give me money for

01:35:54.120 --> 01:35:58.480
[Guest 1]: three years, I'll take your money and I'll build a league.

01:35:58.480 --> 01:36:00.960
[Guest 1]: I'll build from scratch, and I'll build an audience.

01:36:00.960 --> 01:36:06.640
[Guest 1]: Now that's, that's not franchising, that is literally investing in something and taking

01:36:06.640 --> 01:36:10.080
[Guest 1]: sort of outsourcing of risk, I would say.

01:36:10.080 --> 01:36:15.080
[Guest 1]: On the other hand, you look at the BBL in Australia, who owns the BBL, Cricket Australia

01:36:15.080 --> 01:36:21.760
[Guest 1]: owns the entire BBL, every single team within it, when it's ready and right, it will divest

01:36:21.760 --> 01:36:28.640
[Guest 1]: because at that point, that sport needed sort of growth, needed sort of establishment.

01:36:28.640 --> 01:36:32.360
[Guest 1]: And when the time is right, you can also bring in private capital.

01:36:32.360 --> 01:36:38.120
[Guest 1]: And just just to end when I talked about earlier, the importance of governance to bring private

01:36:38.120 --> 01:36:39.520
[Guest 1]: capital in.

01:36:39.520 --> 01:36:45.240
[Guest 1]: At the same time, the importance of governance because private capital is going to come in.

01:36:45.240 --> 01:36:50.320
[Guest 1]: All the more reason we are going to need that regulatory function of sports bodies to be

01:36:50.320 --> 01:36:52.800
[Guest 1]: done excellently.

01:36:52.800 --> 01:36:56.440
[Guest 1]: Because the profit motive is great, competition is great.

01:36:56.440 --> 01:37:01.320
[Guest 1]: But private enterprise can also be destructive of the sports movement.

01:37:01.320 --> 01:37:07.240
[Guest 1]: It leads to things like conflict of interest, the sort of the private sort of profiteering,

01:37:07.240 --> 01:37:12.280
[Guest 1]: and you have someone in the body, also with an interest in that profiteering.

01:37:12.280 --> 01:37:17.640
[Guest 1]: If you do not build a governance framework, private capital can damage as much as it can

01:37:17.640 --> 01:37:19.440
[Guest 1]: support the growth of sport.

01:37:19.440 --> 01:37:24.960
[Guest 2]: No, no, I have a lot to say, and a lot of which Nandan may have discussed over so many,

01:37:24.960 --> 01:37:26.600
[Guest 2]: so many discussions.

01:37:26.600 --> 01:37:31.600
[Guest 2]: But first and foremost, what happens is that one of the problems is firstly, when you start

01:37:31.600 --> 01:37:36.360
[Guest 2]: a sport, you turn around and say, OK, this is an IPL, let's make a league, OK?

01:37:36.360 --> 01:37:38.080
[Guest 2]: Let me give you some basic issues.

01:37:38.080 --> 01:37:41.800
[Guest 2]: One is that every game is not good for a league, OK?

01:37:41.800 --> 01:37:44.240
[Guest 2]: Individual sports, it's not easy to build a league in.

01:37:44.240 --> 01:37:46.320
[Guest 2]: And I'll give you a typical case.

01:37:46.320 --> 01:37:50.520
[Guest 2]: In the 70s, there was something called World Team Tennis in the United States of America.

01:37:50.520 --> 01:37:54.600
[Guest 2]: John McEnroe was playing for Los Angeles, Jimmy Connors was playing for New York, Bjorn

01:37:54.600 --> 01:37:56.240
[Guest 2]: Borg was playing for Washington.

01:37:56.240 --> 01:37:57.240
[Guest 2]: It didn't work.

01:37:57.240 --> 01:37:59.920
[Guest 2]: Why didn't it work?

01:37:59.920 --> 01:38:05.120
[Guest 2]: Because people were watching Borg versus Connors or Borg versus McEnroe, Connors versus McEnroe.

01:38:05.120 --> 01:38:10.920
[Guest 2]: They were never watching Washington versus New York or LA or any such contrived thing.

01:38:10.920 --> 01:38:16.240
[Guest 2]: The problem is individual sport does not lend itself to leagues in the same way as team

01:38:16.240 --> 01:38:18.840
[Guest 2]: sports do, number one.

01:38:18.840 --> 01:38:25.080
[Guest 2]: Number two, there are some games which are more television-friendly, others less so.

01:38:25.080 --> 01:38:27.040
[Guest 2]: Cricket is a great television-friendly game.

01:38:27.040 --> 01:38:28.040
[Guest 2]: Hockey is not.

01:38:28.040 --> 01:38:29.760
[Guest 2]: So you'll ask, the ball is equally small.

01:38:29.760 --> 01:38:35.720
[Guest 2]: But remember, when you play cricket, you have 15 seconds of live action, OK?

01:38:35.720 --> 01:38:38.160
[Guest 2]: Bowler goes in, bowls a ball, the batsman hits the ball.

01:38:38.160 --> 01:38:40.840
[Guest 2]: And then you have a minute of replays.

01:38:40.840 --> 01:38:42.560
[Guest 2]: Cricket is essentially a game of replays.

01:38:42.560 --> 01:38:46.960
[Guest 2]: If you think about it, cricket is a game of four to five replays.

01:38:46.960 --> 01:38:52.160
[Guest 2]: It's the ratio of live action to replays about one is to five, OK?

01:38:52.160 --> 01:38:53.720
[Guest 2]: Hockey is exactly the opposite.

01:38:53.720 --> 01:38:58.160
[Guest 2]: You barely have time to show a replay because the action is so fast.

01:38:58.160 --> 01:39:01.840
[Guest 2]: Maybe you'll get in the replay of a penalty corner or two, but during a football game

01:39:01.840 --> 01:39:04.920
[Guest 2]: or a hockey game, it's very difficult to get in replays.

01:39:04.920 --> 01:39:07.360
[Guest 2]: Now here, football, the ball is large enough.

01:39:07.360 --> 01:39:08.360
[Guest 2]: You can follow the action.

01:39:08.360 --> 01:39:13.920
[Guest 2]: So football, volleyball, basketball, easy games to create.

01:39:13.920 --> 01:39:16.000
[Guest 2]: The second thing is, do games have breaks?

01:39:16.000 --> 01:39:19.200
[Guest 2]: So football is, in fact, one of the tougher games because you don't have that many breaks

01:39:19.200 --> 01:39:23.440
[Guest 2]: to put in ads, whereas cricket is terrific for ads because in every over, you have a

01:39:23.440 --> 01:39:24.840
[Guest 2]: chance to put in ads.

01:39:24.840 --> 01:39:30.360
[Guest 2]: So all these are factors that come into, A, whether you can make your sport viable or

01:39:30.360 --> 01:39:31.360
[Guest 2]: not.

01:39:31.360 --> 01:39:32.360
[Guest 2]: Is it an individual sport?

01:39:32.360 --> 01:39:33.360
[Guest 2]: Is it television friendly?

01:39:33.360 --> 01:39:35.560
[Guest 2]: For example, I love playing table tennis.

01:39:35.560 --> 01:39:39.400
[Guest 2]: I actually played at a fairly decent level in college as well.

01:39:39.400 --> 01:39:43.080
[Guest 2]: But table tennis is not a sport I can watch.

01:39:43.080 --> 01:39:45.800
[Guest 2]: I watch tennis, which I've never played in my life.

01:39:45.800 --> 01:39:49.520
[Guest 2]: But table tennis is not a sport I can watch simply because the mechanics of the game and

01:39:49.520 --> 01:39:51.680
[Guest 2]: how it looks on the tables.

01:39:51.680 --> 01:39:53.720
[Guest 2]: So those are things that you need to look at.

01:39:53.720 --> 01:39:55.760
[Guest 2]: So everything cannot be a league.

01:39:55.760 --> 01:39:59.920
[Guest 2]: Secondly, a lot of things are suited by just a tournament.

01:39:59.920 --> 01:40:03.280
[Guest 2]: What you call a league can just be a terrific tournament, and you can make it.

01:40:03.280 --> 01:40:05.040
[Guest 2]: And that's what it used to be.

01:40:05.040 --> 01:40:10.560
[Guest 2]: So you didn't have an Indian soccer league before, but you used to have the Durant Cup,

01:40:10.560 --> 01:40:13.080
[Guest 2]: the Borderline Cup, the DCM Cup.

01:40:13.080 --> 01:40:14.920
[Guest 2]: You had the Rovers Cup.

01:40:14.920 --> 01:40:17.920
[Guest 2]: So Bombay had the Rovers, DCM in Delhi.

01:40:17.920 --> 01:40:21.080
[Guest 2]: The Durant used to happen all over the place, mostly in Delhi.

01:40:21.080 --> 01:40:23.400
[Guest 2]: The IFA Shield used to happen in Calcutta.

01:40:23.400 --> 01:40:24.720
[Guest 2]: That's how it used to operate.

01:40:24.720 --> 01:40:29.240
[Guest 2]: So a good tournament also makes sense because you're attracting teams, you're attracting

01:40:29.240 --> 01:40:30.560
[Guest 2]: people out there.

01:40:30.560 --> 01:40:34.760
[Guest 2]: And some cases, you look at a sport and you say, you know what, this needs a tournament.

01:40:34.760 --> 01:40:41.040
[Guest 2]: This doesn't need a league because everything does not need to be an IPL.

01:40:41.040 --> 01:40:45.960
[Guest 2]: The next thing is, how do I actually benchmark the price of the players?

01:40:45.960 --> 01:40:47.800
[Guest 2]: And this is the biggest problem.

01:40:47.800 --> 01:40:52.600
[Guest 2]: If I turn on benchmark and say that, you know what, if an IPL player gets $100,000, the

01:40:52.600 --> 01:40:57.960
[Guest 2]: average IPL player gets $100,000, my league players need to get $25,000, that's totally

01:40:57.960 --> 01:41:00.080
[Guest 2]: the wrong way to look at it.

01:41:00.080 --> 01:41:03.360
[Guest 2]: Because is your league going to generate that cash?

01:41:03.360 --> 01:41:04.760
[Guest 2]: If not now in three years' time?

01:41:04.760 --> 01:41:08.960
[Guest 2]: If it's not, pay them the amount of money you think they'll generate in three years'

01:41:08.960 --> 01:41:09.960
[Unknown]: time.

01:41:09.960 --> 01:41:13.340
[Guest 2]: Because otherwise, your league will never have a path to profitability.

01:41:13.340 --> 01:41:16.000
[Guest 2]: And that's a big, big, big issue with a lot of leagues.

01:41:16.000 --> 01:41:20.440
[Guest 2]: I mean, badminton, the kind of money the players are being paid, I'm looking at it and saying,

01:41:20.440 --> 01:41:22.240
[Guest 2]: can they sustain this league?

01:41:22.240 --> 01:41:23.240
[Guest 2]: It turns out they can't.

01:41:23.240 --> 01:41:25.760
[Guest 2]: We don't have a badminton league anymore.

01:41:25.760 --> 01:41:26.840
[Guest 2]: Let's be very honest.

01:41:26.840 --> 01:41:31.320
[Guest 2]: At this point in time, we're talking about Indian sport and all that, we're Congo.

01:41:31.320 --> 01:41:37.200
[Guest 2]: There's an Indian Premier League, there's an ISL, there's I-League, which is also football,

01:41:37.200 --> 01:41:38.200
[Guest 2]: there's Kabaddi.

01:41:38.200 --> 01:41:41.320
[Guest 2]: There may be volleyball, which we're doing at the end of the year.

01:41:41.320 --> 01:41:43.240
[Guest 2]: Name one other league which is extinct.

01:41:43.240 --> 01:41:44.880
[Guest 2]: There isn't.

01:41:44.880 --> 01:41:46.240
[Guest 2]: And that's a fact of it.

01:41:46.240 --> 01:41:47.360
[Guest 2]: Wrestling has gone under.

01:41:47.360 --> 01:41:48.800
[Guest 2]: Badminton has gone under.

01:41:48.800 --> 01:41:50.120
[Guest 2]: Handball has not started.

01:41:50.120 --> 01:41:53.520
[Guest 2]: Coco, we think will start, nobody knows whether it'll ever start or not.

01:41:53.520 --> 01:41:55.040
[Guest 2]: Hockey has gone under.

01:41:55.040 --> 01:41:56.320
[Guest 2]: And that's a fact.

01:41:56.320 --> 01:42:00.160
[Guest 2]: Because all of these are over-promised, under-delivered.

01:42:00.160 --> 01:42:05.880
[Guest 2]: And OK, the single most important thing when you're looking for a league is the ownership.

01:42:05.880 --> 01:42:11.200
[Guest 2]: So if you have a guy who's the owner, who's turning around and said, boss, you mean Abhishek

01:42:11.200 --> 01:42:15.320
[Guest 2]: Bachchan has a team and I'm going to sit beside him when the picture is taken, he's going

01:42:15.320 --> 01:42:19.080
[Guest 2]: to be there for one or two years till the novelty of sitting beside Abhishek Bachchan

01:42:19.080 --> 01:42:20.520
[Guest 2]: makes sense.

01:42:20.520 --> 01:42:25.600
[Guest 2]: After that, three or four crores he's losing, it no longer makes sense.

01:42:25.600 --> 01:42:31.200
[Guest 2]: So these are all the barriers that, practical barriers that come into trying to make a league.

01:42:31.200 --> 01:42:36.260
[Guest 2]: And why a lot of our leagues have gone bottoms up, primarily because a lot of these things

01:42:36.260 --> 01:42:39.360
[Guest 2]: probably didn't deserve to be leagues in the first place.

01:42:39.360 --> 01:42:44.160
[Guest 2]: And leagues jumped simply because it was easy to explain to people that the IPL model, oh,

01:42:44.160 --> 01:42:46.440
[Guest 2]: like the IPL, we have our league.

01:42:46.440 --> 01:42:50.680
[Guest 2]: So that's one of the things and lessons we've got to learn in Indian sport to say, OK, what

01:42:50.680 --> 01:42:51.960
[Guest 2]: is it that we make a league?

01:42:51.960 --> 01:42:53.720
[Guest 2]: What is it that we make a tournament?

01:42:53.720 --> 01:42:56.840
[Guest 2]: What is it that's best served by doing something completely else?

01:42:56.840 --> 01:43:01.600
[Guest 2]: And all these are, mind you, I believe that even in archery, you can have an activity

01:43:01.600 --> 01:43:06.240
[Guest 2]: which is financially rewarding, makes sense to athletes, and works.

01:43:06.240 --> 01:43:10.360
[Guest 2]: But you have to create that framework based on where the game is and what you can get

01:43:10.360 --> 01:43:11.560
[Guest 2]: out of it.

01:43:11.560 --> 01:43:14.360
[Guest 2]: And that's what we're not doing nowadays very well.

01:43:14.360 --> 01:43:16.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, all great points.

01:43:16.520 --> 01:43:19.500
[Amit Varma]: I'm learning so much during this conversation.

01:43:19.500 --> 01:43:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Just to give my thoughts on some of the points.

01:43:22.000 --> 01:43:26.480
[Amit Varma]: One, I take your point, Nandan, that these are not necessarily monopsonies, though, you

01:43:26.480 --> 01:43:31.540
[Amit Varma]: know, one thinks of it as a monopsony because when the BCCI shut down the ICL, essentially

01:43:31.540 --> 01:43:35.840
[Amit Varma]: by threatening the players who played it that you can't play for your countries again, there

01:43:35.840 --> 01:43:39.920
[Amit Varma]: were effectively behaving as a monopsony and they had the market power to do so because

01:43:39.920 --> 01:43:41.720
[Amit Varma]: they had a monopoly over the sport.

01:43:41.720 --> 01:43:42.800
[Amit Varma]: So it worked that way.

01:43:42.800 --> 01:43:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And I would go further by saying that, yeah, I buy your point that they're not monopsonies

01:43:46.200 --> 01:43:51.440
[Amit Varma]: necessarily, they're not even necessarily monopolies in terms of setting the rules.

01:43:51.440 --> 01:43:52.720
[Amit Varma]: That's the way it's been normalized.

01:43:52.720 --> 01:43:53.760
[Amit Varma]: We think of it like that.

01:43:53.760 --> 01:43:58.520
[Amit Varma]: But if you look at what happens to new sports, for example, recently, I went into this rabbit

01:43:58.520 --> 01:44:02.240
[Amit Varma]: hole where I was watching a lot of Tetris World Championships and so on.

01:44:02.240 --> 01:44:05.520
[Amit Varma]: And there are sort of different federations which have different kinds of World Championships.

01:44:05.520 --> 01:44:09.720
[Amit Varma]: One is the newest kind of Tetris, which is very funky and colorful and sound effects

01:44:09.720 --> 01:44:10.720
[Amit Varma]: and all that.

01:44:10.720 --> 01:44:15.800
[Amit Varma]: The other is a classic console Tetris, where I think recently the previous champion 17

01:44:15.800 --> 01:44:19.720
[Amit Varma]: year old Joseph Saley lost to the 13 year old new champion whose name is Dog.

01:44:19.720 --> 01:44:22.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, he calls himself Dog and all these are happening online.

01:44:22.960 --> 01:44:27.740
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, something new like poker, like I recently represented India in a particular

01:44:27.740 --> 01:44:30.960
[Amit Varma]: form of poker called match poker, we won the Asian Championships.

