[Guest 1]: There aren't public golf courses in India.

01:57:02.400 --> 01:57:07.640
[Guest 1]: So, so much of that is still sort of privilege based access to even playing the sport, forget

01:57:07.640 --> 01:57:10.240
[Guest 1]: about progressing at the sport.

01:57:10.240 --> 01:57:13.840
[Guest 1]: And there is very much a sort of a class system, which is not fully dissipated.

01:57:13.840 --> 01:57:18.800
[Guest 1]: I think one of the great joys and successes is to see even the Indian cricket team and

01:57:18.800 --> 01:57:23.680
[Guest 1]: how it has got democratized and you call it the Dhoni effect, you call it whatever else.

01:57:23.680 --> 01:57:29.820
[Guest 1]: But today, I think anyone who's good has a way in, there are various reasons for that.

01:57:29.820 --> 01:57:34.360
[Guest 1]: But you also see a lot of other sports and one of the things that becomes very clear

01:57:34.360 --> 01:57:39.720
[Guest 1]: is it's sport is not just about this sort of actualization and self-actualization.

01:57:39.720 --> 01:57:44.880
[Guest 1]: But for many, many of our athletes, it is a simply a matter of livelihood.

01:57:44.880 --> 01:57:49.560
[Guest 1]: Solution to that has been sort of it moved from patronage and needing patronage of the

01:57:49.560 --> 01:57:50.560
[Guest 1]: Rajas.

01:57:50.560 --> 01:57:55.480
[Guest 1]: I mean, early Olympic movement was supported by the Tatas, just sort of collecting money

01:57:55.480 --> 01:57:56.840
[Guest 1]: together.

01:57:56.840 --> 01:57:58.640
[Guest 1]: Lots of things have happened.

01:57:58.640 --> 01:58:03.240
[Guest 1]: But when we went to sort of independent India, we used a slightly different model.

01:58:03.240 --> 01:58:08.320
[Guest 1]: So if you look at the big models of the world, you look at the US, it's college sport that

01:58:08.320 --> 01:58:11.480
[Guest 1]: drives sort of really top class sport.

01:58:11.480 --> 01:58:15.480
[Guest 1]: And actually, I was amazed with a couple of things in just my personal journey.

01:58:15.480 --> 01:58:20.360
[Guest 1]: So I went to the UK, I went to Oxford as a graduate student.

01:58:20.360 --> 01:58:24.720
[Guest 1]: So I'd finished at a national law school, I'd played a pretty high level of cricket

01:58:24.720 --> 01:58:26.280
[Guest 1]: in India.

01:58:26.280 --> 01:58:31.600
[Guest 1]: When I go and turn up at my college, there are 39 colleges at Oxford, every single one

01:58:31.600 --> 01:58:39.320
[Guest 1]: of them had either equal or better facilities than I had used as a state level cricketer.

01:58:39.320 --> 01:58:43.920
[Guest 1]: So state level cricketers, we got four or five games on turf, all the rest was on matting.

01:58:43.920 --> 01:58:47.800
[Guest 1]: We barely got to play in the nets, maybe a few days before the tournament, pretty sort

01:58:47.800 --> 01:58:49.320
[Guest 1]: of decrepit.

01:58:49.320 --> 01:58:55.640
[Guest 1]: I played that level of cricket, I'd never had a physio to work with, what sort of physical

01:58:55.640 --> 01:59:01.200
[Guest 1]: training involved is okay, the nets are starting in sort of 20 minutes, run 10 rounds of Chinnaswamy

01:59:01.200 --> 01:59:03.360
[Guest 1]: Stadium and that's your warm up.

01:59:03.360 --> 01:59:05.360
[Guest 1]: Few stretches seemed like a big deal.

01:59:05.360 --> 01:59:10.120
[Guest 1]: I mean, you talk to some of the Indian cricketers who played in the early 2000s, they did not

01:59:10.120 --> 01:59:13.720
[Guest 1]: have a legitimate physiotherapist.

01:59:13.720 --> 01:59:18.920
[Guest 1]: Like anything happened, what you would get is a doctor popping crocin for you.

01:59:18.920 --> 01:59:25.320
[Guest 1]: Whatever happened, muscle pain, injury, muscle pull, to the crocin was only sort of the Andrew

01:59:25.320 --> 01:59:31.100
[Guest 1]: Lepus and others who come in and change sports science in some ways.

01:59:31.100 --> 01:59:36.040
[Guest 1]: But what I'm getting back to is sort of that notion of access to infrastructure.

01:59:36.040 --> 01:59:42.640
[Guest 1]: If a college and 39 colleges have the equivalent of what maybe 35 states have in India, and

01:59:42.640 --> 01:59:44.760
[Guest 1]: that's in one little town.

01:59:44.760 --> 01:59:49.560
[Guest 1]: And then you go to the US and you look at college sport, and the craziness of college

01:59:49.560 --> 01:59:51.760
[Guest 1]: sport and NCAA football.

01:59:51.760 --> 01:59:56.440
[Guest 1]: And it's only recently, in fact, in the last few months, that that amateurism has been

01:59:56.440 --> 02:00:02.840
[Guest 1]: sort of diluted sort of athletes in the US today cannot be paid zero while college programs

02:00:02.840 --> 02:00:05.160
[Guest 1]: make millions and millions and coaches make millions.

02:00:05.160 --> 02:00:09.760
[Guest 1]: There's a recent case on name, image and likeness and the right to be paid for that.

02:00:09.760 --> 02:00:16.440
[Guest 1]: But they still built an entire culture around an identity which was not necessarily national.

02:00:16.440 --> 02:00:17.600
[Guest 1]: It was parochial.

02:00:17.600 --> 02:00:22.640
[Guest 1]: And I think Ram Guha talks about a lot about this of needing to be parochial for sport.

02:00:22.640 --> 02:00:25.040
[Guest 1]: But you can find your own parochial isms.

02:00:25.040 --> 02:00:31.000
[Guest 1]: And the US founded through colleges, Europe founded through clubs.

02:00:31.000 --> 02:00:32.520
[Guest 1]: So there's a massive club system.

02:00:32.520 --> 02:00:37.680
[Guest 1]: I mean, you look again at Holland, I think, Amsterdam has more hockey pitches, or at least

02:00:37.680 --> 02:00:40.400
[Guest 1]: had more hockey pitches than all of India did.

02:00:40.400 --> 02:00:42.440
[Guest 1]: All of them run by clubs.

02:00:42.440 --> 02:00:43.440
[Guest 1]: What did we do?

02:00:43.440 --> 02:00:46.320
[Guest 1]: We are, again, very state driven.

02:00:46.320 --> 02:00:52.200
[Guest 1]: What we did is we made sure that every decent athlete got a government job.

02:00:52.200 --> 02:00:57.440
[Guest 1]: So there was actually a mandate that the public sector units, many of them have surpluses,

02:00:57.440 --> 02:01:03.000
[Guest 1]: they were forced to employ our athletes that had an element of security.

02:01:03.000 --> 02:01:08.120
[Guest 1]: And like I've said in sort of my piece earlier, and you talked about intermediate rewards,

02:01:08.120 --> 02:01:11.640
[Guest 1]: but it's also where lots of ambitions went to die.

02:01:11.640 --> 02:01:17.040
[Guest 1]: So it was the terminal result and reward that people wanted a government job was secure.

02:01:17.040 --> 02:01:21.620
[Guest 1]: That's where your sort of aspiration ended, because that was seen as the end goal.

02:01:21.620 --> 02:01:25.520
[Guest 1]: So for many years, we ran on sort of the public sector support.

02:01:25.520 --> 02:01:28.240
[Guest 1]: I mean, private sector was nowhere, right?

02:01:28.240 --> 02:01:31.640
[Guest 1]: And it's only in these 2000s that the IPL comes in.

02:01:31.640 --> 02:01:35.440
[Guest 1]: I sort of have my journey, go and study the UK and the US.

02:01:35.440 --> 02:01:39.680
[Guest 1]: I worked for three years at a law firm, I come back to India wanting to do something

02:01:39.680 --> 02:01:41.200
[Guest 1]: meaningful with my skills.

02:01:41.200 --> 02:01:44.560
[Guest 1]: I'm a lawyer, but deeply interested in sport.

02:01:44.560 --> 02:01:47.800
[Guest 1]: And I go around talking to people, people I've played with other people doing great

02:01:47.800 --> 02:01:48.800
[Guest 1]: things in sport.

02:01:48.800 --> 02:01:53.280
[Guest 1]: And when I asked them, which lawyer do you use, they just give me this quizzical look,

02:01:53.280 --> 02:01:54.280
[Guest 1]: what do you mean, lawyer?

02:01:54.280 --> 02:01:55.280
[Guest 1]: Right?

02:01:55.280 --> 02:02:00.720
[Guest 1]: No, never dealt with a lawyer in and that that's the professionalism that Joy talks

02:02:00.720 --> 02:02:01.720
[Guest 1]: about as well.

02:02:01.720 --> 02:02:04.880
[Guest 1]: And to me, for me, the game changed in 2008.

02:02:04.880 --> 02:02:11.600
[Guest 1]: When IMG comes in to the IPL, contracts, sponsorship contracts, franchise agreement, that that

02:02:11.600 --> 02:02:15.800
[Guest 1]: IPL franchise agreement has been copied, I think, 25 different times, and I keep joking

02:02:15.800 --> 02:02:20.520
[Guest 1]: with the IMG lawyers who I know quite well, you have lawyered for all of Indian sport

02:02:20.520 --> 02:02:25.560
[Guest 1]: with that one contract, they've been massacred, but but they still have some of the words

02:02:25.560 --> 02:02:30.620
[Guest 1]: I've seen some of the other leagues where the word IPL still still appears in the contract.

02:02:30.620 --> 02:02:36.580
[Guest 1]: But what you saw there was a gradual professionalization and then a sudden professionalization.

02:02:36.580 --> 02:02:38.360
[Guest 1]: So nothing happened for many years.

02:02:38.360 --> 02:02:44.400
[Guest 1]: But 2008, you suddenly started seeing many, many more people coming in, even if only seasonally

02:02:44.400 --> 02:02:45.400
[Guest 1]: to sport.

02:02:45.400 --> 02:02:50.360
[Guest 1]: So you had many doers, very few heads and very few people thinking sport.

02:02:50.360 --> 02:02:55.280
[Guest 1]: But suddenly you saw that because the money attracted enough professionals to sport.

02:02:55.280 --> 02:02:57.280
[Guest 1]: And then you had the IPL for three months.

02:02:57.280 --> 02:03:01.200
[Guest 1]: But then the other people had another nine months to do something else with.

02:03:01.200 --> 02:03:05.520
[Guest 1]: So a lot of the people who started the other leagues were the product of the IPL, they'd

02:03:05.520 --> 02:03:07.520
[Guest 1]: work within a franchise.

02:03:07.520 --> 02:03:11.560
[Guest 1]: It's not a 12 month league, you have other things to do, your mind is active, you start

02:03:11.560 --> 02:03:12.560
[Guest 1]: doing other things.

02:03:12.560 --> 02:03:17.480
[Guest 1]: And to me, that's where a lot of the sort of democratization, not just from structure,

02:03:17.480 --> 02:03:20.560
[Guest 1]: but just from the market started playing out.

02:03:20.560 --> 02:03:25.760
[Guest 1]: People brought physios in, people brought foreign coaches in, Indian coaches got to work very

02:03:25.760 --> 02:03:26.960
[Guest 1]: closely.

02:03:26.960 --> 02:03:32.440
[Guest 1]: But most importantly of all, I think that divide between foreigner and Indian in the

02:03:32.440 --> 02:03:36.480
[Guest 1]: players minds dissipated and disappeared.

02:03:36.480 --> 02:03:41.360
[Guest 1]: Cricket gets a lot of flack for what it does for other sports.

02:03:41.360 --> 02:03:43.240
[Guest 1]: You don't hear that language anymore.

02:03:43.240 --> 02:03:48.240
[Guest 1]: I think people appreciate what Indian cricket has done for other sports in many ways.

02:03:48.240 --> 02:03:50.040
[Guest 1]: So that world is flat.

02:03:50.040 --> 02:03:54.800
[Guest 1]: I mean, you watch the sort of performance of India and in Australia.

02:03:54.800 --> 02:03:59.240
[Guest 1]: That was a transformative series, not just for cricket, but for Indian sport.

02:03:59.240 --> 02:04:03.840
[Guest 1]: Are you telling me the Indian girls who played that quarterfinal against Australia wouldn't

02:04:03.840 --> 02:04:05.880
[Guest 1]: have had that in their minds?

02:04:05.880 --> 02:04:07.180
[Guest 1]: Absolutely, yes.

02:04:07.180 --> 02:04:11.300
[Guest 1]: So many battles are not fought by the necessarily the same athletes.

02:04:11.300 --> 02:04:16.120
[Guest 1]: But the battles of breaking down competition, believing what is possible is a sort of a

02:04:16.120 --> 02:04:17.720
[Guest 1]: nationwide team.

02:04:17.720 --> 02:04:20.040
[Guest 1]: It's not broken by sport.

02:04:20.040 --> 02:04:25.680
[Guest 1]: And Abhinav Bindra in shooting, you couldn't have a more different sport than than Chavelin.

02:04:25.680 --> 02:04:32.520
[Guest 1]: And still you see Neeraj Chopra sort of attributing some element of his mindset and his mind game

02:04:32.520 --> 02:04:37.000
[Guest 1]: to the fact that Abhinav Bindra went 13 years before.

02:04:37.000 --> 02:04:40.600
[Amit Varma]: So my next question comes out of sort of an aside that sprung to my mind where you spoke

02:04:40.600 --> 02:04:42.480
[Amit Varma]: about the lack of infrastructure.

02:04:42.480 --> 02:04:46.520
[Amit Varma]: Like I'm just thinking of chess, for example, when Anand was coming up in the late 80s as

02:04:46.520 --> 02:04:50.960
[Amit Varma]: a really promising young adolescent and then young teenage player.

02:04:50.960 --> 02:04:56.200
[Amit Varma]: He obviously ran into the Soviet system and the Soviet system had incredible pedagogy.

02:04:56.200 --> 02:05:00.640
[Amit Varma]: Like there is this story about how, you know, Anand would be figuring out things over the

02:05:00.640 --> 02:05:04.760
[Amit Varma]: board concretely calculating and all that at the age of 17 or 18.

02:05:04.760 --> 02:05:08.800
[Amit Varma]: And all of those heuristics had been taught to, you know, his Soviet opponents when they

02:05:08.800 --> 02:05:10.760
[Amit Varma]: were like eight years old or nine years old.

02:05:10.760 --> 02:05:12.120
[Amit Varma]: So it was second nature to them.

02:05:12.120 --> 02:05:13.560
[Amit Varma]: And it wasn't second nature to him.

02:05:13.560 --> 02:05:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And he had to battle that.

02:05:14.960 --> 02:05:19.840
[Amit Varma]: And that is such an enormous achievement getting to the top despite that I often speak about,

02:05:19.840 --> 02:05:23.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, what Anand did was really equal to winning a Formula One race in a Maruti

02:05:23.840 --> 02:05:24.840
[Amit Varma]: 800.

02:05:24.840 --> 02:05:28.400
[Amit Varma]: That's effectively what he did when you consider the infrastructural disadvantages.

02:05:28.400 --> 02:05:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, what you see in modern times is that that's leveled out because of the internet

02:05:33.600 --> 02:05:39.280
[Amit Varma]: and because of this incredibly powerful pedagogical software in the sense that for the last 15

02:05:39.280 --> 02:05:44.040
[Amit Varma]: years or so computers have been much better than humans and they play a huge role in pedagogy

02:05:44.040 --> 02:05:48.920
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, people can play hundreds of thousands of games in a year and just learn

02:05:48.920 --> 02:05:51.160
[Amit Varma]: so much use computers for analysis.

02:05:51.160 --> 02:05:52.800
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of changed everything.

02:05:52.800 --> 02:05:55.840
[Amit Varma]: So now here is a big question that comes up about chess.

02:05:55.840 --> 02:06:00.440
[Amit Varma]: And I'll tell you why I bring it up and in the context of other sports, which is that

02:06:00.440 --> 02:06:04.760
[Amit Varma]: on the one hand, it's true that Anand becoming successful led to a chess boom in India, like

02:06:04.760 --> 02:06:05.760
[Amit Varma]: after him.

02:06:05.760 --> 02:06:08.420
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there was a gap about who the next grandmaster would be.

02:06:08.420 --> 02:06:10.120
[Amit Varma]: It was like Thipsey versus Barua.

02:06:10.120 --> 02:06:11.120
[Amit Varma]: And that was the thing.

02:06:11.120 --> 02:06:12.360
[Amit Varma]: And eventually they both got there.

02:06:12.360 --> 02:06:13.600
[Amit Varma]: And today they're like a dime a dozen.

02:06:13.600 --> 02:06:16.880
[Amit Varma]: I think last year, the squares on a chess board were covered.

02:06:16.880 --> 02:06:20.200
[Amit Varma]: We reached 64 and then we crossed 64 and they're a dime a dozen.

02:06:20.200 --> 02:06:24.160
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, there can be a narrative that Anand led to a chess boom, which is definitely

02:06:24.160 --> 02:06:25.480
[Amit Varma]: true to some extent.

02:06:25.480 --> 02:06:29.560
[Amit Varma]: On the other hand, there is a narrative that it's this democratization of technology and

02:06:29.560 --> 02:06:35.760
[Amit Varma]: pedagogy and infrastructure, as it were, which led to that chess boom and Anand to some extent,

02:06:35.760 --> 02:06:36.760
[Amit Varma]: but also this.

02:06:36.760 --> 02:06:41.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, this leads me to think about what historians call the great man theory of history, where

02:06:41.920 --> 02:06:46.160
[Amit Varma]: there are these severe disagreements between people about whether history is shaped by

02:06:46.160 --> 02:06:49.020
[Amit Varma]: great men or occasionally women.

02:06:49.020 --> 02:06:53.480
[Amit Varma]: But we know how sexist history has generally been in these matters, that you only have

02:06:53.480 --> 02:06:55.400
[Amit Varma]: great men, but is shaped by great men.

02:06:55.400 --> 02:07:00.160
[Amit Varma]: And there's another view that says that there are certain tides and processes to history,

02:07:00.160 --> 02:07:02.520
[Amit Varma]: and we shouldn't ascribe too much credit to individuals.

02:07:02.520 --> 02:07:07.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, when I think on Indian sport, it seems to me that there are many inflection points,

02:07:07.560 --> 02:07:11.660
[Amit Varma]: which tie into the great man theory or the great moment theory, like for Indian cricket,

02:07:11.660 --> 02:07:16.440
[Amit Varma]: you can say 1983 made a big difference, you know, or you could say the IPL made a big

02:07:16.440 --> 02:07:17.440
[Amit Varma]: difference.

02:07:17.440 --> 02:07:19.980
[Amit Varma]: And I do believe both of those certainly made a difference.

02:07:19.980 --> 02:07:23.580
[Amit Varma]: For the great man theory, you spoke about, you know, how Bindra's gold medal made a great

02:07:23.580 --> 02:07:28.280
[Amit Varma]: difference in terms of self belief and the perceptions that people had towards the sport.

02:07:28.280 --> 02:07:30.480
[Amit Varma]: Equally, you know, you can look at Gopichand.

02:07:30.480 --> 02:07:34.940
[Amit Varma]: If Gopichand did not exist, would badminton be where it is today?

02:07:34.940 --> 02:07:38.760
[Amit Varma]: And I think there's an argument there to be made that no, perhaps it would not.

02:07:38.760 --> 02:07:42.760
[Amit Varma]: Even with say, why do so many of our women wrestlers from Haryana do well, and that has

02:07:42.760 --> 02:07:47.240
[Amit Varma]: to do with the happenstance of you know, in the late 70s, great coach Chandigarh, who

02:07:47.240 --> 02:07:51.160
[Amit Varma]: doesn't have any sons, gets the news that the Olympics is now going to open up wrestling

02:07:51.160 --> 02:07:52.160
[Amit Varma]: to women.

02:07:52.160 --> 02:07:56.040
[Amit Varma]: So he trains his daughters and one of his assistant coaches is Mahavir Singh Phogat.

02:07:56.040 --> 02:07:57.520
[Amit Varma]: And he does the same thing.

02:07:57.520 --> 02:08:00.520
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and that ecosystem suddenly comes up.

02:08:00.520 --> 02:08:06.600
[Amit Varma]: So what is sort of your take on this on the importance of these sort of inflection points?

02:08:06.600 --> 02:08:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And would it be the case that Indian sport is now reaching a stage of maturity, where

02:08:11.000 --> 02:08:15.440
[Amit Varma]: we don't need these anymore, where we are progressing along a certain route, we will

02:08:15.440 --> 02:08:16.440
[Amit Varma]: get there.

02:08:16.440 --> 02:08:20.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, we are not reliant on individual inspirational figures or individual people

02:08:20.360 --> 02:08:24.880
[Amit Varma]: like Gopichand to set up something, but that there is a broader movement that has now begun

02:08:24.880 --> 02:08:28.040
[Amit Varma]: and that has a momentum of its own.

02:08:28.040 --> 02:08:29.040
[Guest 2]: Here's my take on it.

02:08:29.040 --> 02:08:35.040
[Guest 2]: And I'm, again, as I said, all this is very much a matter of debate.

02:08:35.040 --> 02:08:39.280
[Guest 2]: I feel that sport, more than anything else, requires heroes.

02:08:39.280 --> 02:08:40.600
[Guest 2]: It requires heroes and heroines.

02:08:40.600 --> 02:08:45.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, I use it in a completely non-sexual sense, more than anything else, because the

02:08:45.320 --> 02:08:47.080
[Guest 2]: inspirational factor cannot come there.

02:08:47.080 --> 02:08:53.080
[Guest 2]: And I'll take an example, which is not mentioned by any of you, which is to do with football.

02:08:53.080 --> 02:08:57.880
[Guest 2]: I mean, Northeast football, OK, you have Tao, who is 1948.

02:08:57.880 --> 02:09:03.260
[Guest 2]: He's the captain of the 1948 Olympic team, very respected man, plays in Calcutta football.

02:09:03.260 --> 02:09:06.500
[Guest 2]: You have a couple of people in the 80s, Pem Dorji plays in the 80s.

02:09:06.500 --> 02:09:11.280
[Guest 2]: But it's Baichung Bhutia who opens the tap to the Northeast.

02:09:11.280 --> 02:09:12.680
[Guest 2]: And I'll take you through that.

02:09:12.680 --> 02:09:18.400
[Guest 2]: If you look at 93, 94, Baichung Bhutia comes, starts playing for East Bengal, starts playing

02:09:18.400 --> 02:09:22.400
[Guest 2]: soccer, and suddenly the entire Northeast is open.

02:09:22.400 --> 02:09:28.520
[Guest 2]: And then within the next 7, 8, 10 years, you'll find the teams dominated, men's teams, women's

02:09:28.520 --> 02:09:30.800
[Guest 2]: teams dominated by the Northeast.

02:09:30.800 --> 02:09:38.000
[Guest 2]: And I think because sport is all about dreaming, I feel individuals play a far bigger factor

02:09:38.000 --> 02:09:41.160
[Guest 2]: than they do normally.

02:09:41.160 --> 02:09:45.160
[Guest 2]: It's easy for you to turn around and say that if it hadn't been Abhinav Bindra, somebody

02:09:45.160 --> 02:09:46.520
[Guest 2]: else would have done it.

02:09:46.520 --> 02:09:49.560
[Guest 2]: I don't believe that's necessarily true.

02:09:49.560 --> 02:09:54.600
[Guest 2]: The unique set of circumstances that made Abhinav Bindra a champion are probably difficult

02:09:54.600 --> 02:09:56.880
[Guest 2]: to replicate, because he were two, three things.

02:09:56.880 --> 02:10:02.440
[Guest 2]: He had the money, he had the means, but he also had that complete perfectionist phase.

02:10:02.440 --> 02:10:07.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, think about a fact about thinking about that I'm going to play in an auditorium,

02:10:07.640 --> 02:10:08.640
[Guest 2]: which is very large.

02:10:08.640 --> 02:10:12.960
[Guest 2]: So instead of shooting in my shooting gallery, which is small, I need to shoot in a large

02:10:12.960 --> 02:10:16.760
[Guest 2]: place just to get used to that hall I'll be in Beijing.

02:10:16.760 --> 02:10:20.680
[Guest 2]: That's the kind of detailing that an insane guy does.

02:10:20.680 --> 02:10:25.840
[Guest 2]: And I'm sorry that it's easy to turn around and say that history will, somebody else like

02:10:25.840 --> 02:10:29.040
[Guest 2]: Abhinav Bindra would have turned up, but the odds are against it.

02:10:29.040 --> 02:10:33.520
[Guest 2]: And that's why, again, you look at history, you look at 1983.

02:10:33.520 --> 02:10:37.080
[Guest 2]: Had India not won in 83, would the cricket have been the same?

02:10:37.080 --> 02:10:42.000
[Guest 2]: Well, I can tell you one thing, you know, for all recorded history there is, we certainly

02:10:42.000 --> 02:10:44.520
[Guest 2]: wouldn't have bid for a World Cup in 1987.

02:10:44.520 --> 02:10:49.360
[Guest 2]: Had we not won in 83, all of them were planning, they thought they'd lose, and they were going

02:10:49.360 --> 02:10:51.880
[Guest 2]: for a holiday to the US after that.

02:10:51.880 --> 02:10:56.160
[Guest 2]: Had that happened, would the 1987 World Cup happened in India?

02:10:56.160 --> 02:10:57.520
[Guest 2]: And I don't think it would have.

02:10:57.520 --> 02:11:03.160
[Guest 2]: So I feel that, you know, this great man theory or great woman theory, I mean, there's no

02:11:03.160 --> 02:11:04.840
[Guest 2]: this thing involved in that.

02:11:04.840 --> 02:11:09.880
[Guest 2]: I think for sport, you need those kind of lucky breaks, you need those kind of once

02:11:09.880 --> 02:11:11.840
[Guest 2]: in a generational breaks.

02:11:11.840 --> 02:11:16.400
[Guest 2]: And I'd be really interested in hearing what Nandan has to say about that.

02:11:16.400 --> 02:11:21.320
[Guest 1]: I mean, I largely agree and a lot of my work has been related to that is to create that

02:11:21.320 --> 02:11:25.360
[Guest 1]: one example, which which what we call changes the script.

02:11:25.360 --> 02:11:30.640
[Guest 1]: And that's that's a hashtag we use quite often, which is, we came in 2006, 7, I just found

02:11:30.640 --> 02:11:34.600
[Guest 1]: so much cynicism about Indian sport, it was so different from the conversation we've just

02:11:34.600 --> 02:11:39.280
[Guest 1]: had around the Tokyo Games, where there was disappointment coming from expectation.

02:11:39.280 --> 02:11:44.160
[Guest 1]: Earlier, it was disappointment coming from just sort of, we're not good enough.

02:11:44.160 --> 02:11:45.800
[Guest 1]: And this really doesn't matter.

02:11:45.800 --> 02:11:50.360
[Guest 1]: And I just wanted to get out of that cynicism and start doing something it was I was a lawyer,

02:11:50.360 --> 02:11:52.400
[Guest 1]: but I had a great interest in sport.

02:11:52.400 --> 02:11:56.000
[Guest 1]: So I just said, Now, can we create new path breakers?

02:11:56.000 --> 02:12:00.760
[Guest 1]: So I believe, okay, there's you, I can accept we don't have a sports culture.

02:12:00.760 --> 02:12:03.160
[Guest 1]: How am I going to change people's mindsets?

02:12:03.160 --> 02:12:06.400
[Guest 1]: I'm not going to tell them, hey, you don't know what you're doing.

02:12:06.400 --> 02:12:09.760
[Guest 1]: You don't think like me, and we're good at sport.

02:12:09.760 --> 02:12:17.520
[Guest 1]: But what can I do, I can create new examples, I can present new evidence, and allow people

02:12:17.520 --> 02:12:21.480
[Guest 1]: to consider that evidence and see, am I willing to change my mind.

02:12:21.480 --> 02:12:22.480
[Guest 1]: And that takes time, right?

02:12:22.480 --> 02:12:28.240
[Guest 1]: So what we did is working with, in some sense, the unusual and the unexpected.

02:12:28.240 --> 02:12:34.080
[Guest 1]: So looking at sports, which had not been supported, looking at disciplines, which mean may not

02:12:34.080 --> 02:12:36.120
[Guest 1]: have had an Olympian yet.

02:12:36.120 --> 02:12:42.520
[Guest 1]: So looking at diversity, not for its own sake, but for its ability to create that trailblazer

02:12:42.520 --> 02:12:48.000
[Guest 1]: pathbreaker, I mean, these are sort of a little bit hyperbolic, but that person who creates

02:12:48.000 --> 02:12:52.160
[Guest 1]: the first example, and I'll reconnect that to my story of being that person asked, do

02:12:52.160 --> 02:12:53.160
[Guest 1]: you want to be a lawyer?

02:12:53.160 --> 02:12:57.720
[Guest 1]: Or do you want to be a cricketer asked that question by the National Law School director,

02:12:57.720 --> 02:13:00.640
[Guest 1]: I might still choose to be a lawyer.

02:13:00.640 --> 02:13:03.040
[Guest 1]: But has that ratio changed?

02:13:03.040 --> 02:13:05.520
[Guest 1]: I mean, for me, it was at 595.

02:13:05.520 --> 02:13:07.220
[Guest 1]: How do I get that ratio to change?

02:13:07.220 --> 02:13:12.360
[Guest 1]: How do I get people, key stakeholders and by that the most key stakeholder is actually

02:13:12.360 --> 02:13:15.000
[Guest 1]: the parent of the sports child.

02:13:15.000 --> 02:13:20.480
[Guest 1]: I think we underestimate the importance of what is going on in the parent's head.

02:13:20.480 --> 02:13:25.400
[Guest 1]: And the conversation the parent has with the child, very rarely does a child decide what

02:13:25.400 --> 02:13:26.580
[Guest 1]: sport they play.

02:13:26.580 --> 02:13:31.440
[Guest 1]: Very often, it's the parent who initiates, the child might sort of click.

02:13:31.440 --> 02:13:35.940
[Guest 1]: But the motivation is very often parental motivation.

02:13:35.940 --> 02:13:40.280
[Guest 1]: And you look at the great Indian athletes, so many of them have super motivated and very

02:13:40.280 --> 02:13:43.680
[Guest 1]: often sporting parents who go to extremes.

02:13:43.680 --> 02:13:47.960
[Guest 1]: And it's something worth talking about is how difficult it is to be the parent of a

02:13:47.960 --> 02:13:50.680
[Guest 1]: talented sports child today.

02:13:50.680 --> 02:13:57.240
[Guest 1]: But the reality is, if we can change that conversation, the one that the child has with

02:13:57.240 --> 02:14:02.700
[Guest 1]: the parent, and to me that those single people help change that conversation.

02:14:02.700 --> 02:14:09.120
[Guest 1]: If a young person says, hey, I want to pursue fencing, what is the natural question a parent

02:14:09.120 --> 02:14:10.120
[Guest 1]: is going to ask?

02:14:10.120 --> 02:14:15.400
[Guest 1]: The parent is going to ask, show me one person who has made a living out of fencing.

02:14:15.400 --> 02:14:19.000
[Guest 1]: Now India has that answer.

02:14:19.000 --> 02:14:25.200
[Guest 1]: And I think that in my belief, you can change perceptions one athlete at a time.

02:14:25.200 --> 02:14:28.680
[Guest 1]: And you are not going to go and say, hey, now change your perception that we can have

02:14:28.680 --> 02:14:30.200
[Guest 1]: an Indian fencer.

02:14:30.200 --> 02:14:31.800
[Guest 1]: The performance speaks for itself.

02:14:31.800 --> 02:14:34.120
[Guest 1]: And that's the beauty of the Olympics.

02:14:34.120 --> 02:14:38.560
[Guest 1]: We don't need to say she's a good fencer, she's gone out, done what she needs to do.

02:14:38.560 --> 02:14:43.520
[Guest 1]: The next person aspiring to be a fencer, or for that matter, not even in sport, aspiring

02:14:43.520 --> 02:14:48.600
[Guest 1]: to do something that has not been done before, it is a conversation changer.

02:14:48.600 --> 02:14:53.440
[Guest 1]: So I do believe and I agree with Joy that one athlete can change trajectories.

02:14:53.440 --> 02:14:57.880
[Guest 1]: And there's this notion of path dependency as well, right, the path that is tread.

02:14:57.880 --> 02:15:03.600
[Guest 1]: The one thing I will add to that is there can be also confluences of events, where that

02:15:03.600 --> 02:15:06.960
[Guest 1]: great athlete comes along with something else.

02:15:06.960 --> 02:15:12.600
[Guest 1]: And I think we saw the sort of the airwaves and the privatization of the airwaves come

02:15:12.600 --> 02:15:14.720
[Guest 1]: with Tendulkar as well, right?

02:15:14.720 --> 02:15:20.140
[Guest 1]: And those are sort of, that's a double whammy competition in distribution, but also this

02:15:20.140 --> 02:15:22.160
[Guest 1]: great athlete coming through.

02:15:22.160 --> 02:15:27.880
[Guest 1]: You saw the 2007 World Cup coming with the IPL.

02:15:27.880 --> 02:15:34.440
[Guest 1]: The IPL without the 2007 T20 World Cup win would have been nothing, I mean, not nothing,

02:15:34.440 --> 02:15:39.480
[Guest 1]: but it gave it its sort of fumes, the Yuvaraj Singh 6-6s.

02:15:39.480 --> 02:15:45.080
[Guest 1]: So there can be groupings of events to me that become this catalyzing effect, which

02:15:45.080 --> 02:15:49.360
[Guest 1]: may, if one of them happened alone, may not have been adequate.

02:15:49.360 --> 02:15:53.720
[Guest 1]: So that's sort of the addition I would make to one person can change it, but there can

02:15:53.720 --> 02:15:56.080
[Guest 1]: be something else that gives it its fuel.

02:15:56.080 --> 02:16:00.000
[Guest 1]: So timing can bring fortune, timing can bring confluence.

02:16:00.000 --> 02:16:05.760
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with both of you entirely, and I think individual dreamers like that can

02:16:05.760 --> 02:16:07.040
[Amit Varma]: have that kind of impact.

02:16:07.040 --> 02:16:11.640
[Amit Varma]: But I think what a sports administrator really has to do is find a way to enable the dreamers

02:16:11.640 --> 02:16:14.960
[Amit Varma]: and to enable the dreaming and to make it seem practical.

02:16:14.960 --> 02:16:19.160
[Amit Varma]: Before I move on to my next question, Nandan, I didn't at all finish that whole personal

02:16:19.160 --> 02:16:22.360
[Amit Varma]: narrative of what your arc was like, which always interests me a lot.

02:16:22.360 --> 02:16:26.840
[Amit Varma]: So let's quickly finish that arc that you're given that choice when you get into law school,

02:16:26.840 --> 02:16:30.720
[Amit Varma]: you get your law degree, you go to Oxford on a road scholarship, whereas you pointed

02:16:30.720 --> 02:16:34.200
[Amit Varma]: out every single college had better sporting infrastructure than your state.

02:16:34.200 --> 02:16:36.200
[Amit Varma]: And then you go to Harvard Law School.

02:16:36.200 --> 02:16:37.680
[Amit Varma]: And then you work three years abroad.

02:16:37.680 --> 02:16:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And then you say, I'm not going to do this, I'm going to come back to India and do something

02:16:41.000 --> 02:16:42.600
[Amit Varma]: for Indian sport.

02:16:42.600 --> 02:16:45.360
[Amit Varma]: That seems so baffling and incredible to me.

02:16:45.360 --> 02:16:46.760
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about that.

02:16:46.760 --> 02:16:49.160
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about, you know, how could you make that choice?

02:16:49.160 --> 02:16:50.160
[Amit Varma]: What motivated you?

02:16:50.160 --> 02:16:54.400
[Amit Varma]: Did you have specifics in mind that I will do ABC, or were you like that?

02:16:54.400 --> 02:16:58.960
[Amit Varma]: And I'm going to go and figure it out, and I want to do something.

02:16:58.960 --> 02:16:59.960
[Guest 1]: It was more the latter.

02:16:59.960 --> 02:17:03.680
[Guest 1]: I mean, so I mean, I'd done what I needed to do, I just felt I'd spent my 20s.

02:17:03.680 --> 02:17:09.040
[Guest 1]: I mean, I got so much privilege, so many opportunities, choose the place I wanted to study, and I'd

02:17:09.040 --> 02:17:11.200
[Guest 1]: gotten, I'd got these chances.

02:17:11.200 --> 02:17:15.400
[Guest 1]: And I'd given myself essentially six years, I'd said, I'm going to study for three years,

02:17:15.400 --> 02:17:16.640
[Guest 1]: work for three years.

02:17:16.640 --> 02:17:21.640
[Guest 1]: And I need to I need to be back, I mean, call me whatever it is, I could call me patriotic,

02:17:21.640 --> 02:17:23.200
[Guest 1]: you could call me a homebody.

02:17:23.200 --> 02:17:29.320
[Guest 1]: I just wanted to be home, and wanted to start figuring out where I can make a contribution

02:17:29.320 --> 02:17:30.800
[Guest 1]: and be useful.

02:17:30.800 --> 02:17:37.600
[Guest 1]: And in some sense, sport just found me again, I wanted to do sport, but it just the things

02:17:37.600 --> 02:17:43.520
[Guest 1]: around me started, I'd done a lot by then, a lot of work on internet law, technology

02:17:43.520 --> 02:17:48.720
[Guest 1]: law, intellectual property, all of which started becoming extremely useful in my sports law

02:17:48.720 --> 02:17:49.960
[Guest 1]: practice.

02:17:49.960 --> 02:17:53.240
[Guest 1]: I wanted to do sports law, but it didn't automatically come through.

02:17:53.240 --> 02:17:56.960
[Guest 1]: Like I said, the IPL happens, lots of the people I played cricket with come back to

02:17:56.960 --> 02:17:58.960
[Guest 1]: me and ask me legal questions.

02:17:58.960 --> 02:18:02.080
[Guest 1]: So in some sense, sport reclaimed me.

02:18:02.080 --> 02:18:06.720
[Guest 1]: And I think that that original love just was never lost.

02:18:06.720 --> 02:18:10.920
[Guest 1]: And it attracted me back in a way that I really can't explain.

02:18:10.920 --> 02:18:16.480
[Guest 1]: But I sort of dealt with each opportunity as it came, first started trying to work with

02:18:16.480 --> 02:18:23.520
[Guest 1]: athletes represent them, but then move to a much more sort of use my skills well, and

02:18:23.520 --> 02:18:29.440
[Guest 1]: my skills were law, and backed into working in sports law, sports regulation, sports governance,

02:18:29.440 --> 02:18:33.840
[Guest 1]: but also figuring out how to buffer that there wasn't a huge amount of work to do.

02:18:33.840 --> 02:18:39.160
[Guest 1]: So I also continued working on technology law, internet law, which were my specialties,

02:18:39.160 --> 02:18:43.800
[Guest 1]: but then also started the foundation with a couple of other colleagues, in fact, from

02:18:43.800 --> 02:18:50.120
[Guest 1]: my same school, where we really felt we had to sort of stop being so cynical, not be the

02:18:50.120 --> 02:18:55.000
[Guest 1]: people who are sitting there cursing the television and say, Okay, I mean, we may not be experts,

02:18:55.000 --> 02:18:57.200
[Guest 1]: we don't have the money, we don't have the expertise.

02:18:57.200 --> 02:19:02.120
[Guest 1]: But what we do have is intent and desire and just a love for sport, which should count

02:19:02.120 --> 02:19:07.960
[Guest 1]: for something sort of incorporated a nonprofit, a trust, Go Sports Foundation is what it ended

02:19:07.960 --> 02:19:08.960
[Guest 1]: up becoming.

02:19:08.960 --> 02:19:10.440
[Guest 1]: For years, it was extremely difficult.

02:19:10.440 --> 02:19:16.000
[Guest 1]: I mean, there's so much cynicism, not just in people watching, but we ask someone for

02:19:16.000 --> 02:19:17.000
[Guest 1]: money.

02:19:17.000 --> 02:19:18.000
[Guest 1]: And they say, like, why are you wasting your time?

02:19:18.000 --> 02:19:23.280
[Guest 1]: I mean, the people closest to me would have thought of me as and did think of me as extremely

02:19:23.280 --> 02:19:24.280
[Guest 1]: naive.

02:19:24.280 --> 02:19:28.720
[Guest 1]: It sounds like an absurd thing to do, right, you're giving up a law firm career, the sort

02:19:28.720 --> 02:19:33.880
[Guest 1]: of the most structured profession you can think of in the US most disciplined, you get

02:19:33.880 --> 02:19:37.820
[Guest 1]: want something done, it gets done in five minutes or 10 minutes.

02:19:37.820 --> 02:19:41.320
[Guest 1]: You don't send an email out without reading it five times to make sure there's every full

02:19:41.320 --> 02:19:47.200
[Guest 1]: stop and comma and come into the disorganized world of Indian sport, but there's something

02:19:47.200 --> 02:19:48.880
[Guest 1]: attracted me to it.

02:19:48.880 --> 02:19:55.440
[Guest 1]: And I think looking back, a lot of it is what sport gave me for identity, for confidence,

02:19:55.440 --> 02:19:57.280
[Guest 1]: for who I became.

02:19:57.280 --> 02:20:03.280
[Guest 1]: And also the skills that it gave me to navigate the world and life, even my educational opportunities,

02:20:03.280 --> 02:20:08.040
[Guest 1]: I saw everything as something that could be gamified, something that you could figure

02:20:08.040 --> 02:20:11.080
[Guest 1]: out the rules, play by the rules do well.

02:20:11.080 --> 02:20:14.000
[Guest 1]: It gave me a lot of the tools to navigate the world.

02:20:14.000 --> 02:20:18.400
[Guest 1]: And I started asking the broader questions of if it made some difference to me, can I

02:20:18.400 --> 02:20:22.000
[Guest 1]: make it count similarly for other people.

02:20:22.000 --> 02:20:25.840
[Guest 1]: And I wouldn't call any of the things I've gone through as scars, they were just more

02:20:25.840 --> 02:20:30.560
[Guest 1]: observations of my own sort of being self critical of the life I'd lived.

02:20:30.560 --> 02:20:35.840
[Guest 1]: I just felt from those learnings can something positive emerge and having had those opportunities,

02:20:35.840 --> 02:20:42.560
[Guest 1]: time to flip it and do something meaningful, that counts for other people.

02:20:42.560 --> 02:20:47.560
[Guest 1]: And using sport as a tool, which I thought was heavily underdone in our country.

02:20:47.560 --> 02:20:51.800
[Guest 1]: Sport as a tool, not just for winning and identity and other things, but just sport

02:20:51.800 --> 02:20:56.720
[Guest 1]: as a tool for living a better life at an individual level.

02:20:56.720 --> 02:21:03.600
[Guest 1]: And in some sense, crafting a better society, a place where all of us sort of pursue excellence,

02:21:03.600 --> 02:21:08.040
[Guest 1]: work on friendship, work on respect and just the spirit of Olympism.

02:21:08.040 --> 02:21:11.960
[Guest 1]: Looking back now I hear all these words, but I think they were just intrinsic, that motivation

02:21:11.960 --> 02:21:17.880
[Guest 1]: to work on these projects for that sake was just extremely intrinsic and just a lived

02:21:17.880 --> 02:21:20.440
[Guest 1]: experience which I wanted to share in some sense.

02:21:20.440 --> 02:21:25.840
[Guest 1]: So it wasn't any great altruism, I was just trying to find what I thought was a life worth

02:21:25.840 --> 02:21:33.920
[Guest 1]: living and finding in some sense the joy in sharing what I found as meaningful.

02:21:33.920 --> 02:21:37.640
[Amit Varma]: So before I get to you know, the specifics of what you know, your foundation does, which

02:21:37.640 --> 02:21:41.380
[Amit Varma]: I'm very keen to learn more about a final broad question, you know, you mentioned the

02:21:41.380 --> 02:21:44.840
[Amit Varma]: little kid who goes to his mom and says, Hey, I want to do fencing and the mom says, you

02:21:44.840 --> 02:21:49.640
[Amit Varma]: know, but who is there who has been successful and now that kid can point to someone, but

02:21:49.640 --> 02:21:53.600
[Amit Varma]: most of the time, like if a kid was to come to me, I would say that yeah, there is someone

02:21:53.600 --> 02:21:55.440
[Amit Varma]: but that is survivorship bias.

02:21:55.440 --> 02:21:59.160
[Amit Varma]: Is there an ecosystem, there's no ecosystem here, I don't see any league, I don't see

02:21:59.160 --> 02:22:00.160
[Amit Varma]: anything.

02:22:00.160 --> 02:22:01.240
[Amit Varma]: It's a scene in the unseen, right?

02:22:01.240 --> 02:22:05.000
[Amit Varma]: The scene is that one kid who makes it, the unseen is the many, many other countless kids

02:22:05.000 --> 02:22:06.080
[Amit Varma]: who don't make it.

02:22:06.080 --> 02:22:09.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, there is an opportunity cost for them for pursuing that.

02:22:09.080 --> 02:22:13.000
[Amit Varma]: So I would say ki nahi yaar, woh Nandan ki tarah ban jaa, law kar le.

02:22:13.000 --> 02:22:15.920
[Amit Varma]: And this is not something you would say to someone in cricket necessarily, because there

02:22:15.920 --> 02:22:17.720
[Amit Varma]: is that rich ecosystem.

02:22:17.720 --> 02:22:22.680
[Amit Varma]: Now it strikes me that when you set out to do whatever you do, the first goal would

02:22:22.680 --> 02:22:27.440
[Amit Varma]: obviously be that, okay, let us support the athletes who are there, that who are the talented

02:22:27.440 --> 02:22:29.680
[Amit Varma]: kids in whatever sports, let's support them.

02:22:29.680 --> 02:22:33.220
[Amit Varma]: Your second goal down the road, though, has to be to build that ecosystem.

02:22:33.220 --> 02:22:37.160
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, then, you know, instead of giving a boy a fish, you're teaching him how to fish,

02:22:37.160 --> 02:22:43.480
[Amit Varma]: you're building an ecosystem which will produce its own stars, which will enable whoever wants

02:22:43.480 --> 02:22:45.800
[Amit Varma]: to dream within that ecosystem.

02:22:45.800 --> 02:22:49.100
[Amit Varma]: Now, this would seem to be an incredibly tough thing to do.

02:22:49.100 --> 02:22:53.400
[Amit Varma]: But I would also imagine that, as I said, for futurists, as I often say, for creators,

02:22:53.400 --> 02:22:57.640
[Amit Varma]: that we can tend to overestimate the short term, but underestimate the long term.

02:22:57.640 --> 02:23:01.320
[Amit Varma]: Now both of you have sort of worked at creating these ecosystems.

02:23:01.320 --> 02:23:05.480
[Amit Varma]: In fact, my episode with Joy earlier was called creating sports ecosystems, if I remember

02:23:05.480 --> 02:23:09.480
[Amit Varma]: right, because, you know, you did a lot of work with during the football time of not

02:23:09.480 --> 02:23:14.160
[Amit Varma]: just holding an event, but trying to introduce a culture of football across the country.

02:23:14.160 --> 02:23:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And that was such an inspiring conversation for me to have.

02:23:17.760 --> 02:23:22.680
[Amit Varma]: So I'd love your thoughts on one, in your experience of working with sport over the

02:23:22.680 --> 02:23:27.480
[Amit Varma]: last decade and a half or so, longer than that, but in this specific context, that has

02:23:27.480 --> 02:23:31.680
[Amit Varma]: there been a sense that yes, ecosystems can evolve, we should not be cynical.

02:23:31.680 --> 02:23:35.760
[Amit Varma]: Today, there may not be an ecosystem for say, fencing, five years later, they can be we

02:23:35.760 --> 02:23:40.040
[Amit Varma]: should have that hope we should work towards that, or at on certain margins, has it ever

02:23:40.040 --> 02:23:46.080
[Amit Varma]: gotten frustrating that we are supporting talented sports people, but these are individuals,

02:23:46.080 --> 02:23:48.300
[Amit Varma]: there's nothing broader and deeper happening.

02:23:48.300 --> 02:23:51.800
[Amit Varma]: So what's your sort of sense of that?

02:23:51.800 --> 02:23:58.960
[Guest 2]: So my sense of that is that definitely there is a much larger ecosystem than there was.

02:23:58.960 --> 02:24:03.600
[Guest 2]: And again, what we were talking about the fact that there is a private public partnership,

02:24:03.600 --> 02:24:07.600
[Guest 2]: something is happening, there is movement happening in sport, there is definitely movement

02:24:07.600 --> 02:24:12.520
[Guest 2]: happening in sport, how well it's doing and how long term it is, is the basic question

02:24:12.520 --> 02:24:13.680
[Guest 2]: that you have to ask yourself.

02:24:13.680 --> 02:24:20.240
[Guest 2]: And I think that, you know, when you're coming to it, Indian sport now is well served at

02:24:20.240 --> 02:24:21.240
[Guest 2]: the top level.

02:24:21.240 --> 02:24:27.400
[Guest 2]: I think now between tops and Olympic gold quest, because remember, even more than this

02:24:27.400 --> 02:24:32.120
[Guest 2]: thing, a lot of these people are saying they are very goal oriented, they are middle oriented,

02:24:32.120 --> 02:24:37.280
[Guest 2]: and their reasons to be because funding, the sad bad fact of it is that, you know, and

02:24:37.280 --> 02:24:38.560
[Guest 2]: Nandan tries his best.

02:24:38.560 --> 02:24:43.360
[Guest 2]: And I know this is a very tough struggle to turn on and say that it's about the process,

02:24:43.360 --> 02:24:44.360
[Guest 2]: not about the medals.

02:24:44.360 --> 02:24:48.600
[Guest 2]: And it's, it's something that they actually go sports foundation talks about to people

02:24:48.600 --> 02:24:52.480
[Guest 2]: who are, you know, trying to help them, you know, supporting this ecosystem.

02:24:52.480 --> 02:24:59.600
[Guest 2]: But the fact of the matter is, medals matter, newspaper articles matter, you know, even

02:24:59.600 --> 02:25:03.760
[Guest 2]: if a Deepak Karmakar does not get there to a medal place, at least she's there to place

02:25:03.760 --> 02:25:06.800
[Guest 2]: where she's bought attention to gymnastics, you know.

02:25:06.800 --> 02:25:11.400
[Guest 2]: So tomorrow, if there's a gymnastics athlete, somebody in the world of gymnastics is easier

02:25:11.400 --> 02:25:15.120
[Guest 2]: for somebody to invest in and turn on and say that, okay, I like Deepak, there's something

02:25:15.120 --> 02:25:16.120
[Guest 2]: here.

02:25:16.120 --> 02:25:19.240
[Guest 2]: So I think the top level is well served.

02:25:19.240 --> 02:25:23.560
[Guest 2]: I think the level below that, because it's in the hands of the Federation, and state

02:25:23.560 --> 02:25:29.040
[Guest 2]: federations more than anything else, is really badly served at this point in time, it's tough,

02:25:29.040 --> 02:25:36.040
[Guest 2]: it's difficult, because we basically create an ecosystem where we and this is true of

02:25:36.040 --> 02:25:37.040
[Guest 2]: all sports.

02:25:37.040 --> 02:25:41.800
[Guest 2]: So for example, I'll give you another example, in the 2017 World Cup, you know, the first

02:25:41.800 --> 02:25:46.040
[Guest 2]: thing we went around when Javier and me joined as, you know, project director and tournament

02:25:46.040 --> 02:25:49.840
[Guest 2]: director was, how good is the Indian team, do we have a chance?

02:25:49.840 --> 02:25:53.440
[Guest 2]: And they turned on and they said something which is interesting, they said, we have 30-35

02:25:53.440 --> 02:25:59.340
[Guest 2]: kids, we're going to put into a camp and give the best exposure for the next three years.

02:25:59.340 --> 02:26:00.720
[Guest 2]: But what does that mean?

02:26:00.720 --> 02:26:03.520
[Guest 2]: Does any developed country do that?

02:26:03.520 --> 02:26:04.520
[Guest 2]: Will Brazil do that?

02:26:04.520 --> 02:26:06.080
[Guest 2]: Will Argentina do that?

02:26:06.080 --> 02:26:11.920
[Guest 2]: They look at the best, most talented 40 kids three months before, six months before, and

02:26:11.920 --> 02:26:15.080
[Guest 2]: then get those in and decide which ones are going to play.

02:26:15.080 --> 02:26:18.880
[Guest 2]: But we don't have that luxury, because we know that if we do that, these kids will just

02:26:18.880 --> 02:26:21.000
[Guest 2]: not have enough exposure.

02:26:21.000 --> 02:26:22.000
[Guest 2]: So what do we do?

02:26:22.000 --> 02:26:27.720
[Guest 2]: We identify X number of kids, we put them together very early, and we hope we do that.

02:26:27.720 --> 02:26:32.400
[Guest 2]: So that's, Amit, what we're doing well.

02:26:32.400 --> 02:26:39.160
[Guest 2]: If an athlete is somewhere close to being Olympic worthy, medal worthy, I think today

02:26:39.160 --> 02:26:47.280
[Guest 2]: GoSport, TOPS, JSW, OGQ, all are getting together to do a very, very decent job of making sure

02:26:47.280 --> 02:26:52.340
[Guest 2]: that they lack for nothing in those last 20 yards.

02:26:52.340 --> 02:26:55.800
[Guest 2]: But if you're looking at, say, if you think of it, you know, if you look at the analogy

02:26:55.800 --> 02:27:01.160
[Guest 2]: as an Olympic sprint, it's like saying the first 80 meters of that 100-meter sprint,

02:27:01.160 --> 02:27:02.520
[Guest 2]: there's nobody.

02:27:02.520 --> 02:27:06.920
[Guest 2]: The last 20 meters, dude, we have all the support in the world you want.

02:27:06.920 --> 02:27:11.440
[Guest 2]: And it's the first 80 meters, unfortunately, who does it rest with?

02:27:11.440 --> 02:27:17.640
[Guest 2]: It rests with state organizations, it rests with organizations who don't really see results

02:27:17.640 --> 02:27:18.640
[Guest 2]: at that stage.

02:27:18.640 --> 02:27:22.440
[Guest 2]: And that's the real lacuna in the system.

02:27:22.440 --> 02:27:24.920
[Guest 2]: And let me tell you one thing, there are two factors that are involved in it.

02:27:24.920 --> 02:27:29.600
[Guest 2]: One is the fact that our federations are inefficient, which, unfortunately, you know, I've said

02:27:29.600 --> 02:27:35.840
[Guest 2]: ad infinitum, but the second part of it is we really don't have a culture of checks and

02:27:35.840 --> 02:27:36.840
[Guest 2]: balances.

02:27:36.840 --> 02:27:38.800
[Guest 2]: Who will the checks and balances come?

02:27:38.800 --> 02:27:41.320
[Guest 2]: They'll come from parents.

02:27:41.320 --> 02:27:46.760
[Guest 2]: So for example, the example that I always give that, you know, Europe has fantastic

02:27:46.760 --> 02:27:51.560
[Guest 2]: facilities, you have great soccer teams, and they win, it's not soccer, I shouldn't say

02:27:51.560 --> 02:27:54.780
[Guest 2]: soccer anymore, football teams, and they keep winning.

02:27:54.780 --> 02:27:58.320
[Guest 2]: But South America has won, also won eight World Cups.

02:27:58.320 --> 02:27:59.520
[Guest 2]: Why have they won those World Cups?

02:27:59.520 --> 02:28:05.360
[Guest 2]: Actually, nine World Cups, because they have won those World Cups because they have a passion

02:28:05.360 --> 02:28:06.840
[Guest 2]: for the sport.

02:28:06.840 --> 02:28:11.200
[Guest 2]: So if there's a local league happening, there's a local football match happening, people come

02:28:11.200 --> 02:28:13.760
[Guest 2]: in and watch it, just like in the US.

02:28:13.760 --> 02:28:18.000
[Guest 2]: You travel in the US, you stop at a small petrol pump, and they'll turn on and say,

02:28:18.000 --> 02:28:22.240
[Guest 2]: you know what, that guy there, the petrol pump, he was an all-star athlete for school,

02:28:22.240 --> 02:28:24.560
[Guest 2]: and they won us local championships in 2015.

02:28:24.560 --> 02:28:26.560
[Guest 2]: There's a culture of that.

02:28:26.560 --> 02:28:27.560
[Guest 2]: Why?

02:28:27.560 --> 02:28:29.800
[Guest 2]: Because there's a culture of sport.

02:28:29.800 --> 02:28:34.040
[Guest 2]: And that's the one thing, I tell parents, I said, forget everything else.

02:28:34.040 --> 02:28:38.680
[Guest 2]: If you can go, one of you can go and watch your kids playing a football game, that'll

02:28:38.680 --> 02:28:43.360
[Guest 2]: keep the coach honest, that'll keep the team honest, and that'll actually make sure that,

02:28:43.360 --> 02:28:46.200
[Guest 2]: you know, stupid things are not happening at that level.

02:28:46.200 --> 02:28:52.640
[Guest 2]: Because 50 to 70% of the best athletes drop out at that level, because, you know, somebody

02:28:52.640 --> 02:28:56.840
[Guest 2]: else is there watching the sport whose father is more interested and wants his kid in.

02:28:56.840 --> 02:29:00.600
[Guest 2]: And that's the point at which he leaves the sport and says, you know, I'd rather concentrate

02:29:00.600 --> 02:29:07.680
[Guest 2]: on academics, it's less qualitative, the assessment is less qualitative and more operational.

02:29:07.680 --> 02:29:10.320
[Guest 2]: And that's one of the biggest problems with Indian sport.

02:29:10.320 --> 02:29:14.040
[Guest 2]: So these are the two basic issues that we are working with.

02:29:14.040 --> 02:29:19.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, if you solve them, you're doing 90% of the journey of Indian sport.

02:29:19.640 --> 02:29:23.240
[Guest 2]: You know, firstly, you're just doing the top level.

02:29:23.240 --> 02:29:29.880
[Guest 2]: And B is that below that, you just don't have the domestic support, the support of people,

02:29:29.880 --> 02:29:31.560
[Guest 2]: because this is not federations.

02:29:31.560 --> 02:29:35.600
[Guest 2]: This is about other people supporting it to make sport work.

02:29:35.600 --> 02:29:41.400
[Guest 1]: And I would agree there with Joy very much that it's not necessarily about sort of funding,

02:29:41.400 --> 02:29:42.920
[Guest 1]: training and other things like that.

02:29:42.920 --> 02:29:45.860
[Guest 1]: Sometimes all we need is more competition.

02:29:45.860 --> 02:29:49.480
[Guest 1]: And we deal with this all the time with young athletes, there are many federations where

02:29:49.480 --> 02:29:54.520
[Guest 1]: at best they hold the nationals, and that's once a year, so you'll have a sub junior nationals

02:29:54.520 --> 02:29:56.200
[Guest 1]: or junior nationals.

02:29:56.200 --> 02:29:58.440
[Guest 1]: And there's very little in between.

02:29:58.440 --> 02:30:04.240
[Guest 1]: If you can only simply bring more competitions at the junior level, a lot of the other stuff

02:30:04.240 --> 02:30:09.440
[Guest 1]: solves itself, you'll have academies that pick up coaches that get interested, but you

02:30:09.440 --> 02:30:16.200
[Guest 1]: have to build a demand for coaching and build a demand for micro organizations to grow around

02:30:16.200 --> 02:30:17.200
[Guest 1]: sport.

02:30:17.200 --> 02:30:22.800
[Guest 1]: This is another sort of public private issue of how do you bring in more private interest

02:30:22.800 --> 02:30:29.020
[Guest 1]: into sport into sports coaching, sports scouting, sports training, more sort of professional

02:30:29.020 --> 02:30:30.440
[Guest 1]: services around that.

02:30:30.440 --> 02:30:36.280
[Guest 1]: And the reality is for a young athlete today, if you want to play at the international level,

02:30:36.280 --> 02:30:40.400
[Guest 1]: it's much more expensive to be an Indian athlete than it is to be, for example, a European

02:30:40.400 --> 02:30:41.400
[Guest 1]: athlete.

02:30:41.400 --> 02:30:45.360
[Guest 1]: And here I talk about let's say a sport like tennis, you take a young Spanish athlete was

02:30:45.360 --> 02:30:52.040
[Guest 1]: a young Indian athlete, there's some tournaments that now are held, but the average Indian

02:30:52.040 --> 02:30:56.800
[Guest 1]: athlete has to travel, let's say 15 times has to travel internationally a year just

02:30:56.800 --> 02:31:02.040
[Guest 1]: to pick up the few ITF ranking points, while that Spanish equivalent, he's like literally

02:31:02.040 --> 02:31:07.480
[Guest 1]: traveling 20 miles and playing a tournament, traveling next weekend somewhere else.

02:31:07.480 --> 02:31:13.480
[Guest 1]: And like literally going home after the match, while the Indian is traveling international

02:31:13.480 --> 02:31:17.080
[Guest 1]: flight ticket hotel parent has to probably go along.

02:31:17.080 --> 02:31:21.680
[Guest 1]: So the cost of being an Indian athlete is in fact, in some cases much more than being

02:31:21.680 --> 02:31:23.000
[Guest 1]: a European athlete.

02:31:23.000 --> 02:31:24.360
[Guest 1]: So we're loading up costs.

02:31:24.360 --> 02:31:28.860
[Guest 1]: And what does that mean that that means that the people who end up accessing some of those

02:31:28.860 --> 02:31:33.520
[Guest 1]: opportunities are people with privilege, people with access, either to their own money or

02:31:33.520 --> 02:31:35.800
[Guest 1]: to sources of funding.

02:31:35.800 --> 02:31:42.600
[Guest 1]: And what we have to do is another way of democratizing is just building more tournament opportunities,

02:31:42.600 --> 02:31:44.800
[Guest 1]: allowing competition to play out.

02:31:44.800 --> 02:31:48.840
[Guest 1]: But when you do that, there are lots of very structural things to fix.

02:31:48.840 --> 02:31:53.800
[Guest 1]: And one we cannot avoid is the issue of age fraud in India.

02:31:53.800 --> 02:31:59.440
[Guest 1]: One of the largest issues which turns so many parents away is age cheating.

02:31:59.440 --> 02:32:03.120
[Guest 1]: And that's across all sports, talk about cricket, talk about football.

02:32:03.120 --> 02:32:07.160
[Guest 1]: I don't think there's a sport that hasn't been touched by age fraud, which is people

02:32:07.160 --> 02:32:09.960
[Guest 1]: falsifying that age.

02:32:09.960 --> 02:32:15.000
[Guest 1]: In fact, I mean, there's a ton of stories in terms of the way people have been people

02:32:15.000 --> 02:32:19.320
[Guest 1]: born apparently in auto rickshaws, I mean, we have a genuine problem with being able

02:32:19.320 --> 02:32:22.440
[Guest 1]: to tax someone's age on to some database, right?

02:32:22.440 --> 02:32:25.760
[Guest 1]: And that is exploited and exposed quite often.

02:32:25.760 --> 02:32:30.880
[Guest 1]: And the reality is something like this can be a structural barrier to keeping a young

02:32:30.880 --> 02:32:34.680
[Guest 1]: person who's actually following the rules, keeping them in sport.

02:32:34.680 --> 02:32:36.520
[Guest 1]: So I think you need competition.

02:32:36.520 --> 02:32:41.760
[Guest 1]: But if you can't do that with integrity, you're also sort of devaluing the sport.

02:32:41.760 --> 02:32:48.200
[Guest 1]: So there's both more activity, but also better activity and fixing some very, very fundamental

02:32:48.200 --> 02:32:52.680
[Guest 1]: problems in youth and junior sport, which must happen at the same time.

02:32:52.680 --> 02:32:55.920
[Guest 1]: And then allowing some of that ecosystem to evolve around.

02:32:55.920 --> 02:32:59.960
[Guest 1]: Like I said, if you look at the sport of badminton, you look at the number of academies today

02:32:59.960 --> 02:33:01.880
[Guest 1]: in badminton is fabulous.

02:33:01.880 --> 02:33:04.800
[Guest 1]: Very few are government driven academies.

02:33:04.800 --> 02:33:05.800
[Guest 1]: What did it take?

02:33:05.800 --> 02:33:10.480
[Guest 1]: If you took one great coach to follow another great coach, you have a padukone followed

02:33:10.480 --> 02:33:15.360
[Guest 1]: by a Gopichand and you have a whole sort of stable of athletes come out.

02:33:15.360 --> 02:33:19.800
[Guest 1]: And then what's happened that the conversation with parents has changed, you can be a Olympic

02:33:19.800 --> 02:33:26.280
[Guest 1]: medalist, you can sort of play on a professional circuit, the game has changed.

02:33:26.280 --> 02:33:32.680
[Guest 1]: But it meant that suddenly hundreds more kids are buying badminton rackets, making a sort

02:33:32.680 --> 02:33:38.440
[Guest 1]: of a supplier successful, joining academies, making coaches commercially successful.

02:33:38.440 --> 02:33:43.400
[Guest 1]: But that comes from repetitious tournaments, which sort of separate the competitors from

02:33:43.400 --> 02:33:47.240
[Guest 1]: the contenders and allow the resources of the state.

02:33:47.240 --> 02:33:52.960
[Guest 1]: Let's accept that the state must fund a little bit, but that resources have to be funded

02:33:52.960 --> 02:34:00.840
[Guest 1]: funding the sort of the optimal talent, not funding too early, and not funding too late.

02:34:00.840 --> 02:34:05.040
[Guest 1]: And it's not an easy place to determine where to fund and how much the state should fund

02:34:05.040 --> 02:34:06.040
[Guest 1]: when.

02:34:06.040 --> 02:34:09.480
[Guest 1]: But it is a balance we will find only if we can push people up.

02:34:09.480 --> 02:34:14.920
[Guest 1]: And there's enough quantity in the funnel to determine that the person is actually deserving.

02:34:14.920 --> 02:34:18.960
[Guest 1]: And it's not just simply an anecdotal person who's sort of been lucky to get where they

02:34:18.960 --> 02:34:24.100
[Guest 1]: are simply because other people didn't try or the pool of talent was not large enough.

02:34:24.100 --> 02:34:28.960
[Guest 1]: So this is actually essential to the not just talent scouting, but the talent progression

02:34:28.960 --> 02:34:34.560
[Guest 1]: pathway of recognizing how much of the resources of the state to spend on what level and there

02:34:34.560 --> 02:34:39.800
[Guest 1]: are very efficient ways to do that, simply with strong sort of regional, state, local

02:34:39.800 --> 02:34:45.340
[Guest 1]: and national competitions, but them happening at regular intervals, and the data from them

02:34:45.340 --> 02:34:48.400
[Guest 1]: being collected and acted upon smartly.

02:34:48.400 --> 02:34:50.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a great point.

02:34:50.440 --> 02:34:54.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, as I, you know, keep telling people who do my writing class, or as I keep telling

02:34:54.560 --> 02:34:59.400
[Amit Varma]: creators that the only way to excellence is through endless iteration, you know, if I

02:34:59.400 --> 02:35:03.200
[Amit Varma]: was recording one podcast episode a year, it would be pretty shitty.

02:35:03.200 --> 02:35:07.880
[Amit Varma]: But for many young sports people, they have that one sub junior national event to go through.

02:35:07.880 --> 02:35:11.920
[Amit Varma]: And even the point about falsifying age, we joke about that, but you are right that it

02:35:11.920 --> 02:35:12.920
[Amit Varma]: can be very pernicious.

02:35:12.920 --> 02:35:16.440
[Amit Varma]: I think Malcolm Gladwell had a study a few years ago or spoke about a study a few years

02:35:16.440 --> 02:35:20.560
[Amit Varma]: ago in maybe outliers, where he spoke about how, you know, if you're playing at the under

02:35:20.560 --> 02:35:25.480
[Amit Varma]: 13, or under 14 level, or whatever, studies have found that those born in Jan, Feb, March

02:35:25.480 --> 02:35:29.680
[Amit Varma]: tend to do much better than those born in November and December, simply because the

02:35:29.680 --> 02:35:33.280
[Amit Varma]: Freakonomics I think has that Freakonomics, yeah, oh, Freakonomics had it.

02:35:33.280 --> 02:35:35.880
[Amit Varma]: Okay, I somehow thought Gladwell wrote about it.

02:35:35.880 --> 02:35:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Maybe he also did.

02:35:37.000 --> 02:35:40.920
[Amit Varma]: And the result of that is that, you know, at that age, the people who are in November

02:35:40.920 --> 02:35:45.920
[Amit Varma]: and December can't keep up with their peers, who have those seven, eight extra months of

02:35:45.920 --> 02:35:49.000
[Amit Varma]: development, which makes for a big difference.

02:35:49.000 --> 02:35:50.560
[Amit Varma]: And so they tend to drop out.

02:35:50.560 --> 02:35:53.960
[Amit Varma]: And if people are falsifying ages, it's not a question of months, it's a question of years.

02:35:53.960 --> 02:35:59.160
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how are you really going to compete, I have a funny story about this, by the way,

02:35:59.160 --> 02:36:02.360
[Amit Varma]: which is that, you know, I used to play chess in my teens.

02:36:02.360 --> 02:36:07.120
[Amit Varma]: So I remember I once went to the Maharashtra Junior Chess Championships, and which was

02:36:07.120 --> 02:36:08.120
[Amit Varma]: under 20.

02:36:08.120 --> 02:36:12.680
[Amit Varma]: And I was 18 or 19 or whatever, I was well under the age this thing, but I had a beard,

02:36:12.680 --> 02:36:14.020
[Amit Varma]: so Punjabi jeans and all that.

02:36:14.020 --> 02:36:19.480
[Amit Varma]: So I had a proper beard, and after six rounds, I was a sole leader with six points in six

02:36:19.480 --> 02:36:20.480
[Amit Varma]: rounds.

02:36:20.480 --> 02:36:24.480
[Amit Varma]: And they had an English newspaper, which was a local English newspaper, which was the biggest

02:36:24.480 --> 02:36:27.920
[Amit Varma]: selling English newspaper locally, but I forget what it was called.

02:36:27.920 --> 02:36:31.840
[Amit Varma]: And the next day, I wasn't on the sports pages, I was on the front page, there was a photograph

02:36:31.840 --> 02:36:36.680
[Amit Varma]: of me with the headline is this boy really under 19 or whatever the thing it was.

02:36:36.680 --> 02:36:40.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I eventually shaved off my beard, but that didn't really help me.

02:36:40.480 --> 02:36:45.720
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, I mean, that aside apart, I can see why it can have a pernicious effect.

02:36:45.720 --> 02:36:50.340
[Amit Varma]: Let's get down to specifics, because, you know, I'm so fascinated, not just by the fact

02:36:50.340 --> 02:36:55.320
[Amit Varma]: that you chose to embark on your journey, but that you've actually helped so many sports

02:36:55.320 --> 02:36:58.880
[Amit Varma]: people like Deepak Karmarkar is just one example, you pointed out, but there are so many that

02:36:58.880 --> 02:36:59.880
[Amit Varma]: you've helped.

02:36:59.880 --> 02:37:03.200
[Amit Varma]: So can you tell me what your thought process was like when you started GoSports?

02:37:03.200 --> 02:37:06.840
[Amit Varma]: Like, where are we going to make our specific interventions?

02:37:06.840 --> 02:37:11.400
[Amit Varma]: Because obviously, you have also at that point, a paucity of resources in terms of time, mental

02:37:11.400 --> 02:37:12.880
[Amit Varma]: bandwidth, all of that.

02:37:12.880 --> 02:37:15.160
[Amit Varma]: So where do you decide to make an intervention?

02:37:15.160 --> 02:37:16.160
[Amit Varma]: Why?

02:37:16.160 --> 02:37:19.280
[Amit Varma]: How do those areas of focus evolve over the years?

02:37:19.280 --> 02:37:21.120
[Amit Varma]: And what are the kind of specific things you do?

02:37:21.120 --> 02:37:25.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, is it identifying promising athletes and saying, okay, what do they need to train

02:37:25.440 --> 02:37:27.320
[Amit Varma]: properly, we'll give them that much money?

02:37:27.320 --> 02:37:28.640
[Amit Varma]: Or how does the thinking evolve?

02:37:28.640 --> 02:37:31.060
[Guest 1]: So take me through that process.

02:37:31.060 --> 02:37:34.520
[Guest 1]: So the first thing we did, and we tried to identify what is the problem we were trying

02:37:34.520 --> 02:37:39.720
[Guest 1]: to solve, and that was the problem of dropout, where we recognize that people who should

02:37:39.720 --> 02:37:41.080
[Guest 1]: not be dropping.

02:37:41.080 --> 02:37:46.600
[Guest 1]: So sport has good dropout, the people who should be dropping out for the reason of sort

02:37:46.600 --> 02:37:50.880
[Guest 1]: of attributing resources well, but there are people who should be progressing, but are

02:37:50.880 --> 02:37:51.880
[Guest 1]: dropping out.

02:37:51.880 --> 02:37:56.320
[Guest 1]: So we did a brief study at the very start, and trying to find the right age group to

02:37:56.320 --> 02:37:57.320
[Guest 1]: make the intervention.

02:37:57.320 --> 02:38:00.880
[Guest 1]: So we were we didn't have huge amounts of money we were raising from friends and family,

02:38:00.880 --> 02:38:04.640
[Guest 1]: some amounts of funds, trying to make very specific interventions.

02:38:04.640 --> 02:38:10.160
[Guest 1]: So five, six athletes, where did we feel that change could even the little money that we

02:38:10.160 --> 02:38:11.520
[Guest 1]: had could make a difference.

02:38:11.520 --> 02:38:16.640
[Guest 1]: So we also looked at certain different sports, which had not really been supported well,

02:38:16.640 --> 02:38:22.080
[Guest 1]: like swimming, a few other sports, which had pretty large sort of middle potential, but

02:38:22.080 --> 02:38:27.280
[Guest 1]: had not really been looked at in some depth, professionalizing that working with coaches,

02:38:27.280 --> 02:38:33.040
[Guest 1]: so very small micro interventions, and it was a little bit ended up being like pilot

02:38:33.040 --> 02:38:37.120
[Guest 1]: ish, raise a few lakhs, find five, six people give them out.

02:38:37.120 --> 02:38:43.320
[Guest 1]: So it was really like cottage industry, nonprofit in the early bits.

02:38:43.320 --> 02:38:48.800
[Guest 1]: But we started seeing that even small bits of support started, we started seeing feedback

02:38:48.800 --> 02:38:53.680
[Guest 1]: from the system, people getting better stability coming into their lives.

02:38:53.680 --> 02:38:58.740
[Guest 1]: And we said, Hey, this is making a difference, how can we up the game a little bit?

02:38:58.740 --> 02:38:59.960
[Guest 1]: And how can we raise funds?

02:38:59.960 --> 02:39:04.160
[Guest 1]: So by this time, I mean, I've also been running my law practice, I end up meeting a lot of

02:39:04.160 --> 02:39:08.120
[Guest 1]: people along the way, they also start saying, Hey, how can we help out, I think they just

02:39:08.120 --> 02:39:09.120
[Guest 1]: saw the intent.

02:39:09.120 --> 02:39:12.400
[Guest 1]: And they saw naive bunch of people trying to do something.

02:39:12.400 --> 02:39:17.440
[Guest 1]: And you end up attracting a certain type of person also to you is my belief when you show

02:39:17.440 --> 02:39:19.800
[Guest 1]: intent and you show purpose.

02:39:19.800 --> 02:39:25.120
[Guest 1]: And we ended up working with an Abhinav Bindra, Gopichand, Rahul Dravid, all of whom actually

02:39:25.120 --> 02:39:28.560
[Guest 1]: came to us and said, let me know how I can help you.

02:39:28.560 --> 02:39:35.200
[Guest 1]: And we had a few bits of fortune at work with Rohan Bhopanna, he got us Roger Federer racket,

02:39:35.200 --> 02:39:39.800
[Guest 1]: and we auctioned it, we raised a pretty large amount of money and money from that auction

02:39:39.800 --> 02:39:45.760
[Guest 1]: of Federer racket, Rahul Dravid cricket bat, all of that gave us our first sort of little

02:39:45.760 --> 02:39:50.320
[Guest 1]: bit of extra money, where we started building a scholarship program.

02:39:50.320 --> 02:39:55.160
[Guest 1]: At which point, sort of my experiences from different ways of looking at talent, thinking

02:39:55.160 --> 02:40:00.720
[Guest 1]: about talent, we built a selection process, which includes sort of evaluation.

02:40:00.720 --> 02:40:03.840
[Guest 1]: And very clearly, we're not going out and scouting, we're looking at people who are

02:40:03.840 --> 02:40:05.040
[Guest 1]: out there.

02:40:05.040 --> 02:40:10.000
[Guest 1]: And we have an application process and interview process, we build that out.

02:40:10.000 --> 02:40:16.400
[Guest 1]: And it's sort of one thing leads to another, and we come to a point in some in about 2013,

02:40:16.400 --> 02:40:18.760
[Guest 1]: when the CSR law changes.

02:40:18.760 --> 02:40:22.400
[Guest 1]: So the CSR becomes mandatory for a lot of the companies.

02:40:22.400 --> 02:40:28.640
[Guest 1]: And the CSR law originally had a bunch of different things in this schedule seven, which

02:40:28.640 --> 02:40:31.440
[Guest 1]: lists all the things that qualify as CSR.

02:40:31.440 --> 02:40:35.480
[Guest 1]: The interesting thing is, at that point, the person who makes an intervention got nothing

02:40:35.480 --> 02:40:40.880
[Guest 1]: to do with us at that point of time is Abhinav Bindra talks to the corporate affairs ministry,

02:40:40.880 --> 02:40:44.960
[Guest 1]: and says include access to support to sports.

02:40:44.960 --> 02:40:46.480
[Guest 1]: So a specific entry comes in.

02:40:46.480 --> 02:40:50.080
[Guest 1]: And if you want to talk about great man, the great man can work in different ways, not

02:40:50.080 --> 02:40:54.040
[Guest 1]: just through achievement, but sort of different points like this, right.

02:40:54.040 --> 02:40:59.760
[Guest 1]: And you get an entry in the company's act, which says, training of Olympic and Paralympic

02:40:59.760 --> 02:41:04.680
[Guest 1]: athletes in national and rural sports as well.

02:41:04.680 --> 02:41:11.400
[Guest 1]: So a specific entry comes in, which recognizes CSR as sport as CSR eligible.

02:41:11.400 --> 02:41:15.400
[Guest 1]: And for us, by that time, we've worked with enough athletes to show that we sort of know

02:41:15.400 --> 02:41:16.400
[Guest 1]: what we're doing.

02:41:16.400 --> 02:41:18.600
[Guest 1]: We may not be experts, but there's good intent.

02:41:18.600 --> 02:41:24.700
[Guest 1]: The foundation is also run sort of almost out of my law firm, very much legally oriented.

02:41:24.700 --> 02:41:30.000
[Guest 1]: So a lot of paperwork, there's contracts, there's reports, all of the things that companies

02:41:30.000 --> 02:41:31.000
[Guest 1]: want, right.

02:41:31.000 --> 02:41:35.840
[Guest 1]: So we're at this interesting place where we have enough athletes needing the support.

02:41:35.840 --> 02:41:40.240
[Guest 1]: And we're ready to talk the language of corporate India as well.

02:41:40.240 --> 02:41:45.980
[Guest 1]: So in some sense, to translate the two worlds, speak corporate language to the athlete and

02:41:45.980 --> 02:41:47.800
[Guest 1]: athlete language to the corporate.

02:41:47.800 --> 02:41:51.360
[Guest 1]: And that has been the place where we've played for the last eight or 10 years.

02:41:51.360 --> 02:41:54.120
[Guest 1]: And that's been in some sense, transformative.

02:41:54.120 --> 02:41:59.080
[Guest 1]: So the thing we were able to do is support athletes in the early parts of their journeys,

02:41:59.080 --> 02:42:01.240
[Guest 1]: maybe a step below many of the others.

02:42:01.240 --> 02:42:05.440
[Guest 1]: And even before the government, very often, the only other source of support at the time

02:42:05.440 --> 02:42:08.240
[Guest 1]: is parents, and in some cases, state government.

02:42:08.240 --> 02:42:14.440
[Guest 1]: So we, what Joy talked about the last 20 meters, maybe we went from the 60th meter onwards.

02:42:14.440 --> 02:42:18.680
[Guest 1]: So added another 20 meters to that, we would love for more and more people to solve the

02:42:18.680 --> 02:42:22.560
[Guest 1]: rest of the 60 meters, but we had to start in a particular place.

02:42:22.560 --> 02:42:29.040
[Guest 1]: And that's where we chose in some sense, what has led from there is just more and more people

02:42:29.040 --> 02:42:34.440
[Guest 1]: recognizing that there is a role for sport, which is greater than sport.

02:42:34.440 --> 02:42:36.200
[Guest 1]: It is not just about the medal.

02:42:36.200 --> 02:42:37.640
[Guest 1]: It's the process.

02:42:37.640 --> 02:42:40.740
[Guest 1]: It's what the process means to us as people.

02:42:40.740 --> 02:42:45.600
[Guest 1]: But more than that, what does sport mean for India, you win a medal great, but I mean,

02:42:45.600 --> 02:42:52.120
[Guest 1]: you can win what happens 30 years later, let's say we top the medal table, is the job done?

02:42:52.120 --> 02:42:56.800
[Guest 1]: No, you have to figure out what is the role of sport in society?

02:42:56.800 --> 02:42:57.800
[Guest 1]: What is it changing?

02:42:57.800 --> 02:43:02.400
[Guest 1]: What is our perception of our own identities, our capabilities, there's a very beautiful

02:43:02.400 --> 02:43:05.960
[Guest 1]: thing that happened at this Olympics, and Joy had a role to play in that Joy talked

02:43:05.960 --> 02:43:10.960
[Guest 1]: about the, that sensitization program that we helped run for all of the athletes.

02:43:10.960 --> 02:43:14.640
[Guest 1]: If you notice, almost all of the athletes by the end of their game, whether they won

02:43:14.640 --> 02:43:17.240
[Guest 1]: or lost, they ended with a namaste.

02:43:17.240 --> 02:43:22.460
[Guest 1]: And the beautiful photos of Sindhu, Mirabai, the namaste at the end of that, and just sort

02:43:22.460 --> 02:43:24.800
[Guest 1]: of so proudly Indian at the end of that.

02:43:24.800 --> 02:43:29.760
[Guest 1]: It's one of the things Joy recommended, I was so happy to see many of the athletes do.

02:43:29.760 --> 02:43:34.240
[Guest 1]: And I think all of those little things matter, whether you there at the Olympics, how you

02:43:34.240 --> 02:43:40.120
[Guest 1]: represent yourself, what you do, and what it means to India, in some sense, unashamedly

02:43:40.120 --> 02:43:44.440
[Guest 1]: patriotic India at the Olympics was a fabulous thing.

02:43:44.440 --> 02:43:51.120
[Guest 1]: People went in heads held high, were disappointed when they lost, when they won, they won confidently.

02:43:51.120 --> 02:43:56.600
[Guest 1]: And to me, that ended a journey that I had sort of begun personally, it wasn't me who

02:43:56.600 --> 02:43:57.600
[Guest 1]: solved it.

02:43:57.600 --> 02:44:00.040
[Guest 1]: I was a co participant along the way.

02:44:00.040 --> 02:44:06.400
[Guest 1]: But we saw a well resourced, confident Indian athlete who belong there and believe they

02:44:06.400 --> 02:44:07.800
[Guest 1]: belong there.

02:44:07.800 --> 02:44:13.900
[Guest 1]: And like I said, the medals were incidental to me, fantastic and fabulous to celebrate.

02:44:13.900 --> 02:44:16.320
[Guest 1]: We could have got more, we could have gotten less.

02:44:16.320 --> 02:44:21.400
[Guest 1]: But still, this was a very personal level, sort of the closure of a journey that I had

02:44:21.400 --> 02:44:28.280
[Guest 1]: personally begun, and a great amount of satisfaction to see the way the athletes competed, and

02:44:28.280 --> 02:44:33.720
[Guest 1]: sort of the broader perception of what the value and role of athletes is in society.

02:44:33.720 --> 02:44:40.480
[Guest 1]: I think we have turned the corner and I'm optimistic of what the future holds as well.

02:44:40.480 --> 02:44:44.080
[Amit Varma]: That Namaste story is really inspiring, kudos to you, Joy.

02:44:44.080 --> 02:44:48.080
[Amit Varma]: And it reminds me of, you know, what Tagore used to say and what Ram Guha also talks about

02:44:48.080 --> 02:44:52.420
[Amit Varma]: whenever he's on the show about the difference between patriotism and nationalism.

02:44:52.420 --> 02:44:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, incorporating a little symbolic thing like that seems to me to be the best

02:44:57.000 --> 02:44:58.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of patriotism.

02:44:58.280 --> 02:45:01.080
[Amit Varma]: My next question is something that both of you must have at different points in time

02:45:01.080 --> 02:45:07.000
[Amit Varma]: dealt with, which is that, okay, this is a largely private, voluntary initiative to make

02:45:07.000 --> 02:45:11.040
[Amit Varma]: things happen to make our sportsmen better to, you know, bring pride to the country or

02:45:11.040 --> 02:45:12.040
[Amit Varma]: whatever.

02:45:12.040 --> 02:45:13.960
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, the state runs the sport.

02:45:13.960 --> 02:45:17.920
[Amit Varma]: You have to interface with the federations, you have to interface with the governments.

02:45:17.920 --> 02:45:22.160
[Amit Varma]: Did they ever feel threatened when you guys were doing, you know, the separate things

02:45:22.160 --> 02:45:24.760
[Amit Varma]: that you were doing in your particular domains?

02:45:24.760 --> 02:45:25.760
[Amit Varma]: Was that a problem?

02:45:25.760 --> 02:45:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Was there a problem of, hey, you know, I am in charge, or I should get the credit here,

02:45:30.000 --> 02:45:33.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, whatever you're doing, you know, did you take my permission before doing this

02:45:33.200 --> 02:45:34.200
[Amit Varma]: or blah, blah, blah?

02:45:34.200 --> 02:45:36.760
[Amit Varma]: Is there that kind of friction within the system?

02:45:36.760 --> 02:45:40.920
[Amit Varma]: And if so, you know, how did you kind of navigate that?

02:45:40.920 --> 02:45:45.400
[Guest 2]: So first of all, if you look at the system and where it stands, cricket, for example,

02:45:45.400 --> 02:45:48.560
[Guest 2]: is completely out of the system, because, you know, really it's not a sport that depends

02:45:48.560 --> 02:45:51.520
[Guest 2]: on any of this and all this.

02:45:51.520 --> 02:45:55.960
[Guest 2]: So cricket does not bother about what happens, what doesn't happen.

02:45:55.960 --> 02:46:01.040
[Guest 2]: With a lot of the other sports, I think Nandan would have seen a bunch of other sports, where

02:46:01.040 --> 02:46:03.480
[Guest 2]: I saw a couple of team sports.

02:46:03.480 --> 02:46:07.680
[Guest 2]: And the fact of the matter is that it is very difficult.

02:46:07.680 --> 02:46:11.240
[Guest 2]: There are egos involved, there are people involved, and it's very individual based.

02:46:11.240 --> 02:46:16.560
[Guest 2]: And again, the more loose the system is, you know, you have an autocrat running the system,

02:46:16.560 --> 02:46:19.080
[Guest 2]: sometimes a good autocrat, sometimes a bad autocrat.

02:46:19.080 --> 02:46:23.840
[Guest 2]: But as far as I'm concerned, as Nandan will probably concur, I'd rather the autocrat be

02:46:23.840 --> 02:46:26.560
[Guest 2]: the rules rather than an individual.

02:46:26.560 --> 02:46:31.000
[Guest 2]: And in most cases in Indian sport, it's an individual rather than the rules.

02:46:31.000 --> 02:46:36.800
[Guest 2]: So sometimes you'll have a good dictator running it, but he's still a dictator.

02:46:36.800 --> 02:46:42.400
[Guest 2]: Because he's running it his way, and he has all the right intentions in the world.

02:46:42.400 --> 02:46:45.160
[Guest 2]: And he probably doesn't want to make money out of the sport, but he's running it in a

02:46:45.160 --> 02:46:49.360
[Guest 2]: particular way because he thinks that's the way the sport should be run.

02:46:49.360 --> 02:46:54.400
[Guest 2]: And what Nandan believes, and I believe in also totally, is that if we could make those

02:46:54.400 --> 02:46:59.800
[Guest 2]: rules much better, that the system and the rules are running it, and we are working within

02:46:59.800 --> 02:47:04.560
[Guest 2]: those rules, or whoever is in there is running within those rules, that would be a far better

02:47:04.560 --> 02:47:05.560
[Guest 2]: outcome.

02:47:05.560 --> 02:47:08.240
[Guest 2]: But it doesn't unfortunately happen as often as we would think.

02:47:08.240 --> 02:47:11.760
[Guest 2]: And therefore, those are the problems that Indian sport has.

02:47:11.760 --> 02:47:16.720
[Guest 2]: And those are the problems we'll grapple with as long as we cannot clear these lacunas in

02:47:16.720 --> 02:47:17.720
[Guest 2]: Indian sport.

02:47:17.720 --> 02:47:23.280
[Guest 2]: But I'm confident as one of the good things that's happening is the more results you get,

02:47:23.280 --> 02:47:27.880
[Guest 2]: you know, and social media is a powerful thing, much more powerful than you would think.

02:47:27.880 --> 02:47:32.360
[Guest 2]: And here when the pressure is brought to bear saying that, you know, this is what it is,

02:47:32.360 --> 02:47:37.960
[Guest 2]: and these are people who are funding it, these people are making things happen, it's slowly

02:47:37.960 --> 02:47:43.440
[Guest 2]: going to reach a position that is for a lot of these places who are intransigent right

02:47:43.440 --> 02:47:45.480
[Guest 2]: now, more and more untenable.

02:47:45.480 --> 02:47:49.800
[Guest 2]: They'll reach a stage where they have to turn around and say that, you know what, we can't

02:47:49.800 --> 02:47:52.960
[Guest 2]: just go around doing whatever we want to anymore.

02:47:52.960 --> 02:47:59.840
[Guest 2]: And you've seen cases already, I think, wrestling, or even shooting, whatever it is, is it a

02:47:59.840 --> 02:48:02.760
[Guest 2]: bad thing, is it a good thing that things are out in public?

02:48:02.760 --> 02:48:06.160
[Guest 2]: You know, you can turn around and say that, you know, you'd rather talk, wash your dirty

02:48:06.160 --> 02:48:07.160
[Guest 2]: linen in public.

02:48:07.160 --> 02:48:12.760
[Guest 2]: But I believe it's important for the process of purging the system and saying, OK, what

02:48:12.760 --> 02:48:13.760
[Guest 2]: is it?

02:48:13.760 --> 02:48:15.280
[Guest 2]: Let's get down and find out what's wrong.

02:48:15.280 --> 02:48:19.460
[Guest 2]: And yes, there's going to be over sensationalization now.

02:48:19.460 --> 02:48:24.640
[Guest 2]: But over the next two years, or at least the next year before, say, the next Asian Games

02:48:24.640 --> 02:48:28.440
[Guest 2]: or Commonwealth Games comes, if there's a little bit of understanding of what went wrong

02:48:28.440 --> 02:48:32.320
[Guest 2]: here, and somebody saying that, you know, if you don't do it right, next time, there'll

02:48:32.320 --> 02:48:33.320
[Guest 2]: be a problem.

02:48:33.320 --> 02:48:35.520
[Guest 2]: I think that's good for Indian sport.

02:48:35.520 --> 02:48:39.960
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so what we do try and do is find as much alignment as possible.

02:48:39.960 --> 02:48:45.800
[Guest 1]: The reality is that the model itself, the GoSports model was structured in a way that

02:48:45.800 --> 02:48:48.680
[Guest 1]: no one could stop us from supporting athletes.

02:48:48.680 --> 02:48:53.000
[Guest 1]: What we saw ourselves as was a civic society organization.

02:48:53.000 --> 02:48:56.000
[Guest 1]: Can anyone stop me from supporting a fellow individual?

02:48:56.000 --> 02:48:57.000
[Guest 1]: No.

02:48:57.000 --> 02:49:00.640
[Guest 1]: I mean, you can stop me from running a league, you will try and stop me from running a league,

02:49:00.640 --> 02:49:05.840
[Guest 1]: you can stop me from sponsoring a tournament, but you can't stop me from supporting a fellow

02:49:05.840 --> 02:49:06.840
[Guest 1]: Indian.

02:49:06.840 --> 02:49:11.000
[Guest 1]: So I was very conscious of that in structuring the intervention itself.

02:49:11.000 --> 02:49:16.120
[Guest 1]: Not to say that we haven't found sort of pushback as well, we've even had a federation send

02:49:16.120 --> 02:49:20.160
[Guest 1]: us a legal notice saying that we were violating their intellectual property by supporting

02:49:20.160 --> 02:49:21.160
[Guest 1]: their athletes.

02:49:21.160 --> 02:49:27.760
[Guest 1]: I think the wrong person to send that notice to, but not that we haven't seen that.

02:49:27.760 --> 02:49:32.200
[Guest 1]: But I think we've been very careful to support athletes, I mean, support of fellow human

02:49:32.200 --> 02:49:35.960
[Guest 1]: being, which person in their right mind is going to stop you.

02:49:35.960 --> 02:49:42.000
[Guest 1]: So the structure of how we made that intervention, and finding these inroads in was an important

02:49:42.000 --> 02:49:43.760
[Guest 1]: sort of structuring issue.

02:49:43.760 --> 02:49:45.960
[Guest 1]: And we did that early.

02:49:45.960 --> 02:49:49.680
[Guest 1]: And I think we found a way to make it work for everyone.

02:49:49.680 --> 02:49:54.720
[Guest 1]: And I think the real success in the model was in just how we integrated into the Target

02:49:54.720 --> 02:49:59.880
[Guest 1]: Olympic podium scheme, very, very sort of large hearted team there, which really saw

02:49:59.880 --> 02:50:02.960
[Guest 1]: everyone as an ally, could have seen everyone as a threat.

02:50:02.960 --> 02:50:07.440
[Guest 1]: And I think previous iterations of the same scheme might have seen other people as a threat

02:50:07.440 --> 02:50:14.680
[Guest 1]: and said, only you or you can either be with a private foundation or us, we want 100% credit,

02:50:14.680 --> 02:50:16.280
[Guest 1]: no one else should take credit.

02:50:16.280 --> 02:50:21.400
[Guest 1]: But it was a much more open hearted, much more collaborative, you tell us how you can

02:50:21.400 --> 02:50:22.400
[Guest 1]: help.

02:50:22.400 --> 02:50:23.400
[Guest 1]: Let's share information.

02:50:23.400 --> 02:50:28.800
[Guest 1]: Let's make you have resources, you're bringing in maybe CSR resources that we can't tap,

02:50:28.800 --> 02:50:33.960
[Guest 1]: maybe you have a different structure, which brings that money in, we have government funds.

02:50:33.960 --> 02:50:35.560
[Guest 1]: Let's make both of those work.

02:50:35.560 --> 02:50:39.000
[Guest 1]: It may be in whatever ratio, you may be me, you may have a smaller amount, but you may

02:50:39.000 --> 02:50:42.680
[Guest 1]: have more time and attention to spend on a particular athlete.

02:50:42.680 --> 02:50:43.680
[Guest 1]: Let's make that work.

02:50:43.680 --> 02:50:50.800
[Guest 1]: And I think that positivity has huge amounts of wings to be taken forward to find these

02:50:50.800 --> 02:50:53.320
[Guest 1]: private public collaborations.

02:50:53.320 --> 02:51:00.800
[Guest 1]: But in ways that the public structure is protected, and private bodies act with responsibility

02:51:00.800 --> 02:51:01.840
[Guest 1]: as well.

02:51:01.840 --> 02:51:07.320
[Guest 1]: I think you'd be very, very careful because this narrative can also become individuals

02:51:07.320 --> 02:51:09.600
[Guest 1]: becoming saviors of sport in India.

02:51:09.600 --> 02:51:13.800
[Guest 1]: I mean, it can cross your own mind saying, hey, I'm making all this difference, and it's

02:51:13.800 --> 02:51:16.240
[Guest 1]: because of me, and I'm the great man, right?

02:51:16.240 --> 02:51:21.280
[Guest 1]: So I think the worst thing is to build that great man theory in your own head, is that

02:51:21.280 --> 02:51:24.160
[Guest 1]: you are the transformative great man.

02:51:24.160 --> 02:51:28.520
[Guest 1]: And I think everyone needs to recognize you have three choices in Indian sport, you can

02:51:28.520 --> 02:51:32.800
[Guest 1]: either be a participant, a spectator or a bystander.

02:51:32.800 --> 02:51:36.240
[Guest 1]: And I think everyone has the choice to make of where they want to play.

02:51:36.240 --> 02:51:40.240
[Guest 1]: And if you're, I mean, full respect to you, if you just want to be a bystander, you'll

02:51:40.240 --> 02:51:44.560
[Guest 1]: sort of read the newspapers once every four years, you can be a spectator and participate

02:51:44.560 --> 02:51:46.200
[Guest 1]: and make sport more successful.

02:51:46.200 --> 02:51:52.080
[Guest 1]: But to me, I've always seen myself as a co-participant along with athletes along with federations

02:51:52.080 --> 02:51:53.360
[Guest 1]: along with the government.

02:51:53.360 --> 02:51:56.360
[Guest 1]: And I'll do my bit and I'd love for everyone else to do their bit.

02:51:56.360 --> 02:52:02.320
[Guest 1]: So there is a progression, can you move from bystander to spectator, spectator to participant,

02:52:02.320 --> 02:52:06.280
[Guest 1]: there are ways to participate and we will all find ways to participate if we really

02:52:06.280 --> 02:52:07.280
[Guest 1]: want to.

02:52:07.280 --> 02:52:12.920
[Guest 1]: I just found one way which was civic participation through support to fellow athletes, fellow

02:52:12.920 --> 02:52:13.920
[Guest 1]: Indians.

02:52:13.920 --> 02:52:15.040
[Guest 1]: And really no one could stop me.

02:52:15.040 --> 02:52:20.640
[Guest 1]: And if anything, the government and others, federations included have been encouraging

02:52:20.640 --> 02:52:23.580
[Guest 1]: and saying you're doing something we haven't been able to do.

02:52:23.580 --> 02:52:28.520
[Guest 1]: In fact, I take as the I was participating in the drafting of the top scheme many years

02:52:28.520 --> 02:52:29.780
[Guest 1]: ago.

02:52:29.780 --> 02:52:34.960
[Guest 1]: In many ways, I'd like to think that a lot of our ideas have been improved upon and given

02:52:34.960 --> 02:52:36.200
[Guest 1]: scale by the government.

02:52:36.200 --> 02:52:42.160
[Guest 1]: So there's a startup versus sort of mature relationship going on as well, where a startup

02:52:42.160 --> 02:52:47.120
[Guest 1]: can think and think of new things, new ways of doing and it can be adopted at scale by

02:52:47.120 --> 02:52:48.120
[Guest 1]: the government.

02:52:48.120 --> 02:52:50.640
[Guest 1]: So we're going to see more and more progression.

02:52:50.640 --> 02:52:55.240
[Guest 1]: Sport is getting more and more and more competitive while we look at these process improvements.

02:52:55.240 --> 02:53:01.680
[Guest 1]: The countries are advancing so much on sports science, on analytics, on performance enhancement,

02:53:01.680 --> 02:53:07.320
[Guest 1]: on just huge amounts of, I mean, we may be walking now, but they have been running.

02:53:07.320 --> 02:53:11.680
[Guest 1]: And if we want to keep up, we want to go up the medals table, there's lots more work to

02:53:11.680 --> 02:53:12.680
[Guest 1]: do.

02:53:12.680 --> 02:53:17.280
[Guest 1]: And it's not about sort of capturing turf, capturing territory, determining who is going

02:53:17.280 --> 02:53:18.480
[Guest 1]: to get credit.

02:53:18.480 --> 02:53:22.640
[Guest 1]: It's about moving forward and looking at the bigger game and knowing that everyone has

02:53:22.640 --> 02:53:24.480
[Guest 1]: a specific role to play.

02:53:24.480 --> 02:53:28.120
[Guest 1]: And I think Joy might have more to offer, but I mean, that's a perspective.

02:53:28.120 --> 02:53:31.720
[Guest 1]: I don't know how many people share with me, but it's something I'm extremely passionate

02:53:31.720 --> 02:53:37.760
[Guest 1]: about is that everyone has a stake in sport and everyone has a stake in sports governance.

02:53:37.760 --> 02:53:41.120
[Guest 1]: You just don't realize it yet if you aren't a participant.

02:53:41.120 --> 02:53:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, these are very inspiring and insightful words.

02:53:44.240 --> 02:53:47.840
[Amit Varma]: And I think listeners, you know, listening to this episode, seeing your humility might

02:53:47.840 --> 02:53:49.760
[Amit Varma]: just have found new sporting heroes.

02:53:49.760 --> 02:53:53.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's also fascinating, I could talk for three more hours about this, but we've

02:53:53.240 --> 02:53:54.840
[Amit Varma]: already spoken for three hours.

02:53:54.840 --> 02:53:56.680
[Amit Varma]: So I'll end with three final questions.

02:53:56.680 --> 02:53:58.560
[Amit Varma]: So that's like three threes right there.

02:53:58.560 --> 02:54:04.080
[Amit Varma]: My third last question is really for Nandan, that tell me a little bit about TOPS, what

02:54:04.080 --> 02:54:07.760
[Amit Varma]: it did, who were the stakeholders, how they came together, and then specifically tell

02:54:07.760 --> 02:54:10.080
[Amit Varma]: me about the run up to Tokyo.

02:54:10.080 --> 02:54:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Like you've pointed out that, you know, this was different from all Olympics, you know,

02:54:14.120 --> 02:54:18.280
[Amit Varma]: though you won't use a phrase, I'd say the expected value of the Indian contingent was

02:54:18.280 --> 02:54:23.000
[Amit Varma]: much greater than previous Olympics, perhaps even if we got seven medals, you know, we

02:54:23.000 --> 02:54:25.160
[Amit Varma]: could easily have done more, as you point out.

02:54:25.160 --> 02:54:26.160
[Amit Varma]: What was the difference?

02:54:26.160 --> 02:54:30.700
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that about, you know, what changed earlier, you said the Hockey

02:54:30.700 --> 02:54:34.600
[Amit Varma]: Federation changed a lot, great things happened in fencing, for example, where you wouldn't

02:54:34.600 --> 02:54:36.040
[Amit Varma]: expect them to.

02:54:36.040 --> 02:54:39.760
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about the good work of these, you know, the last few years.

02:54:39.760 --> 02:54:45.280
[Guest 1]: So I think the like I said, the thing that changed was the scheme came out in 2013-14.

02:54:45.280 --> 02:54:47.760
[Guest 1]: It was issued in end of 2014.

02:54:47.760 --> 02:54:51.280
[Guest 1]: In fact, I was the one who got to choose the name even and then the logo of it.

02:54:51.280 --> 02:54:55.320
[Guest 1]: So it was very interesting exercise I went through with the sports ministry didn't do

02:54:55.320 --> 02:54:57.040
[Guest 1]: very well in the early stages.

02:54:57.040 --> 02:55:01.880
[Guest 1]: And I think there's an article recently by Amrit Mathur, which reflects this and, and

02:55:01.880 --> 02:55:06.880
[Guest 1]: the challenges that the sports ministry itself saw with its own scheme, in some sense, losing

02:55:06.880 --> 02:55:09.000
[Guest 1]: power over decision making.

02:55:09.000 --> 02:55:13.840
[Guest 1]: But what happened is that Rio was a disaster games for us, right, with just two medals.

02:55:13.840 --> 02:55:18.320
[Guest 1]: And I think it opened people's eyes to okay, we just need to get this right.

02:55:18.320 --> 02:55:24.080
[Guest 1]: And in fact, the scheme got transformed in ways known and unknown, seen and unseen over

02:55:24.080 --> 02:55:25.680
[Guest 1]: the last five years.

02:55:25.680 --> 02:55:30.000
[Guest 1]: But with a proper professional structure, we have Commander Rajesh Rajagopalan, former

02:55:30.000 --> 02:55:35.700
[Guest 1]: Navy Commander, come in as CEO, a full team get built a professional team in the way that

02:55:35.700 --> 02:55:38.040
[Guest 1]: any of our organizations would have built it.

02:55:38.040 --> 02:55:42.280
[Guest 1]: So it becomes almost like a SWAT unit within the ministry.

02:55:42.280 --> 02:55:47.080
[Guest 1]: And the Sports Authority of India, you have a supportive Director General of the Sports

02:55:47.080 --> 02:55:52.840
[Guest 1]: Authority of India, supportive Secretary, what they do is build this as the Indian Olympic

02:55:52.840 --> 02:55:58.420
[Guest 1]: platform, they figure out ways in which federations can be worked with.

02:55:58.420 --> 02:56:03.680
[Guest 1]: So respect the autonomy, bring the federation in help with the selection help with the sort

02:56:03.680 --> 02:56:05.520
[Guest 1]: of the programming and planning.

02:56:05.520 --> 02:56:11.400
[Guest 1]: So respect the regulatory function, but work with the athlete on the funding.

02:56:11.400 --> 02:56:12.640
[Guest 1]: So there's still more work to do.

02:56:12.640 --> 02:56:13.920
[Guest 1]: It's not a perfect scheme.

02:56:13.920 --> 02:56:20.720
[Guest 1]: But what it did is it moved the funding decision away from the federation, and to a slightly

02:56:20.720 --> 02:56:26.880
[Guest 1]: more centralized model of a like a high performance management team, making funding and training

02:56:26.880 --> 02:56:32.200
[Guest 1]: decisions, which included, for example, I think 80 lakhs spent sending Meera Bhai Chanu

02:56:32.200 --> 02:56:38.840
[Guest 1]: to the US simply to work with the best physical fitness instructor in terms of how to increase

02:56:38.840 --> 02:56:43.840
[Guest 1]: the I think six or eight kgs that she increased in her weight in the last 12 months after

02:56:43.840 --> 02:56:45.200
[Guest 1]: having been injured.

02:56:45.200 --> 02:56:50.560
[Guest 1]: So the right biomechanical expert, this would have been unheard of, eight or 10 years ago,

02:56:50.560 --> 02:56:55.640
[Guest 1]: 70 lakhs for one athlete for whatever, three months or six months, you had whole teams

02:56:55.640 --> 02:56:59.600
[Guest 1]: go to other countries so that they didn't have to deal with quarantine.

02:56:59.600 --> 02:57:03.940
[Guest 1]: So the money was not in question, best resource possible.

02:57:03.940 --> 02:57:08.920
[Guest 1]: But what it also did was it looked at this much beyond just Tokyo.

02:57:08.920 --> 02:57:11.760
[Guest 1]: So it built in more recent years a developmental pool.

02:57:11.760 --> 02:57:17.960
[Guest 1]: So it's already picked the 250 which may be going to the 2028 games.

02:57:17.960 --> 02:57:21.840
[Guest 1]: So looking at people who are still eight or 10 years away, I mean, now Paris is just three

02:57:21.840 --> 02:57:22.840
[Guest 1]: years away.

02:57:22.840 --> 02:57:25.720
[Guest 1]: So people are already in training, which was a positive.

02:57:25.720 --> 02:57:30.520
[Guest 1]: But other little things which we had originally planned, but got executed only much later,

02:57:30.520 --> 02:57:35.000
[Guest 1]: which is everyone on the scheme got a stipend.

02:57:35.000 --> 02:57:39.200
[Guest 1]: So for the first time they were paid, it was almost like a central contract that an Indian

02:57:39.200 --> 02:57:44.160
[Guest 1]: cricketer would get, I mean, incomparable in terms of the quantity, but the fact that

02:57:44.160 --> 02:57:49.920
[Guest 1]: it started happening, meant that you respected and recognize that sport is a livelihood issue

02:57:49.920 --> 02:57:56.040
[Guest 1]: for many of these people, is that people are playing and need to support families.

02:57:56.040 --> 02:58:00.760
[Guest 1]: So those are very, very fundamental, but game shifting changes that occur.

02:58:00.760 --> 02:58:04.120
[Guest 1]: And that brings the confidence to the athlete.

02:58:04.120 --> 02:58:07.280
[Guest 1]: It also brought full hockey teams within its limit.

02:58:07.280 --> 02:58:12.520
[Guest 1]: So while the Orissa government also funded, became a sponsor, gave Orissa a home, the

02:58:12.520 --> 02:58:16.440
[Guest 1]: top scheme also funded both hockey teams, which was incredible.

02:58:16.440 --> 02:58:21.960
[Guest 1]: And it includes the coach is hired by the Federation, but also paid for by the Sports

02:58:21.960 --> 02:58:23.320
[Guest 1]: Authority of India.

02:58:23.320 --> 02:58:29.040
[Guest 1]: So there's a system that is coming in, which no longer is asking, are you priority discipline?

02:58:29.040 --> 02:58:33.480
[Guest 1]: If so, your Federation will get the money and will get distributed.

02:58:33.480 --> 02:58:39.180
[Guest 1]: If you are an Olympic contender, and you've qualified for the Olympics or in that range,

02:58:39.180 --> 02:58:44.920
[Guest 1]: you have a shot to directly transact with the government, no longer through sort of

02:58:44.920 --> 02:58:48.880
[Guest 1]: ad hoc schemes earlier, you'd either get the money through your Federation, or there was

02:58:48.880 --> 02:58:54.360
[Guest 1]: the National Sports Development Fund, where you could apply and on an ad hoc basis, the

02:58:54.360 --> 02:58:58.560
[Guest 1]: sort of the most elite athletes would get some amount, but without any systematization

02:58:58.560 --> 02:58:59.560
[Guest 1]: to that.

02:58:59.560 --> 02:59:06.160
[Guest 1]: But in this, whatever 120 plus contingent, I would say over 90% or more were on the top

02:59:06.160 --> 02:59:08.960
[Guest 1]: scheme for a large period of time.

02:59:08.960 --> 02:59:12.520
[Guest 1]: And there were probably another 50 people who didn't make it to Tokyo who were also

02:59:12.520 --> 02:59:13.720
[Guest 1]: on the top scheme.

02:59:13.720 --> 02:59:18.080
[Guest 1]: So you've got a sustained run of three, four, five years of support.

02:59:18.080 --> 02:59:23.000
[Guest 1]: People turned up at the Olympics well resourced and in a position where they weren't thinking,

02:59:23.000 --> 02:59:25.240
[Guest 1]: hey, I'm just here to turn up.

02:59:25.240 --> 02:59:30.360
[Guest 1]: And I have got the entire pathway of being able to be at my best.

02:59:30.360 --> 02:59:35.680
[Guest 1]: Now it's sort of just come and try and sort of put your mind to rest and perform.

02:59:35.680 --> 02:59:40.680
[Guest 1]: And that is a sort of a moment in time in Olympic and Paralympic sport history.

02:59:40.680 --> 02:59:45.080
[Guest 1]: And I must mention the Paralympics, which is still coming up and it starts at the end

02:59:45.080 --> 02:59:46.080
[Guest 1]: of the month.

02:59:46.080 --> 02:59:50.400
[Guest 1]: My guess is we'll have an even better Paralympics than we did in the Olympics.

02:59:50.400 --> 02:59:54.600
[Guest 1]: And that recognition of equity of bringing everyone under the same umbrella, the top

02:59:54.600 --> 02:59:59.060
[Guest 1]: scheme includes multiple dozen Paralympians as well.

02:59:59.060 --> 03:00:03.660
[Guest 1]: These are massive shifts, I mean, they might sound basic to the average listener, but these

03:00:03.660 --> 03:00:07.720
[Guest 1]: are huge shifts over a 10, 15 year period in Indian sport.

03:00:07.720 --> 03:00:15.280
[Guest 1]: And it is a sign of the recognition of role of sport in society and not just medals for

03:00:15.280 --> 03:00:16.280
[Guest 1]: their own sake.

03:00:16.280 --> 03:00:21.800
[Guest 1]: I think there's a recognition of what sport can do at sort of secondary levels and sort

03:00:21.800 --> 03:00:29.720
[Guest 1]: of the value it will deliver outside the pyramid to non-participants to what we consider ourselves

03:00:29.720 --> 03:00:30.880
[Guest 1]: to be capable of.

03:00:30.880 --> 03:00:35.920
[Guest 1]: And it is that recognition that excites me in the next stages, which is the recognition

03:00:35.920 --> 03:00:42.120
[Guest 1]: of a collective, that there is a collective interest and that sport is in some sense of

03:00:42.120 --> 03:00:46.440
[Guest 1]: commons that we all build together and that we will all benefit from.

03:00:46.440 --> 03:00:48.800
[Amit Varma]: Wow, mind blowing.

03:00:48.800 --> 03:00:52.440
[Amit Varma]: So my penultimate question for the day is really about private players, like in the

03:00:52.440 --> 03:00:56.720
[Amit Varma]: sense we've discussed earlier in this episode about how a lot of private players rushed

03:00:56.720 --> 03:01:00.960
[Amit Varma]: in to do these leagues for different sports after the IPL and all of that, and just no

03:01:00.960 --> 03:01:04.920
[Amit Varma]: deeper thinking into it, just kind of following the trend and so on.

03:01:04.920 --> 03:01:08.660
[Amit Varma]: And there, of course, I would say that, yeah, silly moves, but let everybody try everything

03:01:08.660 --> 03:01:10.640
[Amit Varma]: and whatever works, works.

03:01:10.640 --> 03:01:15.480
[Amit Varma]: Also recently, what we've seen on Twitter, for example, is that a lot of companies are

03:01:15.480 --> 03:01:20.020
[Amit Varma]: doing moment marketing, they're trying to sort of expropriate the, you know, the image

03:01:20.020 --> 03:01:22.420
[Amit Varma]: of athletes under the guise of congratulating them.

03:01:22.420 --> 03:01:26.440
[Amit Varma]: And this is something that Joy, you've been tweeting about a fair bit, the dominoes effect,

03:01:26.440 --> 03:01:30.520
[Amit Varma]: as it were, where these random companies will come up and they have not funded any athletes,

03:01:30.520 --> 03:01:32.480
[Amit Varma]: they have nothing to do with any of this.

03:01:32.480 --> 03:01:36.360
[Amit Varma]: And they'll be like, hey, we congratulate so and so and they'll get some brand building

03:01:36.360 --> 03:01:37.360
[Amit Varma]: out of that.

03:01:37.360 --> 03:01:43.680
[Amit Varma]: So this is sort of the seamy side of it, what you kind of expect from many corporates and

03:01:43.680 --> 03:01:44.800
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

03:01:44.800 --> 03:01:49.400
[Amit Varma]: But equally, there is, you know, a wholesome side to it, where many corporates have actually,

03:01:49.400 --> 03:01:53.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, opened their coffers to support these athletes, and they can't even advertise

03:01:53.040 --> 03:01:57.840
[Amit Varma]: it right now, because apparently IOC has that time period in which their sponsors can talk

03:01:57.840 --> 03:02:01.400
[Amit Varma]: about it and you can't so the people who actually put money into these athletes are not allowed

03:02:01.400 --> 03:02:04.680
[Amit Varma]: to talk about it, is random people jumping on the bandwagon.

03:02:04.680 --> 03:02:10.360
[Amit Varma]: But my deeper question is that, what shape can private involvement take in sport in the

03:02:10.360 --> 03:02:11.360
[Amit Varma]: future?

03:02:11.360 --> 03:02:16.400
[Amit Varma]: Because on the one hand, you have this imperative that everything that a company does on spending,

03:02:16.400 --> 03:02:19.760
[Amit Varma]: you have to keep an ROI in mind that what is my ROI in this.

03:02:19.760 --> 03:02:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, I think, hopefully, at this point in time, it will start becoming apparent that,

03:02:23.600 --> 03:02:28.360
[Amit Varma]: listen, there is an ROI, sport is a big deal, it can uplift a nation, when someone like

03:02:28.360 --> 03:02:32.820
[Amit Varma]: Neeraj Chopra wins a gold, it, you know, it can have all these knock on benefits.

03:02:32.820 --> 03:02:38.480
[Amit Varma]: So what are the sort of different ways in which you envisage private players who want

03:02:38.480 --> 03:02:42.200
[Amit Varma]: to contribute, whether it's companies or foundations or individuals?

03:02:42.200 --> 03:02:46.680
[Amit Varma]: What are the different ways in which they can plug into the ecosystem and actually play

03:02:46.680 --> 03:02:47.680
[Amit Varma]: that part?

03:02:47.680 --> 03:02:51.560
[Amit Varma]: So what is the shape of private involvement in the future?

03:02:51.560 --> 03:02:54.080
[Guest 2]: So two things, there are many ways of going about it.

03:02:54.080 --> 03:02:59.720
[Guest 2]: But the first is that, look, even now, even given all the CSR funding that is happening

03:02:59.720 --> 03:03:02.920
[Guest 2]: in sport, that's still much less than it actually can be.

03:03:02.920 --> 03:03:08.560
[Guest 2]: There's still a huge amount of place in CSR, because you're talking about 2% of the profits

03:03:08.560 --> 03:03:11.000
[Guest 2]: of lots of organizations.

03:03:11.000 --> 03:03:15.400
[Guest 2]: And therefore, in the CSR pile, you know, again, roti, kapra and makhan has taken priority,

03:03:15.400 --> 03:03:20.160
[Guest 2]: but sport can also take a priority, because sport in its own way is equally transformative.

03:03:20.160 --> 03:03:22.440
[Guest 2]: And I'll tell you one more thing.

03:03:22.440 --> 03:03:25.520
[Guest 2]: You know, you look at the Odisha government, we've been talking about the Odisha government,

03:03:25.520 --> 03:03:30.880
[Guest 2]: the Odisha government has spent on football, they've spent on hockey.

03:03:30.880 --> 03:03:31.880
[Guest 2]: Everyone knows about that.

03:03:31.880 --> 03:03:33.600
[Guest 2]: They've spent on Olympics.

03:03:33.600 --> 03:03:36.920
[Guest 2]: One of the reasons they've spent is they're not fools.

03:03:36.920 --> 03:03:43.040
[Guest 2]: The amount of bang for the buck that sport gives you for a 5 crore investment or a 10

03:03:43.040 --> 03:03:46.960
[Guest 2]: crore investment, if you want to make a 5 kilometer highway, the amount of money it

03:03:46.960 --> 03:03:51.560
[Guest 2]: takes you, you can sponsor a team for a year, and it makes a difference.

03:03:51.560 --> 03:03:55.720
[Guest 2]: So what I'm trying to say is that given the kind of money you spend in sport for the kind

03:03:55.720 --> 03:04:01.360
[Guest 2]: of benefit and rub off you get out of it, more and more states are beginning to understand

03:04:01.360 --> 03:04:07.400
[Guest 2]: that it's a ratio that actually works hugely in favor of sport.

03:04:07.400 --> 03:04:13.120
[Guest 2]: And you know, I have this great story that I keep telling and I bring it back to cricket,

03:04:13.120 --> 03:04:15.920
[Guest 2]: is that I call it the cricket effect.

03:04:15.920 --> 03:04:20.240
[Guest 2]: So by cricket, I mean, I don't mean cricket as in the game, but as in the insect.

03:04:20.240 --> 03:04:30.320
[Guest 2]: If I was to give Mukesh Ambani the books of Reliance and say, find in these whatever thousands

03:04:30.320 --> 03:04:35.760
[Guest 2]: and thousands of crores, find the Mumbai Indians, he would take half an hour, 45 minutes to

03:04:35.760 --> 03:04:40.680
[Guest 2]: just find that 200 crore entry, 250 crore, whatever it is, among those thousands and

03:04:40.680 --> 03:04:44.240
[Guest 2]: thousands and hundreds and thousands of crores.

03:04:44.240 --> 03:04:50.000
[Guest 2]: But the share of voice of the Mumbai Indians as compared to the kind of investment of value

03:04:50.000 --> 03:04:53.280
[Guest 2]: the Mumbai Indians is huge.

03:04:53.280 --> 03:04:55.360
[Guest 2]: Sport is a cricket.

03:04:55.360 --> 03:05:02.880
[Guest 2]: It shouts much, much larger on many, many more pages than you would think.

03:05:02.880 --> 03:05:05.480
[Guest 2]: And therefore, forget about everything else.

03:05:05.480 --> 03:05:09.600
[Guest 2]: Let's forget for once that there are people who are as decent as Nandan Kamath and I.

03:05:09.600 --> 03:05:15.360
[Guest 2]: I rarely have met such decent people in this part of the universe.

03:05:15.360 --> 03:05:18.040
[Guest 2]: Forget that they have altruistic motives.

03:05:18.040 --> 03:05:25.520
[Guest 2]: So purely, sport is so underleveraged in this country that if you actually spend on sport,

03:05:25.520 --> 03:05:30.800
[Guest 2]: you will get rewards disproportionate to the kind of money you spend.

03:05:30.800 --> 03:05:36.440
[Guest 2]: That's a fact because they're so underleveraged that there's so much time and so little money

03:05:36.440 --> 03:05:40.240
[Guest 2]: is being spent right now that even to spend a little bit of incremental money, you'll

03:05:40.240 --> 03:05:41.840
[Guest 2]: get this much share of voice.

03:05:41.840 --> 03:05:46.240
[Guest 2]: Have you realized the amount of voice even in Odisha has got right now?

03:05:46.240 --> 03:05:49.920
[Guest 2]: Then look at the books and then you will have a sober look at the books.

03:05:49.920 --> 03:05:52.680
[Guest 2]: You won't realize it's not that much money.

03:05:52.680 --> 03:05:58.000
[Guest 2]: So first and foremost, I just want to tell people sport is still in India for the next

03:05:58.000 --> 03:06:03.080
[Guest 2]: five to 10 foreseeable future, a very good investment opportunity.

03:06:03.080 --> 03:06:08.560
[Guest 2]: You're going to get more than enough value, more than enough bang for your buck.

03:06:08.560 --> 03:06:10.360
[Guest 2]: That's the first part of it.

03:06:10.360 --> 03:06:14.560
[Guest 2]: And then the second part of it is that once this journey starts, if you are in on the

03:06:14.560 --> 03:06:20.280
[Guest 2]: ground floor, the opportunities of yours rising with the sport are absolutely huge.

03:06:20.280 --> 03:06:26.420
[Guest 2]: So that's what I would go for because see, it's easy enough to tell people that do this

03:06:26.420 --> 03:06:28.380
[Guest 2]: for the good of the country.

03:06:28.380 --> 03:06:35.560
[Guest 2]: But I generally don't buy that as a concept and altruism does not fuel basic economics.

03:06:35.560 --> 03:06:40.320
[Guest 2]: It's got to be that I see value in it and it's easier for me to spend money here and

03:06:40.320 --> 03:06:42.120
[Guest 2]: get value than it is somewhere else.

03:06:42.120 --> 03:06:44.160
[Guest 2]: And that's the only way money is going to come.

03:06:44.160 --> 03:06:47.840
[Guest 2]: And I'm telling you in Indian sport, that value is there today.

03:06:47.840 --> 03:06:52.520
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I would totally agree with Joy, there are business models and their business models.

03:06:52.520 --> 03:06:56.760
[Guest 1]: And I think one of the business models is using sport for branding, right?

03:06:56.760 --> 03:06:59.920
[Guest 1]: So participating in the great branding game.

03:06:59.920 --> 03:07:06.740
[Guest 1]: And I totally agree the easiest way to get into a newspaper is on the sports page.

03:07:06.740 --> 03:07:12.840
[Guest 1]: It requires sort of the least effort to some tournament you name, you can get a photo in

03:07:12.840 --> 03:07:17.600
[Guest 1]: and that is just a sort of an example of the disproportionate share like Joy says.

03:07:17.600 --> 03:07:22.120
[Guest 1]: Many would argue that we as GoSports are just so minuscule, but get a disproportionate amount

03:07:22.120 --> 03:07:23.240
[Guest 1]: of credit.

03:07:23.240 --> 03:07:27.960
[Guest 1]: And I do recognize that and it's important to recognize that you can give to sport and

03:07:27.960 --> 03:07:31.840
[Guest 1]: but you can't take from sport, sport will give you when it's ready.

03:07:31.840 --> 03:07:37.080
[Guest 1]: But to answer your question, I think CSR is powerful, but it's incumbent on people like

03:07:37.080 --> 03:07:43.600
[Guest 1]: us, but also companies to recognize that it is not sport for its own sake, but also sport

03:07:43.600 --> 03:07:46.520
[Guest 1]: for a tool to solve a lot of other problems.

03:07:46.520 --> 03:07:50.840
[Guest 1]: And I think that those problems are so many that it's you can't even list them.

03:07:50.840 --> 03:07:55.960
[Guest 1]: There have been great examples, even for example, of sport in criminal justice of dealing with

03:07:55.960 --> 03:08:01.040
[Guest 1]: recidivism in prisons, putting up a basketball court in a prison.

03:08:01.040 --> 03:08:04.360
[Guest 1]: How can you use that effectively for CSR funds?

03:08:04.360 --> 03:08:07.120
[Guest 1]: Imagine what can spurt from there and what is possible.

03:08:07.120 --> 03:08:12.120
[Guest 1]: I'd also like to refer to something I was reading recently, a friend Sanjeev Jain and

03:08:12.120 --> 03:08:16.720
[Guest 1]: Alok Sarin, two very famous psychiatrists have written and put together an anthology

03:08:16.720 --> 03:08:20.200
[Guest 1]: on the psychological impact of the partition in India.

03:08:20.200 --> 03:08:25.160
[Guest 1]: So very important book, which talks about the fact that we haven't processed psychologically

03:08:25.160 --> 03:08:29.480
[Guest 1]: the partition, but it's just one line that really struck me in there, which sort of refers

03:08:29.480 --> 03:08:35.480
[Guest 1]: to a UNESCO study that happened in the early fifties, looking back at the partition.

03:08:35.480 --> 03:08:41.320
[Guest 1]: And it made this observation, which said that the rates of violence that is intercommunal

03:08:41.320 --> 03:08:47.320
[Guest 1]: violence are low in places where the children of the communities played together.

03:08:47.320 --> 03:08:52.760
[Guest 1]: So the statistics which said that around the playgrounds of these various cities like Aligarh

03:08:52.760 --> 03:08:55.840
[Guest 1]: and others, the violence rate was less.

03:08:55.840 --> 03:08:56.840
[Guest 1]: Why?

03:08:56.840 --> 03:09:02.600
[Guest 1]: Because the people who lived there had played together and their children played together.

03:09:02.600 --> 03:09:06.160
[Guest 1]: So imagine a more active playing India.

03:09:06.160 --> 03:09:12.880
[Guest 1]: I know it's altruistic joy and I think that altruism doesn't necessarily fund salaries,

03:09:12.880 --> 03:09:14.800
[Guest 1]: but there is a larger play.

03:09:14.800 --> 03:09:17.520
[Guest 1]: It is not medals for its own sake.

03:09:17.520 --> 03:09:24.160
[Guest 1]: And I think the same study also talks about this notion of moving beyond literacy of numbers

03:09:24.160 --> 03:09:32.400
[Guest 1]: and letters, but moving to a literacy of understanding and a large part of that is rootedness and

03:09:32.400 --> 03:09:39.180
[Guest 1]: identity of recognizing we are on a common path and there's rootedness of being together.

03:09:39.180 --> 03:09:42.440
[Guest 1]: And I don't think there's a better thing than sport to do that.

03:09:42.440 --> 03:09:48.280
[Guest 1]: I could disagree with everything that you believe in your politics, your relationship

03:09:48.280 --> 03:09:49.280
[Guest 1]: with gender.

03:09:49.280 --> 03:09:52.940
[Guest 1]: I could hate everything, but we can both celebrate Meera Chopra.

03:09:52.940 --> 03:09:57.560
[Guest 1]: And there's a universality and beauty to that, which we must capture and must recognize and

03:09:57.560 --> 03:09:58.880
[Guest 1]: must value.

03:09:58.880 --> 03:10:04.600
[Guest 1]: And seeing this as a much larger game than just medals, we are part of a large social

03:10:04.600 --> 03:10:05.600
[Guest 1]: engineering project.

03:10:05.600 --> 03:10:08.260
[Guest 1]: And I don't mean that in a negative way.

03:10:08.260 --> 03:10:15.100
[Guest 1]: It's an opportunity which we must see a sport as an instrument to deliver results, not sports

03:10:15.100 --> 03:10:17.720
[Guest 1]: for its own sake, not medals for their own sake.

03:10:17.720 --> 03:10:22.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, that's a stunning insight about parents whose kids play together, less likely

03:10:22.440 --> 03:10:23.440
[Amit Varma]: to fight.

03:10:23.440 --> 03:10:26.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it gives a whole new meaning to Orwell's term of war minus the shooting.

03:10:26.960 --> 03:10:30.480
[Amit Varma]: And I completely agree with, you know, what you said, Joy, about, you know, appealing

03:10:30.480 --> 03:10:34.480
[Amit Varma]: to the self interest of companies that don't do something just for CSR or just because

03:10:34.480 --> 03:10:37.720
[Amit Varma]: it's mandated or just whatever, do it because it's good for you.

03:10:37.720 --> 03:10:41.880
[Amit Varma]: And that's a, you know, great example of reliance and Mumbai Indians, one could argue that,

03:10:41.880 --> 03:10:43.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, cricket is low hanging fruit and all that.

03:10:43.880 --> 03:10:48.160
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, look at the goodwill if, you know, you had funded Meera Chopra for the last five

03:10:48.160 --> 03:10:50.760
[Amit Varma]: years, look at the goodwill you would get just for that.

03:10:50.760 --> 03:10:53.640
[Amit Varma]: So there's just tremendous opportunity in thinking ahead.

03:10:53.640 --> 03:10:58.520
[Amit Varma]: My final question to many guests tends to be on what gives them hope and what gives

03:10:58.520 --> 03:11:04.160
[Amit Varma]: them despair in whatever their specific subject or context is over the next 10 years.

03:11:04.160 --> 03:11:05.960
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to ask you about despair.

03:11:05.960 --> 03:11:09.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, obviously, what would give you despair as if things stay the same or we go backwards

03:11:09.520 --> 03:11:10.520
[Amit Varma]: or whatever.

03:11:10.520 --> 03:11:13.260
[Amit Varma]: But both of you are working for hope in a sense.

03:11:13.260 --> 03:11:18.400
[Amit Varma]: So tell me, you know, 10 years later, if you're looking at the India of 2031, you know, what

03:11:18.400 --> 03:11:21.960
[Amit Varma]: do you think is a realistic place for Indian sport to be in?

03:11:21.960 --> 03:11:25.680
[Amit Varma]: At a philosophical level, I don't see why the Olympics should be a goal at all or any

03:11:25.680 --> 03:11:26.680
[Amit Varma]: of that.

03:11:26.680 --> 03:11:30.080
[Amit Varma]: But in general, do you think, for example, that we will ever become a major player at

03:11:30.080 --> 03:11:34.360
[Amit Varma]: the Olympics and start competing with China in the US and whatever?

03:11:34.360 --> 03:11:36.660
[Amit Varma]: What's the sort of landscape that you see?

03:11:36.660 --> 03:11:39.080
[Guest 2]: What are you moving towards?

03:11:39.080 --> 03:11:41.760
[Guest 2]: So first, I'll start off with, you know, you're talking about the Olympics, I just want to

03:11:41.760 --> 03:11:45.400
[Guest 2]: talk about the World Cup football, which is, you know, the other mega event.

03:11:45.400 --> 03:11:50.680
[Guest 2]: So in the 1980s, the Japanese came together with a plan saying that we want to win a World

03:11:50.680 --> 03:11:51.680
[Guest 2]: Cup.

03:11:51.680 --> 03:11:55.660
[Guest 2]: Their plan was a 100-year plan.

03:11:55.660 --> 03:12:00.360
[Guest 2]: So in 1982, they turned around and said that in 2082, we want to win a World Cup.

03:12:00.360 --> 03:12:04.680
[Guest 2]: And now they've actually, after about 25, 30 years, their plan, they've said, you know

03:12:04.680 --> 03:12:08.960
[Guest 2]: what, we possibly might win one by 2050.

03:12:08.960 --> 03:12:12.400
[Guest 2]: That's the kind of gestation period in football, and that's not necessarily the case in all

03:12:12.400 --> 03:12:13.400
[Guest 2]: sport.

03:12:13.400 --> 03:12:17.080
[Guest 2]: So what I'm trying to say is that if you're going to work in sport, those are the kind

03:12:17.080 --> 03:12:22.120
[Guest 2]: of decades or the kind of numbers that you're going to look at to make significant differences.

03:12:22.120 --> 03:12:26.600
[Guest 2]: It's taken 13 years for us to progress from Abhinav Bindra to where we are.

03:12:26.600 --> 03:12:31.720
[Guest 2]: And Nandan's right, possibly, you know, given what we had, the potential was for maybe 10,

03:12:31.720 --> 03:12:35.760
[Guest 2]: 12 medals rather than, you know, just, you know, the seven medals that we got.

03:12:35.760 --> 03:12:37.300
[Guest 2]: And it's one of those things.

03:12:37.300 --> 03:12:40.880
[Guest 2]: But what I'm saying is that to make that to the next step of, you know, 20 gold medals

03:12:40.880 --> 03:12:46.160
[Guest 2]: and 30 gold medals, I think is clearly unrealistic for the next couple of decades, next two,

03:12:46.160 --> 03:12:47.160
[Guest 2]: three decades.

03:12:47.160 --> 03:12:52.320
[Guest 2]: I think what I'd love to see for Indian sport is whoever goes there to the Olympics is at

03:12:52.320 --> 03:12:57.000
[Guest 2]: a competitive level, you know, and, you know, you're going to have guys who we think are

03:12:57.000 --> 03:12:58.640
[Guest 2]: very good, who are going to crash out.

03:12:58.640 --> 03:13:00.400
[Guest 2]: It happens all the time in sport.

03:13:00.400 --> 03:13:03.000
[Guest 2]: You're going to have guys who we think, you know, aren't that great, who are going to

03:13:03.000 --> 03:13:04.080
[Guest 2]: do it well.

03:13:04.080 --> 03:13:09.400
[Guest 2]: But that's what sport is all about, saying that, okay, we have sent now 120-odd athletes

03:13:09.400 --> 03:13:14.160
[Guest 2]: there, okay, and 50-odd para-athletes, you know, we are already starting to send numbers

03:13:14.160 --> 03:13:15.160
[Guest 2]: which are significant.

03:13:15.160 --> 03:13:21.240
[Guest 2]: I'd love to see over the next decade, maybe 250, maybe double that number.

03:13:21.240 --> 03:13:26.240
[Guest 2]: And forget about the medals, again, let's talk, as Nandan said, if we have the potential

03:13:26.240 --> 03:13:29.880
[Guest 2]: to win 25, 30 medals, I'd be really happy.

03:13:29.880 --> 03:13:32.520
[Guest 2]: You know, will that tally end up at 25, 30?

03:13:32.520 --> 03:13:33.520
[Guest 2]: Who knows?

03:13:33.520 --> 03:13:35.840
[Guest 2]: It might end up at 15, it may end up at 35.

03:13:35.840 --> 03:13:41.760
[Guest 2]: But if we even send squads like that, that have that kind of level, and I think one thing

03:13:41.760 --> 03:13:46.680
[Guest 2]: that's going to happen is a lot of guys, that pressure is going to come down.

03:13:46.680 --> 03:13:52.560
[Guest 2]: The moment, it's like South Korean archers, South Korean archers are used to winning Olympic

03:13:52.560 --> 03:13:53.560
[Guest 2]: medals.

03:13:53.560 --> 03:13:56.440
[Guest 2]: If they don't win Olympic medals, they'll come back in the next Olympics and win them.

03:13:56.440 --> 03:13:59.000
[Guest 2]: It's not life or death.

03:13:59.000 --> 03:14:03.320
[Guest 2]: Our archers, it's life and death, and especially in games like shooting, like archery, where

03:14:03.320 --> 03:14:09.560
[Guest 2]: heart rate, your pressure matters so much, that things like that are so disruptive.

03:14:09.560 --> 03:14:15.040
[Guest 2]: Whereas, where you have a more stable system, and you're used to winning over large periods

03:14:15.040 --> 03:14:16.880
[Guest 2]: of time, those things will stabilize.

03:14:16.880 --> 03:14:23.080
[Guest 2]: So that's my wish, that in those cases, we get to that, maybe double that number, and

03:14:23.080 --> 03:14:27.480
[Guest 2]: have that many athletes, 25, 30 athletes, who we think can compete for medals.

03:14:27.480 --> 03:14:32.860
[Guest 2]: The second part is, I'd love to see much more private involvement in Indian sport in terms

03:14:32.860 --> 03:14:35.080
[Guest 2]: of sustainable leagues.

03:14:35.080 --> 03:14:38.840
[Guest 2]: Okay, forget about whether they're with federations or without federations.

03:14:38.840 --> 03:14:41.920
[Guest 2]: I'd love to see leagues that last for 10 years.

03:14:41.920 --> 03:14:46.480
[Guest 2]: I'd love to see leagues, not just leagues that last for 10 years, but leagues whose

03:14:46.480 --> 03:14:50.020
[Guest 2]: team owners last for 10 years.

03:14:50.020 --> 03:14:54.360
[Guest 2]: Because if you're in a revolving chair of team owners saying that, okay, three years,

03:14:54.360 --> 03:14:57.000
[Guest 2]: somebody's come, they're there, then they realize there's no money in it.

03:14:57.000 --> 03:15:06.160
[Guest 2]: You find some other, in common North Indian parlance, you find a new guy to fool and say

03:15:06.160 --> 03:15:08.120
[Guest 2]: that, okay, next three years, you take over.

03:15:08.120 --> 03:15:11.920
[Guest 2]: I'd love to see somebody sitting in sport for 10 years saying, you know what, I've invested

03:15:11.920 --> 03:15:14.780
[Guest 2]: in sport and it's beginning to show value.

03:15:14.780 --> 03:15:18.800
[Guest 2]: So these are the two visions I have for Indian sport.

03:15:18.800 --> 03:15:22.160
[Guest 1]: I would like to expand a little bit on joy as well.

03:15:22.160 --> 03:15:27.400
[Guest 1]: But my first dream for Indian sport is seeing more teams at the Olympics.

03:15:27.400 --> 03:15:30.440
[Guest 1]: So this time we had the men's hockey team and the women's hockey team.

03:15:30.440 --> 03:15:35.960
[Guest 1]: They were the two biggest stories of the Olympics other than Neeraj Chopra and his gold medal.

03:15:35.960 --> 03:15:39.400
[Guest 1]: The reality is a lot of our other athletes are anecdotal athletes.

03:15:39.400 --> 03:15:41.640
[Guest 1]: We've figured their way out of the system.

03:15:41.640 --> 03:15:46.960
[Guest 1]: We've sent them abroad, got them individual coaches to fly in and work with them.

03:15:46.960 --> 03:15:51.600
[Guest 1]: When a team works, that is an indication of a system working.

03:15:51.600 --> 03:15:56.920
[Guest 1]: And I would love to see India participating at handball, volleyball, football, obviously

03:15:56.920 --> 03:16:01.000
[Guest 1]: for various reasons, basketball, there's three into three basketball, you don't even need

03:16:01.000 --> 03:16:08.240
[Guest 1]: a team of 15 people, you have a three by three basketball, getting more and more team sport

03:16:08.240 --> 03:16:10.120
[Guest 1]: is going to be critical.

03:16:10.120 --> 03:16:15.560
[Guest 1]: But at a larger level, I'd also like the discourse to just move away from this hypercompetitivism

03:16:15.560 --> 03:16:20.500
[Guest 1]: and just about medals, medals, medals, is just that any young person who wants to play

03:16:20.500 --> 03:16:26.440
[Guest 1]: the sport has a place to play and enjoy sport and just makes it a part of their lives.

03:16:26.440 --> 03:16:32.680
[Guest 1]: And what is quite indicative is what is the sort of water cooler conversation that happens

03:16:32.680 --> 03:16:33.680
[Guest 1]: in India.

03:16:33.680 --> 03:16:37.520
[Guest 1]: When I went to the US, I had this sort of moment where someone told me what's the difference

03:16:37.520 --> 03:16:39.440
[Guest 1]: between the US and India.

03:16:39.440 --> 03:16:42.400
[Guest 1]: In the US, a meeting starts with did you watch the football game?

03:16:42.400 --> 03:16:46.160
[Guest 1]: While in India, it starts with which IIT did you go to?

03:16:46.160 --> 03:16:49.160
[Guest 1]: So is that conversation going to change?

03:16:49.160 --> 03:16:52.520
[Guest 1]: And that's when you know, cultural shifts have occurred?

03:16:52.520 --> 03:16:57.760
[Guest 1]: Is it so embedded in society that you just talk of it as a matter of course, you don't

03:16:57.760 --> 03:17:04.920
[Guest 1]: need an Olympics to talk about sporting achievement, and sport for fun, sport for all of the other

03:17:04.920 --> 03:17:08.520
[Guest 1]: things that it's useful for sport for is building a better life.

03:17:08.520 --> 03:17:12.960
[Guest 1]: All of those become as important as our medal quest.

03:17:12.960 --> 03:17:18.280
[Amit Varma]: Well, deeply inspiring and thanks so much for, you know, sharing your time and insights

03:17:18.280 --> 03:17:19.280
[Amit Varma]: with me today.

03:17:19.280 --> 03:17:21.440
[Amit Varma]: I loved having you on the show.

03:17:21.440 --> 03:17:22.440
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

